<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Considers Partial Lifting of Ban on British Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission is
deliberating on whether or not to recommend lifting the worldwide
ban on British beef. Discussion on the issue commenced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ban was imposed 21 months ago and may be lifted on meat
from "certified" herds in Northern Ireland, where computerized
records have been kept.
</P>
<P>
England, Wales and Scotland must wait until a computer tracking
system is in force and working to European Union (EU)'s
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials said there were also signs of progress on
a British plan to allow the ban to be lifted for meat from cattle
born after August 1996.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture commissioner Franz Fischler was expected at
Tuesday's commission meeting to table a plan, under which the
commission would propose that beef from cattle between six and 30
months old could be exported so long as they were from herds free
of mad cow disease for at least eight years.
</P>
<P>
If approved, Fischler's plan will be put to veterinary experts
appointed by each of the 15 EU member states for approval. If the
EU veterinary experts agree by a qualified majority, or 70
percent, the ban could be eased immediately without being put
before the agricultural ministers of the 15 EU member states.
</P>
<P>
Without a qualified majority, the plan will have to be referred
to the next meeting of the council of agricultural ministers who
need only a simple majority of the 15 to approve it.
</P>
<P>
More than 132,000 farmers in Britain have been asked to fill in
forms recording their cattle by January 26 to ensure that the
database contains accurate information.
</P>
<P>
All the forms have to be checked before the tracking system can
be activated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
