<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most SKoreans Have Confidence in President-Elect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Most South Koreans believe the
solution to the country's current economic crisis is
President-elect Kim Dae-jung's main task and believe he will
succeed in handling the problem.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by the President-elect's power takeover team
last week showed a consensus among 1,019 citizens over 20 years of
age.
</P>
<P>
The results of the survey, released Tuesday, show that some
92.4 percent of the respondents described tackling the current
economic crisis as Kim's priority task, while 29.2 percent chose
fighting widespread corruption and 19.4 percent opted for
uprooting regional antagonism.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent of the respondents said Kim is dealing
properly with the economic problems, while less than 12 percent
said he is mishandling the situation.
</P>
<P>
Some 88 percent said they believe the President-elect will
handle the economic crisis well, and 3.7 percent doubted his
capability.
</P>
<P>
On Kim's pledge to honor the IMF bailout conditions, 65 percent
of respondents said it is an inevitable choice.
</P>
<P>
Kim, 72, who won the 15th presidential elections in December
1997, will be sworn in as the president of the Republic of
Korea. He has come into the center of South Korea's politics
against a backdrop of the nation's worst economic crisis in
decades.  
</P>
</TEXT>
