<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Strategic Reserve Grain Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The state-controlled Grain
Marketing Board of Zimbabwe today said the low deliveries of
maize to the board was a cause for concern as this affected the
strategic grain reserve stocks, standing at 541,883 tons.
</P>
<P>
The board said it received only 248,000 tons of maize in 1997
out of the expected 600,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The amount of strategic reserves would be reduced if export
commitments were met this year.
</P>
<P>
Export commitments had to be revised from 300,000 tons to
260,000 tons amid suggestions from some sectors that Zimbabwe
should not export before local requirements were met.
</P>
<P>
''The situation is a bit difficult because people were very
careful not to sell all their grain to the Grain Marketing Board
so they hung on to their maize but no one knows for sure how much
each family will suffer if rains are not good this year,'' a
government official said.
</P>
<P>
The national Grain Loan Committee is expected to meet this
week to assess the amount of food assistance required countrywide
this year following widespread reports of people needing food
aid.
</P>
<P>
The committee will also determine whether it would be
necessary to declare a national disaster warranting emergency
operations in the provision of food aid.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is one of many southern African countries facing the
threat of an El-Nino-induced drought which might endanger the
1997/98 crop.
</P>
<P>
However, above-average rains have been received since the
beginning of January and this has rekindled the hope of most
farmers that the early planted crop might recover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
