<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Government to Hold on to Policy in 1998: Jospin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 13 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin said on Tuesday that the government will hold on to its
fixed socio-economic policy in 1998 despite mounting pressure from
the unemployed and emerging differences within his left-wing
coalition.
</P>
<P>
"Change this policy which has been approved by Parliament
or disrupt the economic and budgetary balances, because a number
of social services were occupied (by protesters), it would be to
condemn all hope of success and thus the creation of jobs," said
Jospin.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, who answered questions at a meeting with
the press, referred to protests being staged by anti-unemployment
militants who demand the government raise minimum social welfare
aid and tackle the 12.4 percent unemployment rate with more
radical measures.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist government has rejected the demand, saying that
it would cost tens of billions of francs and would overwhelm the
budget designed for cutting public deficits and joining the
European single currency.
</P>
<P>
Jospin argued that all the policies on European integration,
reducing work week to 35 hours, seeking economic growth with all
means, emphasizing social protection, and creating jobs for the
youths with government fund are aimed at cutting unemployment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
