<HEADLINE> Philippine Congress Ratifies 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Congress has
finally ratified the country's 1998 budget of 540.8 billion pesos
(12.6 billion U.S. dollars), which will be soon signed into law by
President Fidel Ramos, the Philippine Presidential Press Office
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 budget was approved by both the Senate and the House
of Representatives late Monday night, the press office said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Lower House Speaker Jose de Venecia hailed the budget as a
"landmark measure" designed to meet the current challenges of a
regional currency crisis, globalization and the El Nino weather
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The approved budget gave priority to the education sector,
which was given 80.8 billion pesos (1.8 billion dollars), followed
by the Department of National Defense with 50.9 billion pesos (1.2
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Other priority sectors are the Department of Public Works and
Highways with 47.1 billion pesos (1.1 billion dollars) and the
Department of Interior and Local Government with 30 billion pesos
(700 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
An early congressional passage of the budget as called for by
Ramos will help the government cope with the lingering currency
crisis, economists said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
