<HEADLINE> Slow Start for Post-Christmas Travel Bookings in UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Severe storms in Europe and huge
discounting among rival high-street retailers have been blamed
for the slow start to post-Christmas travel bookings in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Up to December 31, the market was around 2 percent down on the
same period in 1996 but it is likely to have slipped further
behind following poor sales recently, a conference was told here
today.
</P>
<P>
Going Places managing director Peter Shanks said at the EMU For
The Travel Industry conference that sales were disappointing and
the retailer was reviewing its discount levels.
</P>
<P>
The Multiple is featuring the lowest headline discounts at 15
percent, while Lunn Poly and Thomas Cook are offering up to 25
percent off. Core discounts are 10 percent. Carlson Worldchoice is
combining a 10 percent discount with free insurance.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the conference said Airtours has suffered the most
with sales down more than 30 percent. Thomson blamed the bad
weather after reporting sales down slightly.
</P>
<P>
Sunworld, Flying Colours and First Choice are believed to be up
30 percent, 29 percent and 19 percent respectively, they added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
