<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Backs Down on Salmon Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Canada is prepared to weaken its
position on Pacific salmon quotas and is willing to resume talks
with the United States, said reports today.
</P>
<P>
The country will also work with the U.S. to establish
short-term peace in the North Pacific by setting interim fishing
quotas until a permanent agreement can be reached.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Fisheries Minister David Anderson made the
conciliatory remarks following the release of a report by two
special envoys Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report called on the two countries to adopt two-year
arrangements for commercial salmon fishing and to negotiate the
issue government to government.
</P>
<P>
Canada would begin immediate and direct talks with the U.S. to
resolve the salmon dispute, said Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd
Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
"Political will is necessary on both sides to ensure we achieve
the goals of conservation and equity enshrined in the treaty,"
Axworthy said.
</P>
<P>
So far, the two countries have failed to achieve any progress
on the salmon issues after years of talks when the 1985 Pacific
salmon treaty expired.
</P>
<P>
Canada alleged that U.S. fishermen have been stealing its
salmon fish, worth millions of dollars each year.
</P>
<P>
Last summer, angry Canadian fishermen seized a U.S. ferry boat
to protest the U.S. insincerity at resolving the salmon dispute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
