<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Asylum Seekers Drops in Germany in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The number of asylum seekers
coming to Germany dropped by 10.3 percent from the 1996 level to a
total of 104,353 in 1997, continuing a trend registered since
1992, the German Interior Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The biggest ethnic group seeking asylum in Germany last year
were Turks, numbering about 17,000, a drop of nearly 30 percent
compared with 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of asylum seekers from Iraq shot up by
nearly 30 percent last year to almost 15,000.
</P>
<P>
Among a total of 170,800 asylum seekers who had their cases
examined last year in Germany, only 4.9 percent of them were
granted the asylum status, the Interior Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Germany moved to tighten its liberal asylum law in 1993 by
deciding that asylum seekers who arrive from states listed by Bonn
as "safe" are not eligible to the asylum status in Germany and
could be turned back to their original countries.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the number of asylum seekers has dropped by about
75 percent over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Despite of the trend, the German Interior Ministry stressed
today that it would urge the European Union to put more emphasis
on common immigration controls and would ask the EU to work out a
list of required asylum policies for eastern European countries
which are seeking EU membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
