<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues Housing Development Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- China built 300 million sq.m. of
housing in urban areas last year, and 650 million sq.m. in the
countryside, the largest amount of housing construction for the
past decade, according to Minister of Construction Hou Jie.
</P>
<P>
Hou says the housing industry has helped national economic
development and become a major focus of consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
There has been rapid growth in housing development and
improvements in housing conditions from 1992 to 1997, and annual
urban housing construction is above 200 million sq.m., and the
figure for rural housing is 600 million sq.m.
</P>
<P>
As part of the housing development and reform effort, China has
introduced commercial housing, publicly-pooled housing funds,
individual home mortgages, and other measures.
</P>
<P>
The 1.6 billion sq.m. of urban and rural housing built between
1992 and 1997 solved housing problems for over six million
households, and about 25 percent of the urban households have
moved into new housing.
</P>
<P>
The country's average per-capita urban living space has grown
to nearly 9 sq.m., and the figure for rural areas is nearly 18
sq.m.
</P>
<P>
The "Adequate Housing Project" is in effect in more than 200
cities, and has added over 25 million sq.m. of housing.
</P>
<P>
The rapid development of housing cooperatives has increased
fund-raising means and benefited low- to medium-income households.
</P>
<P>
Construction departments have made a great effort to improve
infrastructure for water supplies, drainage, heating, roads,
bridges, highways, tree-planting, and environmental protection
systems and the effort has greatly helped improve the standard
of living.
</P>
<P>
Housing construction for urban areas is expected to account for
about four percent of the country's GNP between 1998 and 2000, Hou
says, and plans for the rest of the century call for nearly a
billion sq.m. of housing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
