<HEADLINE> France to Appoint State Secretary in Charge of Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The French government will
appoint a state secretary in charge of developing public projects
and improving social situation in the cities, said Minister of
Employment and Solidarity Martine Aubry today.
</P>
<P>
The announcement, made by Aubry in a statement quoted by the
daily Le Monde, followed a spate of riots and street violence in
several French cities which occurred around the New Year's eve.
</P>
<P>
It is not known who will be appointed to the post, which will
be run in close coordination with the Ministry of Employment and
Solidarity.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin announced today that
the government will present a draft law in February to the
National Assembly to protect social integration in the cities.
</P>
<P>
President Jacques Chirac also met today with mayors from 12
suburban cities to discuss measures to curb violence and promote
social development.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with the press, Jospin said that in order to
"re-weave the social ties," the government makes it a priority to
revise its policy for cities and for families.
</P>
<P>
He described the revival of city violence in France as "the
symptom of a loss of landmark born from a degradation of living
conditions" of the under-privileged population.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with the press Monday, President Chirac said
that unemployment, social exclusion and urban violence were
weakening the social cohesion of France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
