<HEADLINE> Israeli Conditions on Troop Pullback Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 13 (Xinhua) -- A Palestinian official
Tuesday rejected an Israeli Cabinet decision that conditions
Israeli troop redeployment in the West Bank on Palestinian
fulfillment of a list of obligations.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Tibi, adviser on Israeli affairs to Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat, was quoted by Israel
Radio as blasting the Israeli move as further proof that Israeli
government is doing everything to ignore the existence of signed
agreements.
</P>
<P>
In the document adopted unanimously by ministers, Israeli
Cabinet lists a number of obligations it demands the PNA fulfill
before Israel carries out the second redeployment in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
These obligations include completing revising the Palestinian
Charter calling for Israel's destruction, fighting terror and
preventing violence against Israel, restricting the number of
Palestinian police force as well as PNA activities in Jerusalem,
and extraditing Palestinian terror suspects.
</P>
<P>
Meeting former United States Secretary of State George Shultz
in his office Tuesday, Netanyahu said the cabinet decision was
not an ultimatum, rather a question of honoring the Note for
Record attached to the Hebron agreement signed last January.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said if the PNA lives up to its commitments, there is
no doubt that Israel would move forward with the troop
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Tibi insisted that the Palestinians had no plan to hold
additional deliberations on the Palestinian Charter since it has
already been revised at the last meeting of the Palestine National
Council.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Palestinian side has a list of its own
detailing the violations of signed agreements by Israeli
government, and Arafat intended to present it to U.S. President
Bill Clinton when they meet late this month in Washington.
</P>
<P>
An inter-ministerial committee was set up at Tuesday's Cabinet
meeting to monitor the PNA's fulfillment of the listed
obligations. No timetable was set in the document for the PNA's
fulfillment, but Netanyahu has said earlier that he favored a
five-month trial period to assess the PNA actions.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Cabinet will continue discussions Wednesday and
Thursday on troop redeployment and guidelines for the final-status
talks with the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has promised to determine the scope of the overdue
second troop redeployment before his departure January 19 for
talks with Clinton in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
