<HEADLINE> Many Northeastern Americans Remain Without Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- More than 500,000 residents
in the northern and northeastern United States remained without
power as a result of last week's ice-storms that also struck large
areas of Canada.
</P>
<P>
More than 400,000 people in Maine, about 16,500 homes and
businesses in New Hampshire and 6,000 residents in Vermont were
still left without electricity, an Associated Press report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an estimated 116,500 customers in northern New York
were without power and utility officials estimated that more than
275,000 people were affected. About 9,000 people have to stay in
120 emergency shelters.
</P>
<P>
Last week's storms caused floods across the South and spread
thick ice across the Northeast of the United States and eastern
Canada, leading to 19 deaths in New York, Maine, Tennessee, North
Carolina, South Carolina and Kentucky, as well as 15 deaths in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Maine governor Angus King, who said that the storm
has cost his state nearly 6.2 million U.S. dollars, asked for
federal emergency relief.
</P>
<P>
Utility workers from both local and outside states are busying
with the restoration work, but cold and snowy weather dragged
their work on the heavy damages of power lines and structures.
</P>
</TEXT>
