<HEADLINE> US Backs Afghan Mujahidins Before Soviet Invasion: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. presidential advisor
for national security affairs Zbigniew Brzezinski said in a French
weekly published today that the United States began to support the
Afghan mujahidin guerrillas before the Soviet Union invaded
Afghanistan on December 24, 1979.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the weekly Nouvel Observateur, Brzezinski
said that former U.S. President Jimmy Carter signed his first
order to the CIA on providing secret aid to anti-government
guerrillas in Afghanistan on July 3, 1979.
</P>
<P>
He said that the United States did so in order to "increase the
probability" of a Soviet intervention.
</P>
<P>
"We did not push the Russians to intervene, but we consciously
increased the probability that they do it," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also described the secret operation in aiding the Mujahidins
as "an excellent idea," because it made Russians fall into the
"trap" of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The United States officially admitted aiding the Mujahidins
from 1980. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
