<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Reports Lower-Than-Expected Federal Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Germany saw a better chance to
meet the fiscal requirements for joining the single European
currency Euro after the federal government in Bonn announced
today that its 1997 budget deficit was lower than early planned.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Theo Waigel said in a statement today that
Germany's government budget deficit at the federal level totaled
64.6 billion marks (35.5 billion US dollars) last year, lower than
the 70.9 billion marks (39 billion dollars) planned in November.
</P>
<P>
"Germany's federal budget has made its contribution to meeting
the Euro budget target," Waigel said.
</P>
<P>
However, the latest figures did not include the budget deficits
of the country's local governments, which should also be taken
into account in Euro membership consideration. The data from the
local levels are expected to be released in February.
</P>
<P>
Under the European Union Maastricht Treaty, countries wishing
to join the Euro club must bring their total 1997 budget deficit
to no more than 3 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Waigel had expected in November that Germany would run a total
budget deficit of about 110 billion marks (60.4 billion dollars),
which should exactly meet the 3-percent Euro budget target.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Tackle Turkish Provocations with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus will tackle Turkish
violations of its air space with serious and responsible
self-restraint, government spokesman Manolis Christofides said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was commenting on Monday's violations by four
Turkish aircraft on two separate occasions of Cyprus' air space
and Nicosia Flight Information Region (FIR).
</P>
<P>
A Defense Ministry spokesman said earlier that two Turkish
RF-4 fighters entered Nicosia FIR before noon Monday and flew over
Cyprus' air space 10 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
Early Monday afternoon, another two aircraft violated Nicosia
FIR and entered Cyprus' air space 40 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish violations are believed to be a response to a
Cypriot government announcement that an air base, near the
western coastal town of Paphos in the Greek Cypriot-controlled
south, will be ready for delivery later this month.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said: "We have the possibility to deal with the
Turkish provocations. Cyprus and Greece tackle this with a lot of
self-restraint, in a serious and responsible manner."
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that the joint Greco-Cypriot defense
pact sends the right message about these provocations in the best
possible manner. Cyprus and Greece signed in November 1993 a joint
defense pact, under which Greece will provide Cyprus with military
assistance in case the Mediterranean island is attacked.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that the Paphos air base will "provide
facilities for aircraft to be stationed there, as part of our
defense deal with Greece and the Treaty of Guarantee."
</P>
<P>
The 1960 treaty for the establishment of the Cyprus Republic
stipulates that Greece, Britain and Turkey have the rights to
safeguard the Republic's independence and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said the Cypriot government was making all
necessary representations to international fora about Monday's
violations of air space by Turkish warplanes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish Cypriot daily Kibris reported Monday that
the violations were part of Ankara's measures to counteract the
imminent operation of the Paphos air base.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash have
previously warned they would take countermeasures if the Paphos
air base becomes fully operational and Greek fighters are there
on a permanent basis.
</P>
<P>
They have threatened to upgrade an airport in Turkish-occupied
northern Cyprus to enable Turkish military aircraft to be
stationed there permanently.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the island following a
failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Optimism Expressed at N.Ireland Talks Over New Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's politicians
spoke of optimism today as they met at Stormont to debate a new
peace plan put forward by the British and Irish governments
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The moderate Catholic nationalist Social Democratic and Labor
Party (SDLP) gave the proposals a cautious welcome by saying the
plan was a cause for "hope." Major Protestant parties also voiced
optimism over the proposals.
</P>
<P>
The proposals are for a new Northern Ireland Assembly, an
inter-governmental council, and a North-South Ministerial Council
to oversee islandwide cooperation on economic, trade, and other
matters.
</P>
<P>
Under the new proposals, Northern Ireland would remain under
British control while a majority in the province were so desire,
and Dublin would amend its constitutional claims over the disputed
territory.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam said the ideas were not
set in stone, but "I hope it allows us to start talking."
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, the political arm of IRA guerrillas, voiced concern
about a fresh British-Irish strategy for bringing peace to
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"The... document produced by the governments yesterday is, they
have claimed, an attempt to get substantive negotiations on
board," Sinn Fein chairman Mitchel McLaughlin was quoted by local
reports as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Others, many I think, see it as a sop to the unionists and the
loyalists. Sinn Fein intends to test that, and test it very
rigorously," McLaughlin said.
</P>
<P>
Eight parties are taking part in the talks, along with British
and Irish ministers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
