<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands in UK at Risk From Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Air pollution may contribute to
the deaths up to 24,000 people with asthma and breathing
difficulties a year in urban Britain, according to a government
report released today.
</P>
<P>
Most of the victims were already suffering from severe disease
and would not have survived for more than a few weeks or months in
any event, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Committee on the Medical Effects of Air Pollution was
commissioned by Britain's Department of Health to investigate the
short-term impact of the high levels of pollution which occur in
cities, especially on calm days.
</P>
<P>
It concluded that of the three major pollutants, high levels of
sodium dioxide hastened the death of 3,500 people a year, ozone
possibly as many as 12,500 and particulates 8,100.
</P>
<P>
Ministers are under renewed pressure to cut traffic fumes after
figures showed the terrible consequences.
</P>
<P>
The figures also show between 14,000 and 24,000 hospital
admissions may be linked to poor air quality.
</P>
<P>
The report stressed that the committee had looked only at
British cities, where some 430,000 people die every year, and had
made no attempt to assess the effects of long-term exposure to the
pollutants.
</P>
<P>
"If estimates made elsewhere, particularly in the United
States, do apply in the UK, they suggest that the overall impacts
may be substantially greater than those that we have as yet been
able to quantify," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
