<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Help Achieve Israeli Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Britain will make efforts to
help achieve the implementation of the U.N. Security Council
resolution 425 requiring Israel to withdraw unconditionally from
south Lebanon, British ambassador to Lebanon said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
David Maclennam, whose country will assume the presidency of
the European Union (EU) starting from this month for a six-month
term, made the remark after a meeting with Lebanese Prime
Minister Rafik Hariri.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is good that Israel admitted the principles
stipulated in the resolution 425. "But we need to see if it can
apply it," he added.
</P>
<P>
"I think it will be very difficult. So we are going to help
promote it through our efforts designed to advance the Middle
East peace process," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Israel admitted for the first time the
resolution 425 since it was adopted by the U.N. in 1978, saying
that it will withdraw from its occupied south Lebanon provided
arrangements are agreed by Lebanon to protect its security.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has rejected the offer, saying the Israeli withdrawal
is conditional and its aim is to drive a wedge between Syrian and
Lebanese tracks in the peace talks and to spark strife inside the
country.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in
south Lebanon in 1985 to protect its northern areas from attacks
by Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the visit to Lebanon by French Foreign
Minister Hubert Vedrine two days ago, the ambassador said that
Britain's viewpoint on the Middle East peace talks is close to
that of France and the two countries will cooperate within the EU
to advance the stalled peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
