<HEADLINE> Two London Bombing Suspects Go on Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Two men who were accused of
planning the Irish Republican Army (IRA) explosion in the
Docklands area of London two years ago went on trial today.
</P>
<P>
The explosion in February 1996, which killed two people and
devastated London's Canary Wharf area, was caused by a bomb
concealed in a lorry and marked a major escalation in the IRA's
campaign of violence.
</P>
<P>
Both Patrick McKinley, 34, and James McCardle, 29, have denied
conspiring to cause an explosion.
</P>
<P>
McCardle has also denied murdering the two men who died in the
blast.
</P>
<P>
The bombing marked the end of an IRA cease-fire that had lasted
18 months.
</P>
<P>
Prosecution lawyer John Bevan told the court that, while
warnings of the explosion were received, they were inaccurate and
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
"Those warnings did not begin to give the police sufficient
time to warn and evacuate the many thousands of people at work and
leaving work in the area," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
