<HEADLINE> Arafat Arrives in Jordan for Talks with Hussein </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat arrived here Tuesday evening for
talks with King Hussein in the run-up to the coming meeting
between Arafat and U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Arafat proposed the talks with Hussein on the stalled Middle
East peace process to prepare his position when he meets Clinton
on January 22 in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will meet with Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu separately in Washington in an effort to
reactivate the peace process. His meeting with Netanyahu falls on
January 20.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is expected to brief Hussein on the outcome of last
week's mission by U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross,
according to Jordan's Minister of State for Information Affairs
Samir Mutawi.
</P>
<P>
Hussein, said to be "extremely worried and concerned" over the
lack of progress in the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations and the
apparent right-prone Netanyahu government following last week's
resignation of dovish Foreign Minister David Levy, wants to know
what Arafat will tell Clinton, local analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's visit had been arranged during a telephone
conversation between Arafat and Hussein on Saturday but was
postponed due to the stormy weather.
</P>
<P>
Many believe Clinton's meetings with Arafat and Netanyahu will
be the last chance to save the peace process, which came to a halt
after Israel began construction of a Jewish settlement in Arab
east Jerusalem last march.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want east Jerusalem, seized by Israel in 1967,
to be the capital of their future state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
