<HEADLINE> Israeli Residents Call for Withdrawal from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli residents living
along Israeli-Lebanese border Tuesday called for withdrawal of
Israeli troops from south Lebanon, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the residents' representatives met Tuesday
with Israeli Knesset (parliament) members in Jerusalem, insisting
that the confrontation in south Lebanon could be solved by the
pullout of Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that although northern Israeli residents have
been living under Hezbollah attacks from south Lebanon, the best
way to lower Israeli casualties in south Lebanon is to implement
troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The representatives, some of them have served in Israeli army
in south Lebanon, noted that a number of senior Israeli army
officials also support the withdrawal and they have plans to
maintain the security along the northern border.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai said last week that
Israel is willing to implement the U.N. Security Council
Resolution 425, which calls for Israeli troop withdrawal from
Lebanon unconditionally and the restoration of peace and security
in the region.
</P>
<P>
But he also stressed that the pullout is contingent on
Lebanese authority's obligation to fight Hezbollah in south
Lebanon and eliminate cross-border terror attacks against Israeli
residents.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer zone in
south Lebanon to protect its northern border from guerrilla
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Guerrilla groups, principally the Iranian-backed Hezbollah,
are fighting to oust Israel from the zone. And more than 200
Israeli soldiers have been killed in south Lebanon since the
establishment of the buffer area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
