<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Rise in Smoking by UK Young Men </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- There was a 6 percent rise in
smoking by British young men between 1993 and 1996 to nearly 40
percent, according to an official survey today.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 Health Survey for England published by the Department
of Health said that smoking by men aged from 16 to 34 increased
from 33 percent to 39 percent. Women smokers rose to just under 35
percent from just over 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
The survey of 16,000 adults and 4,000 children found that men
smokers in all age groups rose from 28 percent to 30 percent while
women stayed about the same at 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
Bill O'Neill of the British Medical Association said that while
the focus had been laid on young women because of the risks to
their fertility and of smoking in pregnancy, smoking by young men
had been neglected.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a Guardian/ICM poll published today found that there
is overwhelming public demand for government-endorsed smoking bans
at work and in restaurants and bars. There is even majority
support for a ban in all public places. 
</P>
</TEXT>
