<HEADLINE> US to Concert Action With Allies on Iraq: White House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The White House said today
that the United States would like to concert its action with its
allies in dealing with Iraq's decision to bar a U.N. weapons
inspection team led by an American, but would not rule out
unilateral action when needed.
</P>
<P>
"It is always better to act in concert with others when we can,
but there is never any reluctance to act alone if we must," White
House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton said Monday that he expected the U.N.
Security Council would take "strong and appropriate" action if
Iraq enforces its decision to block the weapons inspection team,
headed by American Scott Ritter, today.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced the decision Monday to prevent the Ritter-led
team from inspecting weapons of mass destruction on the ground
that he was spying for the United States and it also complained
that the composition of the team was not fairly balanced as it was
composed with nine Americans, five Britains, one Russian and one
Australian.
</P>
<P>
While exerting efforts to press its concerns over Iraq's
challenge on weapons inspections within the U.N. Security Council,
the United States is closely monitoring the situation in the Gulf
"day in and day out" in case there is any incident to be
occurring, McCurry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
