<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Exports to Eastern Europe Surge in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Germany's exports to central and
eastern Europe has surged 19 percent to more than 85 billion marks
(46.7 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997, the East Committee of German
Economy announced today.
</P>
<P>
With the latest figures, Germany also saw its exports to the
region nearly doubled within the past four years, the committee
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to the Federal Association of the German
Industry (BDI), Poland was Germany's largest market in central and
eastern Europe in 1997, with its imports of German goods surging
to a record high of nearly 20 billion marks (11 billion dollars),
up about 20 percent from the level of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Germany's exports to the Czech republic also expanded by 15
percent to 15.9 billion marks (8.7 billion dollars). Its exports
to Russia were up more than 25 percent to 14.5 billion marks (8.0
billion dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Germany's imports from the central and
eastern European region totaled 72 billion marks (39.6 billion
dollars) in 1997, up 14 percent from 1996, the BDI said.
</P>
<P>
Separately, the German federal statistics office announced that
Germany's exports to the United States jumped 28 percent to 55.5
billion marks (30.5 billion dollars) in the first nine months last
year. Its exports to Canada crept up 54 percent to 4.8 billion
marks (2.6 billion dollars) during the same period.
</P>
<P>
About 9 percent of Germany's total exports went to North
America, the statistics office said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
