<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Music Sales Start to Slow Worldwide: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 13 (Xinhua) - The global music industry is
entering a period of slower growth over the next five years, a
study said.
</P>
<P>
After a decade in which the music market doubled in value,
retail sales of albums and singles will show real growth of 26
percent by rising from 40.2 billion US dollars last year to 50.7
billion US dollars in 2003, according to the study compiled by MBI
World Report.
</P>
<P>
Sales will continue to show robust growth in developing
markets, notably eastern Europe and Latin America. However, the
increases from these regions are unlikely to counter the
sluggishness of larger, more mature markets such as the US,
Germany, France and Japan, it said.
</P>
<P>
MBI claimed that the balance of power in the industry has
changed. It estimated that PolyGram of the Netherlands is still
the world's biggest record company with a 17 percent market share.
</P>
<P>
Buoyed by the success of Celine Dion and Oasis, Japan's Sony
moved ahead of Warner Music to take second place with 15.7 percent
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Warner, the US entertainment group, fell to third place with
14.5 percent. Best-selling artists such as Puff Daddy and Toni
Braxton propelled BMG, the German media company, into fourth
position with 14 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
