<HEADLINE> Canadian Minister to Visit Laos, Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Raymond Chan, Canada's secretary
of state for Asia-Pacific, will visit Laos and Vietnam from
January 14 to 21, the government said today.
</P>
<P>
Chan's forthcoming visit to Laos will mark the first official
visit by a Canadian minister since 1973.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day visit in Laos, Chan is expected to discuss
regional issues and topics such as landmines, Canada's bid for a
seat in the UN Security Council and human rights, according to the
government.
</P>
<P>
Starting from January 15, Chan will visit Vietnam, accompanied
by a business delegation representing nine Canadian companies.
</P>
<P>
"This trade mission is designed to promote Canadian expertise
and technology and to find ways of adapting them to the needs of
emerging markets such as Vietnam," Chan said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from promoting Canadian business, Chan will also discuss
political, trade and economic matters, as well as regional issues
and human rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
