<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daimler-Benz to Resume Delivery of A-Class Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Daimler-Benz AG
announced today that its car unit Mercedes-Benz will resume the
delivery of its ill-fated A-Class subcompact car in February after
having improved its safety standards.
</P>
<P>
The A-Class car, dubbed "Baby Benz," made its market debut last
autumn but was recalled later after several of them flipped over
on sharp turns during safety tests last October.
</P>
<P>
Mercedes-Benz has since been refitting about 10,000 A-Class
cars with an electronic balancing system as well as lowered
bodywork and wider tires.
</P>
<P>
The company said that the basic price for the improved version
of A-Class would remain unchanged at about 30,000 marks (some
16,500 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
