<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin: 1998 Should Be Year of Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 13 (Xinhua) -- This year should become the
first year of stable economic growth in Russia and its gross
domestic product (GDP) must rise by 2-4 percent, Russian President
Boris Yeltsin said today, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with Boris Nemtsov, the first deputy prime minister, in
Valdai, where the president is vacationing, Yeltsin said the
government should aim at scaling back taxes and adopting a new
tax code, cutting down nonpayments, streamlining social safety
measures and reducing lending rates to revive economic activity.
</P>
<P>
The president also noted the Cabinet should as well concentrate
on repaying debts to the defense industry and providing homes to
discharged servicemen.
</P>
<P>
He said that in total, 210,000 apartments for discharged
military servicemen will be needed over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Nemtsov also discussed the pace of repayment of
state debts to budget-financed organizations. In the president's
opinion, the release of federal budget funds for this purpose
should be under strict control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
