<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Extends Mandate of UN Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations today decided unanimously to extend the mandate
of the United Nations military observers in the Prevlaka Peninsula
for a further period of six months until July 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In its resolution, the Security Council reaffirmed once again
its commitment to the independence, sovereignty and territorial
integrity of the Republic of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
The council welcomed steps taken by the Republic of Croatia and
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia in adopting the practical
options proposed by the United Nations military observers to
reduce tension and improve safety and security in the area.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council reiterated its call upon the parties to
cease all violations of the demilitarization regime in the United
Nations designated zones, to cooperate fully with the United
Nations military observers and to ensure their safety and freedom
of movement.
</P>
<P>
The council expressed its support for the commitment by the
parties to a negotiated resolution of the disputed issue of
Prevlaka.
</P>
<P>
It urged the parties to take concrete steps towards a
negotiated resolution of the disputed issue of Prevlaka in good
faith and without delay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
