<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Relocates Refugees in Flooded Eastern Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) was forced to relocate more
than 3,500 refugees in the Dagahaley camp in eastern Kenya as
heavy rains continue to fall in the area.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued here today, UNHCR said that
thousands of refugees in the nearby Ifo camp were relocated last
November when that camp was flooded.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR is airlifting fuel daily from Kenya's port city of
Mombasa to Dadaab, which have been cut off due to flooding since
mid-November last year.
</P>
<P>
World Food Program (WFP) has undertaken an airdrop operation
with two C-130 Hercules aircrafts since December 24 for 80,000
refugees in Dagahaley and Ifo camps.
</P>
<P>
Two WFP DC-3 planes are transporting food to Hagadera camp,
which has been cut off due to flooding.
</P>
<P>
The release noted that UNHCR was conducting aerial spraying in
the region to combat the rise in malaria-carrying mosquitoes in
order to prevent mass outbreaks of deadly malaria among the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists recorded 500 percent rainfall above normal in
the region in November, 1997 and rains have continued since then,
making the 110 km road from the Provincial capital of Garissa to
Dadaab area unusable.
</P>
<P>
The refugee camps of Ifo, Dagahaley and Hagadera together
shelter some 125,000 refugees mainly from Somalia, Ethiopia,
Sudan and Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
