<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Differences Delay UN Team's Visit to S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 13 (Xinhua) -- A planned visit to Sierra Leone
by United Nations special envoy Francis Okello and a fact-finding
team has been delayed over where he should stay, a report
reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The dispute focuses on whether Okello and the team would stay
at Lungi, where the west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) is
based, or in the capital Freetown, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"The problem of where the UN special envoy to Sierra Leone
will stay and work from in Sierra Leone remains a problem that
has not yet been resolved," junta spokesman Amadou Bailoh Bah was
quoted as saying on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the junta wanted Okello based in
Freetown proper.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome his permanent transfer from Guinea to here. What
we are against is his position of coming to Sierra Leone and
setting up his office in Lungi," he said.
</P>
<P>
Okello has said earlier that it is irrelevant wherever the
team operates from.
</P>
<P>
Any place it choses would just be a liaison office, the
Ugandan-born assistant secretary-general said in Conakry, capital
of Guinea, last weekend.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the team is to monitor development in Sierra
Leone and to work closely with the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) and ECOMOG, and to be in contact with the
regime in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The team, which had been due in Freetown on Friday, has
arrived at Conakry.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that the United Nations, ECOMOG and the junta
were discussing where Okello should be based.
</P>
<P>
At present, the peace process in Sierra Leone has stalled as
the junta said it would be unrealistic to step down by April 22
as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Under the Conakry peace plan signed last October, the junta
agreed to hand over power at that date to elected president Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah ousted in the coup last May.
</P>
<P>
But the junta lately insisted on renegotiating the peace
accord with the delay in disarmament and delivery of
international aids, which were due to start in December.
</P>
<P>
The military regime also wanted Nigeria's role in ECOMOG
diminished, its army kept outside the disarmament process and the
former rebel leader released from detention in Nigeria before
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Okello also noted that the peace plan was still feasible and
the terminal date could be stuck to although the problems
remained unsolved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
