<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guinea to Recall Troops in ECOMOG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Guinea has decided to recall its
troops serving with the west African peacekeeping force known as
ECOMOG in Liberia and Sierra Leone by the end of February.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here today quoted military sources in
Conakry, capital of Guinea, as saying that the pullout from
Liberia is in line with the departure of the force under a peace
plan that ended the seven-year civil war there.
</P>
<P>
One source said that the departure from Sierra Leone was to
save money, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Guinea, which has an estimated 600 soldiers in ECOMOG, must
hold a presidential election by December, its second since the
advent of multi-party politics in 1992.
</P>
<P>
A phased withdrawal of the 11,000 strong ECOMOG force from
Liberia has already begun. Last month, the first contingent of
1,205 Nigerian soldiers returned from Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
The pullout is expected to complete next month according to
the appeal of the Liberian government.
</P>
<P>
The force is currently enforcing international sanctions in
Sierra Leone where the elected civilian government was overthrown
in a coup last May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
