<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Voices Readiness to Develop Ties with Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran Tuesday expressed its
willingness to develop ties with Russia, the Iranian official news
agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation between Iran, Russia and other countries will help
bolster stability in the region, Iran's first Vice President
Hassan Habibi said during a meeting with Russian ambassador to
Iran Knostantine Shuvalov.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that the region needs peace and security more than
any other things.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that the meeting took place when the United
States sent a special envoy to Moscow, trying to persuade Russia
to stop its nuclear cooperation with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Washington has voiced concern over Moscow's assistance of
nuclear technology to Tehran, which Russia has denied.
</P>
<P>
Shuvalov said that Russia attaches importance to the bilateral
relations, which he termed as "developing."
</P>
<P>
He said the cooperation between Russia and Iran will have
positive effect on restoring regional peace and stability, and
called on other states in the region to join the process.
</P>
<P>
Habibi attacked U.S. military presence in the Gulf, which he
said is detrimental to the regional security.
</P>
<P>
"We condemn the presence of foreign forces in the Persian
Gulf. We believe that their presence will solve no problem but
disturb the stability," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian vice president also denounced terrorism in all its
forms, saying that Iran neither is a terrorist state, nor supports
terrorism. Iran believes that terrorism, especially state
terrorism, should be brought to an end, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Russian ambassador appreciated Iran's denunciation of
terrorism and its stand on eliminating weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
He also voiced Moscow's readiness to cooperate with Tehran to
clarify the status of the Caspian Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
