<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aboriginals Account for 3 Pct of Canada's Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The aboriginal population
accounts for about 3 percent of Canada's total population,
Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
Canada had a total of 799,010 aboriginal individuals, according
to a new release from the 1996 census.
</P>
<P>
Two thirds of them were North American Indians, one quarter
were Metis and one in 20 Inuit.
</P>
<P>
But due to different census questions, the 1996 census data
cann't compared with data from the previous ones, the statistics
agency noted.
</P>
<P>
As a result, there is no way to tell what percentage changes
Canada's aboriginal population have experienced in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The statistics showed that Canada's aboriginal population is
continuing to grow more rapidly, though its fertility rate is
declining. And aboriginal's birth rate is 70 percent higher than
the general population.
</P>
<P>
The aboriginal population in 1996 was 10 years younger on
average than the general population. "Over the next two decades,
this will be reflected in large increases within the aboriginal
working-age population," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The release also indicated that one third of Canada's
aboriginal people had an aboriginal language as mother tongue. But
about 68 percent of them had English as mother tongue, while 6
percent French.
</P>
<P>
Among all provinces, Ontario had more North American Indians.
Alberta had the largest Metis population, while the Northwest
Territories had the largest Inuit population.
</P>
<P>
About three of every 10 aboriginal people lived on rural
reserves. Half of them lived in urban areas and the rest in
isolated northern communities, the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
