<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana Preparing to Capture Disputed Islands: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Botswana is preparing to
capture two more islands in southeastern Caprivi for the erection
of military bases, according to reports from Windhoek, Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Johan Mabuku, Namibia's regional councillor for the Caprivi
region, has confirmed this latest development surrounding the
disputed islands, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted Namibian newspapers and radio's reports as saying
that negotiations between delegates of Namibia and Botswana had
reached deadlock.
</P>
<P>
A world court decision on the status and ownership of Kasikili
Island, called Sedudu in Botswana, is being awaited.
</P>
<P>
But even before this problem was sorted out, ownership of two
more islands has become a bone of contention between Namibia and
Botswana. These are Situngu and Luyondo islands situated in the
Linyanti and Chobe rivers on the Namibian side of the border.
</P>
<P>
A few weeks ago an agreement was reached between the Botswana
district commissioner and the governor of the Caprivi region,
allowing Namibian farmers on the islands to continue ploughing
their lands unhindered until the dispute was resolved.
</P>
<P>
Mabuku, however, said that even as the meeting dispersed,
Botswana officials continued with claims that Situngu Island in
southeastern Caprivi was theirs.
</P>
<P>
Botswana reportedly wants to establish a military base on the
island to prevent Namibians from farming the land, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
