<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Denounces Terrorism in Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today strongly condemned terrorism in Algeria on the heels
of the bloodiest carnage in Algeria's six years of violence.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt stands against crimes that intimidate innocent civilians
in Algeria and any other society," Moussa told reporters, adding
that efforts should be taken to halt the brutal slaughter.
</P>
<P>
He said that Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel Meguid
had dispatched a special envoy to Algeria to convey a message that
all the Arabs are against terrorism and crime against innocent
civilians.
</P>
<P>
The message, sent to Algerian President Liamine Zeroul today,
stressed the League's support to the Algerian people and
government against terrorist groups that killed some 1,000 people
over the past 12 days.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo-based League also rejected "attempts to interfere in
the internal Algerian affairs for whatever reasons and
justifications."
</P>
<P>
Terrorists killed 103 people and wounded 70 in a village south
of Algiers overnight, in the worst carnage announced by the
authorities in six years of conflict.
</P>
<P>
More than 65,000 people, including members of security forces
and terrorists, have been killed since early 1992 after the
authorities scrapped a general election when an Islamic party was
poised to win. 
</P>
</TEXT>
