<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Suspected Assassins of Iraqi Diplomat Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 13 (Xinhua) - A senior Jordanian official said
here Tuesday that all the suspects in the January 3 assassination
attempt on an Iraqi diplomat in Amman have been arrested.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Information Affairs Samir Mutawi told the
press after a regular cabinet meeting that the suspects are
holding Iraqi passports and belong to the same family.
</P>
<P>
But he did not give the total number of the new arrests. Local
informed sources, however, put the number at five.
</P>
<P>
On Monday he told reporters that six people had been arrested
in connection with the murder attempt and the police were tracing
down the others.
</P>
<P>
The suspects attacked Rahim Taher, commercial councillor at the
Iraqi Embassy here, not for political reasons, but for family and
financial disputes, according to Mutawi.
</P>
<P>
One of the suspects had confessed to the police that he fired a
shot at Taher when the diplomat was starting his car before his
residence. The bullet missed the diplomat and his son, but hit his
car.
</P>
<P>
Another suspect said he was driving the car carrying the gunman
in the shooting, and the others said they were involved in tracing
Taher and finally locating his residence.
</P>
<P>
After the incident, Taher laid the blames on "either the Iraqi
opposition or Israel or the United States." Iraqi Ambassador to
Jordan Nouri Al Weiss said the attempt was carried out "by some
elements who do not want to see any rapprochement in relations
between Jordan and Iraq taking place."
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two neighbors soured after Iraq executed
four Jordanians convicted of smuggling car parts worth about 850
U.S. dollars on December 8, 1997. Jordan recalled its charge
d'affaires from Baghdad and expelled seven Iraqi diplomats.
</P>
<P>
However, ties improved somewhat in late December when Iraq
agreed to renew a contract to sell oil to Jordan at below-market
prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
