<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Pledges Support for Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan Tuesday
told visiting Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat that Jordan will do its best to support the
Palestinians in their pursuit of peace.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Arafat at the Royal Court, Hussein said
that Jordan will support the Palestinians to realize their
national rights and reject Israel's unilateral actions that can
undermine the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Hussein urged Israel to abide by the previous agreements it
signed with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Arafat said that he briefed the king on the
latest developments of the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks, last
week's regional mission by U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis
Ross and his upcoming meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton
in Washington later this month.
</P>
<P>
Arafat told reporters after the meeting that he asked Hussein
to persuade the U.S. administration to support the demands of the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said that his meeting with Clinton may be the last
chance for the Israeli-Palestinian peace process, adding that "I
hope Mr. Clinton can persuade Mr. Netanyahu to respect the accords
signed with the Palestinians."
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived here Tuesday evening. The visit has been
arranged on Saturday during a telephone conversation between
Arafat and Hussein, but was postponed due to stormy weather.
</P>
</TEXT>
