<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The Following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The Clinton administration once again marshaled its
international allies on Tuesday to present a unified front against
iraq as Baghdad carried out its threat to block a U.S.-led weapons
inspection team and reignited a crisis.
</P>
<P>
-- White House Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles announced that
he planned to stay in his job for another year, thus spoiling
the year-long guessing of a replacement for him.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's cabinet decided that there would be no further
troop withdrawals from the West bank unless the Palestinians
satisfied a series of conditions. Few expected Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat to accept.
</P>
<P>
-- President Bill Clinton's initiative on race, after
struggling for months to overcome poor planning, an uncertain
mandate and wriness from some White House aides toward what they
saw as a politically risky undertaking, has turned a corner.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Indonesia's financial turmoil will pose the biggest threat
to lenders from South Korea and Japan, who must now add
Indonesia to the list of problems they already face in their
home markets.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. inflation all but evaporated in 1997. After climbing
only 0.1 percent, the consumer price index for the year climbed
just 1.7 percent -- half the 3.3 percent increase in 1996.
</P>
