<HEADLINE> U.S.-Baltic Charter to Be Signed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, January 14 (Xinhua)--Presidents of Estonia, Latvia
and Lithuania will join U.S. President Bill Clinton on Friday in
signing the U.S.-Baltic Charter in Washington, D.C., the press
here reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-Baltic charter has been described as a "framework" for
U.S. support for Baltic integration in Western institutions,
such as the EU and NATO.
</P>
<P>
The charter will not, however, give the Baltic states security
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, leaders in the region are also strengthening
the economic and political cooperation among themselves.
</P>
<P>
Early next week, the Baltic Sea Business Summit will be held in
Stockholm. The most prominent business leaders in the Baltic Sea
countries will take part in the summit.
</P>
<P>
On January 22-23, a summit of government leaders from the 11
countries surrounding the Baltic will be held in Riga, capital of
Latvia, under the auspices of the Council of the Baltic Sea
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
