<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Urged to Pressure Israel Committed to Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) Wednesday urged the United States to
pressure Israel into carrying out the signed peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference after their talks, Jordanian Prime
Minister Abdul Salam Majali and PNA President Yasser Arafat warned
that If Israel fails to fulfill its commitments, the Middle East
will be in danger of violence and instability.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said he would ask U.S. President Bill clinton during
their scheduled meeting in Washington, which he said is "the last
chance" to save the peace process, to persuade the Israeli
government to abide by all the peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
Arafat added that Clinton was expected to find a solution to
the current deadlock of the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks after
his meetings with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on
January 20 and with the Palestinian leader on January 22
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Arafat expressed hope that Clinton will convince Netanyahu to
stop unilateral actions, including expanding Jewish settlements in
East Jerusalem and carrying out troop pullback in the West Bank in
one phase rather than three phases.
</P>
<P>
Israel's unilateral actions have paralyzed the peace process,
the region is in danger and the U.S. has to do something now, said
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
He cautioned if the peace process fails, all possibilities,
including renewed chaos, may turn into reality in the region, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Prime Minister Majali also called on the U.S. to work
seriously to save the peace process.
</P>
<P>
If the U.S. does not make efforts to revitalize the peace
process, which he said is in real danger in these days, the region
may witness a comeback of violence, he said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Amman Tuesday evening on a two-day visit and
left here this morning after having consultations with Jordanian
King Hussein and Crown Prince Hassan.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian leaders have expressed their support to the
Palestinian struggle for restoring their national rights, but also
stated that any final solution of the Palestinian issue must take
into consideration the kingdom's national interest. Jordan ruled
from 1950 to 1967 the West Bank and Arab East Jerusalem,
territories on which the Palestinians are struggling to establish
their independent state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
