<HEADLINE> UN Monitoring Team in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 14 (Xinhua) -- A six-man U.N. technical
Survey team arrived here today to study possibilities for the
deployment of U.N. military observers under the Conakry Peace
plan signed in October last year.
</P>
<P>
The team is led by the U.N. Secretary General Special
representative, Frank Kello and includes military and logistics
personnel.
</P>
<P>
They will hold discussions with junta officials including
military ruler Lt. Colonel Jehnny Paul Koroma on a program to
start the deployment of U.N. Observers throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Although the peace plan is far behind schedule, U.N. sources
here said it could be speeded up so as not to affect the April 22
deadline for the return of power to civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
It is not known how long the team will stay in Sierra Leone
but U.N. officials said the duration of their stay in the region
is 10 days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
