<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Condemns Violence in Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government today condemned violence in Burundi and welcomed a
decision of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) to urgently
dispatch a mission to that country.
</P>
<P>
"The South African government wishes to voice its serious
concern regarding the security situation and lack of stability in
Burundi and is deeply shocked by the latest massacre of over 100
people including women and children near Bujumbura," the Foreign
Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The massacre brought the number of persons reportedly killed
in armed clashes in the country to over 300 since the New Year,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"In light of this serious situation in Burundi, the South
African government welcomes the decision by the OAU to urgently
dispatch a high-level mission to that county."
</P>
<P>
The mission, composed of representatives of three member
states of the OAU mechanism for conflict prevention, management
and resolution, would be led by an ambassador of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
In addition to visiting Burundi, the mission would also visit
Uganda and Tanzania in order to consult with the respective
leaders and to emphasize the need for the Arusha peace process to
resume its activities aimed at bringing about a just and peaceful
solution in Burundi, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
An international conference was held in Arusha, Tanzania last
year to discuss ways of ending conflict in the Great Lakes
region.
</P>
<P>
"The South African government wishes to express its strong
support for both the OAU mission and the regional Arusha peace
process, which is led by Mwalimu Nyerere (former president of
Tanzania).
</P>
<P>
South Africa, through its special envoy on the Burundian
issue, ambassador Welile Nhlapo, will continue to play an active
role in international efforts aimed at bringing about national
reconciliation and lasting peace in Burundi," the Foreign
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
In a separate statement, South Africa also condemned the
killing of nine Roman Catholic nuns in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Pretoria accused the Hutu rebels of sabotaging peace and
stability in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The Rwandan government, through its activities has clearly
demonstrated its commitment to peace and reconciliation. However,
the very forces who were responsible for the genocide in Rwanda
in 1994 are now intensifying their terrorist campaign."
</P>
<P>
"It is vital that the international community takes urgent
action to support the Rwandan government and isolate the
extremists," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The two statements were released one week ahead of an
international conference on conflict prevention in Africa to be
held in Arusha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Calls for International Intervention in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The French Minister of Economy
and Finance Dominique Strauss-Kahn said Wednesday that
international intervention is needed to help Asian countries
control the on-going financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The markets cannot regulate the evolution alone," said
Strauss-Kahn during a meeting with the press.
</P>
<P>
He suggested the international community intervene occasionally
to see that things are being corrected in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"There is no perfect market. We need to intervene periodically
to make sure things are correct," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the financial situation in South Korea is almost
under control, although it is difficult to predict to which degree
"other elements in the Asian puzzle are susceptible to capsizing."
</P>
<P>
He said the French economy will be hurt by the Asian crisis,
but not greatly.
</P>
<P>
"One cannot fear a colossal effect on (French) exports, but one
cannot pretend to think that there will not be a considerable
effect," he said.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth in France could exceed three percent this year
if there had not been a crisis in Asia, he said. And if "other
major explosions" take place in Asia, the whole world will have to
review the perspectives of its growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
