<HEADLINE> Ramos Optimistic About Peace Accord with Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
Wednesday expressed optimism that the government and leftist
rebels will sign a peace agreement before he steps down from
office on June 30, this year.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remarks after meeting with Luis
Jalandoni, chief negotiator of the National Democratic Front (NDF)
who made a courtesy call at the Presidential Palace Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Jalandoni arrived in Manila Tuesday to confer with local NDF
members in the country on the on-going peace talks with the
government in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Jalandoni said he and Ramos discussed the agreement on human
rights and international law.
</P>
<P>
Ramos told a press conference that he was optimistic that a
peace accord will be signed soon "since we have also hurdled the
major obstacle which is the aspect on human rights and
humanitarian law" during the two panels' discussion in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The government and the NDF have made progress on issues of
human rights and international law during their on-going peace
talks, but some disagreements still remain.
</P>
<P>
Jalandoni said that while the peace talk is going on, the New
People's Army, the military wing of the NDF, will increase its
tactical military operations against the Armed Forces of the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The NDF, the political wing of the Communist Party of the
Philippines, has been engaging in peace talks with the government
sporadically since 1992 in the Netherlands, where most rebel
leaders live.
</P>
<P>
The NDF has fought against the government for more than three
decades and still has a presence in many hinterland areas in the
country, including some rural villages around metropolitan Manila.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
