<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Call for More Science Magazines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Publishers in China are being
asked to provide more popular science magazines to improve science
and technology education.
</P>
<P>
A random survey by the Chinese Institute of Popular Science
(CIPS) of 4,311 periodicals from all over China has shown that
two-thirds of them deal with science, but only 20 percent are
popular science magazines. This is far from enough to meet the
demand of workers, farmers, and youngsters without a higher
education but who make up a large portion of the total population,
according to Yuan Zhengguang, head of CIPS.
</P>
<P>
Popular science magazines should account for 40 percent of
periodicals to maintain a balance between supply and demand, he
explains, and suggests that the government push for as many as
five popular science magazines like the American's "Science."
</P>
<P>
This will attract more Chinese to science magazines, he
concludes, adding that popular science periodicals are an
important channel of scientific information and should play a more
active role in increasing people's understanding of science and
education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea to Cut Back on Overseas Diplomatic Missions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 14 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's Foreign Ministry
will shut down 15 of its 145 overseas diplomatic missions as part
of a cost-saving effort to overcome the nation's current financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The ministry, which has been under pressure to streamline
its overseas missions, will report its plan to President-elect Kim
Dae-jung's takeover team, a ministry spokesman said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Embassies that are most likely to be closed are those in
Africa, South America and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The consulates-general in Miami, United States, Berlin,
Germany, Kobe, Japan, Karachi, Pakistan, Jeddah and Saudi Arabia
will also be closed.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the country's Defense Ministry announced
its decision to close its military attache offices in Venezuela,
Greece, Austria, Myanmar and Morocco. The move came amid a shortage
of foreign currency caused by the financial crisis gripping the
nations since late 1997.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, South Korea has closed eight diplomatic missions
but set up 14 missions, mostly in Eastern European countries and
the former Soviet republics.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's overseas diplomatic network is made up of 100
embassies, 38 consulates and seven missions as of last March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
