<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Who Survived Earlier Earthquake Now Helping Recent Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The northern Chinese city of
Tangshan, where more than 240,000 people died as a result of a
devastating earthquake on July 28, 1976, is now helping the
victims of another earthquake in the same province, Hebei.
</P>
<P>
Shangyi and Zhangbei counties were hit by a magnitude 6.2
earthquake on January 10, leaving 49 dead, over 2,000 injured, and
over 150,000 houses damaged. Shortly afterwards, the local
government of Tangshan began to ask people and institutions to
make relief donations.
</P>
<P>
The city has so far sent more than a million yuan worth of
relief, including 110,000 items of cotton-padded clothing and
quilts and more than 50 tons of food.
</P>
<P>
Tangshan's New District, which was built on the ruins of the
1976 quake, has donated hundreds of tents, two tons of rice, two
tons of flour, 1,000 items of down clothing, and a truck-load of
medicines.
</P>
<P>
Liu Li, a local businessman who was orphaned by the Tangshan
quake, has become the largest individual donor, providing over
500,000 yuan worth of cotton-padded quilts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
