<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EEB Disappointed With UK Presidency Work Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Environmental
Bureau (EEB) Wednesday expressed its disappointment with Britain's
European Union (EU) presidency work program for the environment.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said it was disappointed that the British
government takes as its starting point the union's minimal
objective of an 8-percent reduction of greenhouse gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
It said the more radical target, a 15-percent reduction EU
proposed at the beginning of last month's Kyoto climate change
conference, should be maintained.
</P>
<P>
The EEB also said it expected to find in the British work
program an initiative for ecological taxation and public transport.
</P>
<P>
The British presidency program was criticized for the absence
of a draft document on strategic environmental impact assessment
which the EEB takes as a test for the British government's
credibility.
</P>
<P>
"We also see it as essential that environmental considerations
are at the heart of the discussions from the outset on the reform
of the common agricultural and structural funds policies," said
EEB Secretary General John Hontelez.
</P>
<P>
The bureau, however, reacted favorably toward the British
government's plans during its six-month presidency of the EU
council of ministers to work toward a better integration of the
environment into other community policies.
</P>
<P>
The EEB also suggested focusing on environment-related issues
such as the follow-up to the Kyoto conference on climate change,
the environmental aspects of EU enlargement to central and eastern
Europe, a strategy for biodiversity, sustainable transport and
further emission reductions to curb air pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
