<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Keeps Fireworks Ban For Spring Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital won't lift
its ban on fireworks during this year's Spring Festival, the
Chinese lunar new year, the municipal government announced today.
</P>
<P>
There have been rumors in Beijing that the government would
loosen its controls on fireworks, which have been in effect since
1993, for the holiday, which falls on January 28 this year.
</P>
<P>
Ji Shijian, a municipal government engineer, said today that
the rumors are absolutely groundless, and that there will be no
changes this year. He said a survey of 80,000 Beijing residents
prior to the ban, found that 86 percent approved of it.
</P>
<P>
The number of people injured by fireworks during the
five-to-seven-day holidays, fell from over 540 in 1993 to 86 in
1997, and the number of fire alarms went from 238 to 166. The
amount of noise at midnight of New Year's Eve has also gone down
sharply to 54.2 decibels from 92.
</P>
<P>
But, the municipal government will designate a number of sites
in suburban areas for fireworks and will organize fireworks
displays in some places.
</P>
<P>
Fireworks have been an indispensable part of Chinese
celebrations for thousands of years, and are believed by some to
be able to drive away demons, but they have been banned in most
large and medium-sized cities.
</P>
<P>
Anyone who sets off fireworks in Beijing can be fined up to 500
yuan (about 60 US dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
