<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Takes Measures to Maintain World Shipping Center Status (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the session, Ip also gave specific data to indicate that
Hong Kong still maintains the status as an international shipping
center.
</P>
<P>
He said that apart from being the busiest container port in the
world for six successive years, Hong Kong also sees a large number
of ocean-going and river trade vessels entering and leaving every
year with the number of voyages totaling 500,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
The shipowners and shipping companies of Hong Kong have in
their possession or control ocean-going vessels (including those
registered overseas) with dead weight tons (DWT) up to 55 million
tons, accounting for eight percent of the total tonnage in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,000 shipping and related companies operate in Hong Kong,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, "our independent shipping register, though having a
short history of seven years, has already gained recognition from
the shipping industry as being one of the best internationally and
has a total fleet of 488 vessels at present".
</P>
<P>
On Hong Kong's superiority in comparison with the shipping
centers in other countries and regions, Ip said the most important
advantage of Hong Kong is that "we have many experienced
shipowners who control a high international fleet based in Hong
Kong."
</P>
<P>
They have not only made significant contributions to the
development of Hong Kong as an international shipping center, but
also provided favorable conditions for future development.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said being an international shipping center, Hong
Kong has a simple tax regime with low tax rates and provides
excellent services in financing, insurance, communication,
accounting, legal and other related fields.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
