<HEADLINE> China Preparing AIDS Information Booklet For Young People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese health workers plan to
provide a booklet with information on sex and the acquired immune
deficiency syndrome (AIDS) as part of an education campaign.
</P>
<P>
The book will be available in June and tried out by some
middle school teachers in September, according to Sun Jiangping,
deputy director of Beijing Medical University's Children's Health
Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
The institute, which will cooperate with the State Education
Commission on the book, does not believe that they are ready to
provide these books directly to children, and that teachers need
to be trained because the AIDS situation in China is critical.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health announced last week that 8,303 HIV cases
had been detected by the end of October, ten percent of them in
people younger than 18. And, because of drug abuse and
prostitution, it is estimated that the real number of cases in
China is between 150,000 and 200,000, and that is expected to grow.
</P>
<P>
A major part of prevention is getting people to avoid risky
behavior, Sun said, emphasizing that schools should play an active
role in this.
</P>
<P>
Education authorities have asked middle schools to provide
information about sexually transmitted, but there is no national
textbook, Sun says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Economy Improved despite Difficult conditions: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Despite a shortfall against
revenue target and slow industrial growth, the economy responded
in a positive manner, recording an improvement of 1.6 billion U.S.
dollars in external balance in the first half of the current
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here on Wednesday, Finance
Minister Sartaj Aziz said that during the first six months,
government bank borrowing amounted to 26 billion rupees (590
million dollars) against the target of 48 billion rupees (1.1
billion dollars) while it was at 68 billion rupees (1.55 billion
dollars) in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Giving details of the positive features in the first half
fiscal year, the Finance Minister said, the External Current
Account Deficit recorded a net improvement of 1.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
This included an improvement of 600 million dollars in the
trade deficit, increase in remittances by 300 million dollars and
a raise of 550 million dollars in the Foreign Currency Accounts
(FCA).
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit in the first six months of 1997-98 fiscal
year was 1.1 billion dollars compared with 1.7 billion dollars
over the same period last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange reserves has increased from 722 million
dollars in November 1996 to 1.2 billion dollars in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Minister claimed that the government has been successful
in curbing the inflation rate which had been running at a double
digit rate of 11 to 13 percent in the past four years while it has
slowed down to an annualized rate of 8.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Minister said, despite difficult situations both on the
internal and external sides, the growth prospective remained
positive.
</P>
<P>
He believed that Pakistan will achieve the growth target of
five to 5.5 percent required by the International Monetary Fund
though "we may not be able to achieve the set target of 6%
growth."
</P>
<P>
Sartaj Aziz said the agriculture sector is expected to achieve
the target growth rate of five percent in the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
However, cotton production will be reduced by one million bales
and less than the last year's 9.4 million bales due to the
unprecedented rains in October 1997, said the Minister.
</P>
<P>
The higher support price coupled with other incentives are
expected to push the production of wheat to a record level of 19
million tons, compared to 16.65 million tons last year.
</P>
<P>
While the growth rates are negative in a number of industries,
the growth rates have turned positive in a number of important
industries, he added.
</P>
<P>
The banking reforms, Aziz said, made good progress in terms of
reducing administrative expenditure, recovery of stuck-up loans
and improving efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The availability of credit to the private sector was ahead of
the target of 54 billion rupees (1.2 billion dollars) for the
first six months of the current fiscal year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Karachi Stock Exchange 100-index, which was 1486 on November
11, 1996, and improved to a record 2056 on October 21, 1997. "It
has, however, received setback during the current month due to the
upheaval in regional markets. This is a temporary phenomena," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Regarding lessons from the financial crisis of the countries of
South East Asian region, Sartaj Aziz said, the economic
fundamentals of these countries were still good and it was
primarily the problems in the banking sector which dragged them
into the present crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Minister, therefore, observed that if the banking
reforms remained healthy and corporate sector show positive signs,
"You can avoid the risk."
</P>
<P>
The Finance Minister termed the debt as the major problem, but
said there was some relief for the government as far as domestic
debt is concerned.
</P>
<P>
The Minister said, the total foreign debt now stands at 30
billion dollars and reduction of three to five billion would
substantially ease the pressure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
