<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steps Taken to Prevent Cholera's Outbreak in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Minister of Health
Bincent Biruta today announced a package of hygienic measures
aimed at countering the outbreak of cholera that is gripping
Rwanda's neighbors, the Rwanda News Agency (RNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
These measures include the maintenance of hygienic standards
in households, hotels and restaurant, and the banning of the
selling of non-properly packed food items.
</P>
<P>
Biruta said the country faces a serious threat of cholera
epidemic since it has already created havoc in neighboring
Tanzania, Uganda, and the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
"Since we have similar food habits, same manners, the same
hygienic problems, it is fear that cholera might break out here
too," Biruta told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Biruta urged Rwandans to respect instructions given, otherwise
the country might face the same tragedy as its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Recent reports show that in Tanzania for instance, over 8,700
cases with 500 deaths have been registered since October 1997,
while in Uganda 1,400 cases have been depicted in Kampala, and
2,600 others in other regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
The reports of cholera outbreak in Kisangani in neighboring
Democratic Congo has increased fears that Rwanda will not be
spared.
</P>
<P>
So far, only a few cases of cholera have been registered in
some neighborhoods of the Rwandan capital Kigali.
</P>
<P>
"Two people have so far died here," Biruea said, explaining
that a crisis committee regrouping the government's officials and
different aid agencies has been established to monitor the
situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
