<HEADLINE> US Ambassador to Cairo Urges Confidence in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 14 (Xinhua) -- New U.S. Ambassador to Egypt
Daniel Kurtzer Wednesday urged more confidence in the future of
the Mideast peace process despite the current difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Kurtzer made the appeal at his first press conference since
arriving here ten days ago to replace his predecessor Edward
Walker who has been appointed U.S. ambassador to Israel.
</P>
<P>
"It is quite important that parties involved in the Mideast
peace process remain confident that the current obstacles can be
overcome and (the peace process) make progress," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that it is especially important to restart peace
process on the Syrian and Lebanese tracks as quickly as possible
so that a more comprehensive peace process can move forward.
</P>
<P>
The veteran diplomat also called for the adoption of an
attitude to "look forward as well as look back" when passing
judgement on the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We have to put in context where we are now (by examining) how
far we have come," Kurtzer said, mentioning the situation that
things were less in shape than nowadays when the peace process was
first started several years ago.
</P>
<P>
He characterized as "of great importance" the meetings
U.S. President Bill Clinton to hold with Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority President
Yasser Arafat later this month in Washington.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. would offer proposals on having talks between
the Palestinians and Israelis that focus on accelerating the final
status talks, a time-out on the Israeli settlement activities on
the ground, implementation of Israel's further troop redeployment
and ensuring security for all the people in the region.
</P>
<P>
"But there are still some difficult decisions required from the
two sides," said the U.S. ambassador, expressing hope that talks
on all the four issues could be moved ahead instead of activating
just one side and one part.
</P>
<P>
His words came just a day after Israel decided not to carry out
a troop pullback in the West Bank until the PLO meets commitments
made a year ago in a U.S.-brokered document, primarily to combat
terrorism and revise the Palestinian National Charter that calls
for the destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Denying any deterioration in ties between Cairo and Washington,
Kurtzer vowed to strengthen the strategic partnership and
alliance. Kurtzer, a Jew, has been in his diplomatic career for
21 years, including two years' service in the U.S. Embassy in
Cairo since 1979 and five years' service at Embassy in Israel
since 1982.
</P>
<P>
Back to Washington, he was appointed Deputy Assistant Secretary
for Near Eastern Affairs in 1989, with responsibility for the
Mideast peace process and U.S. relations with Israel, Egypt,
Jordan, Syria, Lebanon and the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
