<HEADLINE> S.Korea Makes Efforts to Solve Layoff Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 14 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Young-sam urged his cabinet Wednesday to pass a bill that would
implement mass layoffs in order to meet stringent conditions tied
to an international Monetary Fund (IMF) rescue loan of 57 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bill will be submitted to an extraordinary session of the
National Assembly (parliament) next Thursday. Mass layoffs are
expected to start within the ailing financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from labour unions, business and politics will also
meet on the same day to discuss the issue of forthcoming
large-scale unemployment.
</P>
<P>
President-elect Kim Dae-jung, who is to be sworn in as
president in February, voiced optimism that the issue will soon be
solved. His power takeover team and labour leaders are edging
closer to an agreement and a comprehensive solution.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday, IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus appealed to
South Korea to legalize mass layoffs in order to restore the
nation's financial credibility, which is essential to the influx
of foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, once the 11th largest economy in the world, is
suffering from an economic crisis produced by political corruption
scandals, bankruptcies of conglomerates and bad loans by financial
institutions since late 1997. As a result, the country's per
capita income has dropped to 9,400 U.S. dollars from the previous
10,548 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the crisis will worsen this year as the country,
under an agreement with the IMF, will have to open its financial
markets completely, shut down ailing financial institutions and
restructure its economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
