<HEADLINE> Iraq Again Bans Work of American-Led UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 14 (Xinhua) -- For a second day, Iraq
Wednesday again refused to allow an U.N. arms inspection team
headed by Scott Ritter, an American, to carry out their
inspections.
</P>
<P>
Ritter Wednesday told reporters that the Iraqi government had
decided to provide no Iraqi companions for his team, and that
this refusal means that his team would be unable to carry out any
inspections.
</P>
<P>
He added that he had no other option but to delay arms
inspections in Iraq, and that he would submit a relevant report to
Richard Butler, head of the United Nations Special Commission
(UNSCOM) on dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, who is
due to visit Baghdad next Monday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the UNSCOM Baghdad Constant Surveillance and
Verification Center announced that the other UNSCOM inspection
teams carried out their missions Wednesday as usual, accompanied
by some Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Iraq decided to stop any arms inspections by the
UNSCOM team led by Ritter starting from Tuesday, announcing that
it would block the inspections of the team until the team is
recomposed through a balanced participation by permanent members
of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has accused Ritter, a former U.S. Marine captain, as a
spy, and criticized the team, with nine Americans, five Britons, a
Russian and an Australian, for not being balanced in composition.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi move is again setting the country in a collision
course with the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
Iraq ordered the expulsion of the U.S. inspectors on November
13 in its last standoff with UNSCOM. The Americans were allowed to
return, together with their colleagues who then pulled out to
protest the eviction, only after Russian mediation a week later.
</P>
</TEXT>
