<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ducks, Chickens Might Be Segregated to Prevent Avian Flu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government is
actively exploring the possibility of segregating ducks and
chickens as a way to prevent the spread of the H5N1 virus, or the
bird flu, an official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Acting Administrative Secretary Michael Suen confirmed that the
government had received the surveillance results on poultry from
Hong Kong University.
</P>
<P>
The results indicated that ducks on local farms were not
infected with the H5N1 virus, but some samples of chickens, ducks
and geese collected at markets before the year-end slaughter
exercise were positive of the virus, Suen noted.
</P>
<P>
According to scientists, infected chickens are amplifying host
and will develop disease and die. But there is little risk of
infected ducks dying of this infection since they are only
intermittent carriers.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the differences between chickens and ducks to this
virus, the Government Task Force on H5N1 has drawn a preliminary
conclusion that no killing of ducks at local farms is necessary at
this stage," Suen said.
</P>
<P>
But, to protect public health, the government is considering a
number of options to ensure that live chickens and ducks are
handled separately at all levels, he continued.
</P>
<P>
A preliminary view is that live chickens should be allowed to
reach retail outlet for slaughtering on purchase, but live ducks
should not, the official explained, adding the task force is
exploring a number of options on how to handle ducks to achieve an
effective segregation from chickens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renminbi to Remain Stable: Zhu Rongji (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji told a
national banking conference Tuesday afternoon that he is confident
the yuan, the Chinese currency, will remain stable, and that will
contribute to the stability of other Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that this year China's economy will maintain its rapid
growth, with GDP expected to grow by more than eight percent, and
price increases kept slower.
</P>
<P>
He said that although the devaluation of Southeast Asian
currencies could pose severe challenges to China's exports and
influx of foreign funds, China's exports have their own unique
advantages and competitiveness and can meet these challenges.
</P>
<P>
He said that China is politically stable, and with its strong
currency, every-improving investment environment, and lowered
import duties, China will become an Asian center of overseas
investors.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, China's foreign debt structure is
rational, with over 85 percent of the debt in medium- and long-term
loans, and a repayment and debt ratio far below the international
danger line. China's international balance of payments will
maintain its surplus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renminbi To Remain Stable: Zhu Rongji (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said that China's economy in 1997 was the best since the
country began its reforms and opening up and progress was made in
the shift from a planned economy to a socialist market
economy. It has gone from "high growth, high inflation" to "high
growth, low inflation".
</P>
<P>
The market has become a buyers' market, he said, and both grain
and foreign exchange reserves are at their highest level ever,
providing good conditions for sustained and rapid economic
development.
</P>
<P>
China has found new growth areas in its economy, which include
agriculture, water conservancy, railways, highways, technological
improvements, new and high-tech industries, and residential
housing, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also discussed the turmoil Asian countries suffered in the
second half of last year and expressed confidence that the steps
they've taken to deal with the monetary crisis will have the
expected results and Asia's will remain the most dynamic economy
in the world.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) adopted effective measures to maintain its economic and
monetary stability and has a quite rational economic structure, a
stringent monetary monitoring system, and sufficient foreign
exchange reserves to withstand monetary risks.
</P>
<P>
He said the central government supports all the measures
adopted by the SAR government to stablize its financial market,
including pegging the HK dollar to the US dollar.
</P>
<P>
He said that financial work in 1998 should be directed by Deng
Xiaoping Theory and the spirit of the 15th Party Congress. An
effort should be made to accelerate financial reforms, tighten
supervision by the central bank, and establish a modern monetary
management system.  
</P>
