<HEADLINE> U.S. Wins Two Golds at Swimming Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States walked away
with two gold medals from Wednesday's swimming competition at the
world swimming championships.
</P>
<P>
American Lia Maurer upset Pan Pacific champion Mai Nakamuba of
Japan to win the women's 100m backstroke title in a time of
1:01.16.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese finished second in 1:01.28, 0.19 seconds faster
than bronze medalist Sandra Volka of Germany.
</P>
<P>
The American team also triumphed in the women's 4x100m
freestyle relay by clocking 3:42.11. They were followed by
Germany and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Chen Yan won the women's 400m freestyle final in
4:06.72, beating second-placed Brooke Bennett of the United States
by 0.35 seconds. German Dagmar Hase was third in 4:08.82.
</P>
<P>
Russia's four-time Olympic champion Alexander Popov out-touched
Australian Michael Klim to snatch the men's 100m freestyle crown
in 48.93 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Klim got the silver medal in 49.20 and Sweden's Lars Frolander
grabbed the bronze in 49.53.
</P>
<P>
In the day's other final, Ukraine's Denis Silantiev came first to
lift the men's 200m butterfly title, clocking 1:56.61.
</P>
<P>
Frenchman Franck Esposito finished second in 56.77, with American
Tom Malchow third in 57.26. 
</P>
</TEXT>
