<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuala Lumpur Stocks Rebound for Second Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) rebounded sharply Wednesday for the
second consecutive day with relatively heavy volumes as both
foreign and local funds returned to the market.
</P>
<P>
The 100-stock Composite Index moved between a low of 530.21 in
the morning and a high of 545.35 in mid-afternoon, before ending
at 536.68 with a 32.79 point or 6.5 percent gain over Tuesday's
finish.
</P>
<P>
The Emas Index surged 6.7 points to 135.12, the Industrial
Index rose 48.92 points to 1,065.45 and the Second Board Index
jumped 8.99 points to 141.33.
</P>
<P>
Gainers pounded losers by 705 to 61, while 62 counters were
unchanged and 80 untraded.
</P>
<P>
The main board's ready turnover expanded to 335.215 million
shares worth 715.479 million ringgit (about 167 million U.S.
dollars) from 157.981 million shares valued at 368.413 million
ringgit (about 86 million U.S. dollars) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Second Board volume increased to 33 million shares worth 59.674
million ringgit (about 14 million U.S. dollars) from 14.166
million shares valued at 22.712 million ringgit (about 5.3 million
U.S. dollars) previously.
</P>
<P>
Off market deals, however, decreased to 6.701 million shares
worth 13.461 million ringgit (about 3.1 million U.S. dollars) from
7.504 million shares valued at 16.172 million ringgit (about 3.7
million U.S. dollars) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Institutional players who were absent from the market due to
the continued battering on the ringgit, returned as the ringgit
recovered. The ringgit closed firmer Wednesday to 4.2850 to the
U.S. dollar from 4.6000 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A dealer said the market was well supported by funds from the
United States and Europe, as well as local funds, as the market
has gone down about 20 percent since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Although there were still large selling orders, the momentum
was expected to continue Thursday to push the Composite Index to
test the 580 level, the dealer said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
