<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Agrees to Use Members' Currencies in Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) have agreed to increase the use of
their currencies in regional tourism transactions in a bid to
reduce dependence on the US dollar, a senior official here said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during the first ministerial meeting
of the ASEAN Tourism Forum (ATF) held recently in the Philippines,
Antara News Agency reported Wednesday quoting Minister of Tourism,
Post and Telecommunications Joop Ave as saying Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN groups Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, Thailand, the
Philippines, Brunei, Vietnam, Myanmar and Laos.
</P>
<P>
He also said the agreement was not expressed in a memorandum of
understanding, but in an understanding followed by a plan of
action.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, he said, will require an ASEAN member to accept
the currencies of other members as payment for transactions in
tourism.
</P>
<P>
He did not say when the agreement will be put into effect.
</P>
<P>
The present monetary turmoil, which has hit a number of ASEAN
countries and caused their currencies to slide against the US
dollar, has promoted the ASEAN to increase the use of their
currencies in the region to reduce their dependence on the US
dollar, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
