<HEADLINE> Beijing Mayor Offers Economic Blueprints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Beijing Mayor Jia Qinglin said
here today that the municipal government will continue to put
priority on the city's economic growth and high-tech development
in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
He made these remarks in a government work report delivered at
the First Session of the 11th Beijing Municipal People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Jia said that the city's economic development is important to
the country and its opening up to the outside world, and its
advantages lie in high-tech and related industries like electronics
information, biological engineering, new medicines, optical
machinery and new materials.
</P>
<P>
The city will explore different ways to combine science and
technology with finance, Jia said.
</P>
<P>
The mayor also said there are good prospects for service
trades, which are expected to account for around 60 percent of the
city's GDP by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
In addition to commerce, trade, and service, the city will
improve finance, insurance, transportation, telecommunications,
tourism, consulting, real estate, sports and culture.
</P>
<P>
In the industrial sector, Jia said, priority will be
placed on electronics, automobiles, and machinery, and the
metallurgical and chemical industries will be upgraded.  
</P>
</TEXT>
