<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The unemployed of France once again demonstrated in several
cities on Tuesday. Faced with the determination of the protesters,
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin firmly ordered his cabinet ministers to
maintain solidarity of the government and asked the protesters to
``be respectful of the social rules and the law.''
</P>
<P>
-- The plan by Yves-Thibault de Silguy, the European Commissioner
in charge of finance, to run in the regional election in Bretagne in
France has been strongly criticized by British and American
newspapers, which said that a European commissioner cannot have
``any other occupation'' during his mandate. The Wall Street Journal
Europe further pointed out that Silguy is ``not the only one in the
French elite who think that rules are only applied to small men.''
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- President Jacques Chirac met on Tuesday mayors from 12 cities
-- nine of them from the Paris region -- which are faced with the
problem of insecurity. Meanwhile, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
announced an innovation of his policy on cities. Among the measures
to be taken by the government are the creation of a state secretary
in charge of cities, and a plan to promote social integration in
cities which will be presented to the parliament in February.
</P>
<P>
-- Five French employers' associations Tuesday ``solumnly''
warned the Socialist government against the negative consequences
that could result from the reduction of work week time to 35 hours,
as is planned by the government for the year 2000. Apparently
irritated by the demand from the bosses, Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin replied that if the bosses stop laying off workers, he will
stop the 35 hour work week plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
