<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Leaves on Lightning Visit to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
left here Wednesday for Damascus, Syria, on a few hours' visit
during which he will meet with Syrian leaders on Middle East peace
process, the Egyptian Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The talks will deal with the recent developments of the Middle
East peace process and efforts exerted to salvage it out of its
impasse.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is accompanied by a delegation including Prime Minister
Kamal el-Ganzouri, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, and ministers of
information, economy, international cooperation and industry.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's unannounced visit came a day after Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad told visiting French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine that Syria was ready to resume peace talks with Israel
from the point where they left off with the former Israeli
government.
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad also encouraged an effective French and European role
in the region that would help achieve a just and comprehensive
peace.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli talks have been put on ice since February
1996. Syria has conditioned the resumption of talks on a full
return of the occupied Golan Heights as promised by the former
Israeli Labor government, a request the incumbent Likud government
has rejected. 
</P>
