<HEADLINE> Holding Wedding Amid Rubble of Chinese Earthquake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHANGBEI (Hebei Province), January 14 (Xinhua) -- The
earthquake that rocked a village in China's Hebei Province last
Saturday did not keep a young couple from marrying here today in
the falling snow and the debris.
</P>
<P>
The bride, An Yulian, and her boyfriend He Rubin had already
set the date for January 14, but the earthquake destroyed their
village and left them homeless.
</P>
<P>
But, when People Liberation Army (PLA) troops who were doing
rescue work there heard their story, the soldiers offered to help
by putting up a tent for them last night and gave the couple a
padded quilt, a woollen blanket, and a framed mirror as wedding
gifts.
</P>
<P>
"This is the most important day of my life and I owe all this
to the (Chinese Communist) Party, the government, and the PLA
soldiers," An said, to which her husband added, "The warmth we
have received will encourage us to rebuild our homes with our own
hands."
</P>
<P>
The magnitude 6.2 quake, that hit Zhangbei and Shangyi counties
some 220 kilometers northwest of Beijing, the Chinese capital,
left 49 people dead, more than 10,000 injured, and some 150,000
houses collapsed or walls cracked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
