<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dubai's Gold Imports Up 90 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Dubai's gold imports reached
660.3 tonnes in 1997, registering 90 percent growth from 350.5
tonnes in 1996, according to a customs report available here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The growth was the steepest annual increase recorded by the
emirate in the United Arab Emirates (UAE), one of the largest gold
markets in the world in the past 28 years, said the report by the
Dubai Customs.
</P>
<P>
Dubai imported gold from 40 countries, with Switzerland
remaining as the largest supplier which accounted for 68 percent
at 440.8 tonnes in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Other main supply countries included Britain, accounting for
21 percent at 136 tonnes and South Africa 8 percent at 54.2
tonnes.
</P>
<P>
Dubai's fourth major gold supplier was South Korea (4.7
tonnes), followed by Germany (2.69 tonnes), Australia (2.57
tonnes), Oman (1.51 tonnes), the Netherlands (1.3 tonnes) and
Kuwait (1.11 tonnes). 
</P>
</TEXT>
