<HEADLINE> Euro2000 Picks on Seeded Teams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Defending champions Germany
along with England, Italy and Spain were given a boost as they
were to be drawn into five-team instead of six-team preliminary
groups at the 2000 European Soccer Championship.
</P>
<P>
Scotland, Yugoslavia, Romania, Russia and Norway were also
seeded teams as 49 of UEFA's 51 members will be drawn into nine
groups for the 2000 championship which will be held for the first
time in history in two countries.
</P>
<P>
Belgium and the Netherlands are exempt from the draw as
co-hosts while Bosnia and Andorra will be competing for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
Only one of the five other seeds will be drawn into a five-team
group whereas the remaining four will be drawn into six-team
groups, according to the organizing committee of the 2000
championship.
</P>
<P>
Johan Cruyff of the Netherlands and Paul van Himst of Belgium
will represent the co-hosts and help make the draw that will be
held on Sunday in the Belgian city of Gent.
</P>
<P>
The nine group winners plus the best runner-up from the
round-robin preliminary tournament will join co-hosts Belgium and
the Netherlands in the grand finale.
</P>
<P>
They are to be later joined by the four teams that win the
two-legged playoffs between the eight other runners-up from the
group preliminaries.
</P>
<P>
The qualifying tournament starts in September 1998 and ends in
October 1999
</P>
<P>
Four quarter-finalists from the previous championship did not
make the seeding list. They are France, Croatia, the Czech
Republic and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
France is the most notable absentee from the seeding list.
UEFA Secretary General Gerhard Aigner said last month: "The
seedings were based on the co-efficient used for the World Cup in
the United States in 1994, Euro1996 and qualifying for
France1998. As France did not compete in the United States nor
need to qualify for the World Cup finals in France, there was no
way of seeding them." 
</P>
</TEXT>
