<HEADLINE> Annan Suggests Extending UN Observers' Tenure in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today suggested extending the tenure of the U.N.
observation mission in Angola for another three months.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, Annan asked to keep the
U.N. observation mission in Angola till the end of April and at
the same time cut down the number of its officials, military
personnel, observers and police from 2,100 to 1,200.
</P>
<P>
The decision to send the observation team on the basis of the
third UN Angola Inspection Mission, was made in late October
1997. The tenure of the team was scheduled to end by January 31,
1998.
</P>
<P>
The delays in carrying out the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol is
said to be the reason for Annan's new suggestion for extending
the stay of the UN observers in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The UN head said that there should be a mutual trust
atmosphere in Angola so that the peace process can proceed in an
enabling environment.
</P>
<P>
Annan demanded that the Angolan government and the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) make greater
efforts for earlier realization of peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he was happy that UNITA has decided to move its
headquarters from Bailundo and Andulo to Luanda and that UNITA
leader Jonas Savimbi will soon meet Angolan President Eduardo dos
Santos, noting that the summit would help consolidate national
reconciliation and democracy in the country.
</P>
<P>
He called on UNITA to continue its effort to turn itself into
an un-armed political party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
