<HEADLINE> Oil Slick Spreads in UAE Waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The oil slick resulting from
the sinking of an oil barge in the United Arab Emirates (UAE)
waters last Wednesday has spread across at least 40 kilometers of
the Gulf country's coastline.
</P>
<P>
UAE's authorities related to the clean-up task have been told
to spread booms across the entire area to stop the slick which has
polluted four of the UAE's seven emirates, the UAE's Wam news
agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Helicopters patroling in the four northern emirates of Dubai,
Sharjah, Ajman and Umm Al-Quwain are monitoring the situation and
a team of British experts has been flown to the UAE to assist in
the clean-up operations.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 4,000 tonnes of oil leaked out from the
UAE-flagged tanker after it sank fully off Ajman on January 7.
The barge which is lying on its bottom at a depth of about 20
meters has 30 tanks.
</P>
<P>
The oil spill has highlighted the need for water conservation
and the UAE government has urged residents near the polluted
areas to use desalinated water sparingly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
