<HEADLINE> Four Swimmers Tested Positive, Yuan Banned for 4 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Four Chinese swimmers have tested
positive and another Chinese swimmer Yuan Yuan has been banned for
four years for bringing a banned drug into Australia, world
swimming body FINA announced here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Women swimmers Wang Luna, Cai Huijue, Zhang Yi and men swimmer
Wang Wei have tested positive for the banned substance Triamterene
(diuretic), according to the FINA press release issued Wednesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
The samples were collected on January 8 and the analyses were
made at the IOC-sanctioned laboratory "Australian Government
Analytical Laboratories", the press release said.
</P>
<P>
The FINA Executive in their meeting held early Wednesday, has
decided to provisionally suspend the four Chinese until a hearing
can be made following the test of the B sample, said the press
release.
</P>
<P>
Chinese swimmer Yuan Yuan and her coach Zhou Zhewen, both held
responsible for bringing a banned drug into Australia, have
received lengthy suspensions from FINA.
</P>
<P>
Yuan has been suspended from competing in any national or
international competitions for four years beginning on January 8,
FINA announced in its press release on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zhou has been banned for 15 years, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's Olena Lapunova, who tested positive in November last
year, has been banned for four years, according to the FINA press
release.
</P>
<P>
The press release also said that Australian Scot Miller, who
tested positive for Cannabinoids (Marijuana) in September last
year, has been suspended for two months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
