<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New AmCham Chairman Vows to Promote HK's Competitiveness and U.S.-China Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Jeffrey Muir, new chairman of
the American Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong (AmCham), said here
Wednesday that the first of his three top objectives to accomplish
in 1998 is to promote Hong Kong's competitiveness as an
international business center.
</P>
<P>
Delivering his first address as AmCham Chairman at a special
inaugural luncheon, Muir highlighted two aspects of the
competitiveness issue in 1998 -- trimming the costs of doing
business in Hong Kong and maintaining the pegged exchange rate
between the Hong Kong dollar and the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
"Survey after survey shows that AmCham's members believe that
the cost of doing business in Hong Kong is very high," Muir said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong must respond to the pressure of trimming costs
positively or risk that international business will seek lower
cost alternatives elsewhere in Asia, Muir said.
</P>
<P>
"It will be difficult to attract companies back once they have
left," he added.
</P>
<P>
AmCham agree with the SAR government's efforts to moderate real
estate costs by expanding land supply and increasing housing, Muir
said.
</P>
<P>
Effective management of the Hong Kong dollar peg is also
critical to maintain Hong Kong's competitiveness, Muir said.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong government's use of high interest rates to stave
off speculator against Hong Kong dollar has worked thus far, but
at the cost of substantial declines in the property and stock
markets, Muir said.
</P>
<P>
However, unpegging the Hong Kong dollar would unleash a
speculative attack on the currency from both outside and inside
Hong Kong, he added.
</P>
<P>
To maintain the peg, Hong Kong will have to suffer hardship for
a period of time, but it will defeat the speculators in the end,
Muir said.
</P>
<P>
The second issue related to Hong Kong's competitiveness is the
importance of diversity, Muir said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is a very Chinese city, but it is also a very
international city that has integrated selected Western styles and
practices into people's lives.
</P>
<P>
The evolution in Hong Kong's political and social environment
has greatly enhanced Hong Kong's competitiveness as a place to
live and do business in Asia, Muir said.
</P>
<P>
Muir said that the second of his three primary objectives in
his term is to encourage progress in China's World Trade
Organization (WTO) accession talks and to persuade the United
States' government to offer permanent most favored nation trading
status (MFN) for China.
</P>
<P>
The chamber, as well as American business in general, has
devoted tremendous resources to argue that renewal of China's MFN
status is in U.S. strategic interests, Muir said.
</P>
<P>
Ending the annual debate on whether to offer China MFN status
would provide a huge boost to bilateral relations and would allow
business, the Administration, and Congress to devote their
energies to more constructive pursuits, Muir said.
</P>
<P>
AmCham will try to achieve a more important objective -- to
help China obtain its accession to the WTO, Muir said. If
achieved, it will bring a host of benefits to American companies
doing business with China.
</P>
<P>
Muir said that his last objective is to expand local
participation in the chamber.
</P>
<P>
Without abandoning the chamber's commitment to promote American
business interests, AmCham must recognize that an increasing
number of its members are non-Americans, and that making AmCham
relevant to that group is critical for the chamber's long-term
success.
</P>
<P>
"We need to demonstrate that participation in the chamber helps
its Chinese members to better understand U.S. business interests
and policies, making them more effective in their jobs," Muir
said.
</P>
<P>
Jeffrey Muir, external director of the Seagram Asia Pacific,
was elected to lead the American Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong,
the most influential American Chamber of Commerce outside the
United States, throughout 1998 at a general meeting held on
December 15, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Muir has been an active member of the American Chamber of
Commerce in Hong Kong since 1979.
</P>
<P>
He has served as vice chairman, vice president and governor as
well as chairman of the China Business Committee (1983, 1986),
Indochina Business Committee (1991) and Government Relations
Committee (1996).
</P>
<P>
Muir joined Seagram Asia Pacific in 1996 as the director of
external affairs for the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
A native New Yorker and Princeton University graduate in
Chinese Studies (1973), Muir has lived in Hong Kong since 1975.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
