<HEADLINE> Bus Fares Hike in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 14 (Xinhua) -- South Koreans here are to feel
another squeeze from the depreciation of won as the city
government planned to increase bus fares by more than 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Seoul Metropolitan Government announced Wednesday that the
fare of an ordinary bus will jump to 500 won (about 26 U.S. cents)
from 430 won, beginning from Thursday, due to the leap in
petroleum prices following won's sharp depreciation against the
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The city government said the fare of a deluxe bus is to rise to
1,000 won form 850 won while the fares for junior and senior high
school students will be 340 won and primary school students, 200
won.
</P>
<P>
At late night, the fares of luxury and airport coaches are to
grow to 1,100 won from 1,000 won.
</P>
<P>
More and more South Koreans are using the public transport
system in the wake of the ongoing financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Seoul's intra-city buses and subway served more than 70 percent
of commuters last December while the number of cab and private car
users declined sharply.
</P>
<P>
South Korea relies heavily on oil imports to meet fuel demands.
</P>
<P>
The heating fuel is also expected to rise due to increasing oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
The country's briquette production rose 38.2 percent to 217,00
tons last December from the previous month's 157,000 tons,
according to the Korea Federation of Fuel Supply Cooperatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
