<HEADLINE> 51 Taliban Killed in Plane Crash: Taliban Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 14 (Xinhua) -- A total of 51 Taliban,
including six crew members, on board a Russian-made plane were
killed when the aircraft crashed late Tuesday night in Pakistan's
Balochistan Province.
</P>
<P>
This was told by Taliban Spokesman Abdul Rehman in the southern
Afghan city of Kandhar Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Rehman said all passengers on board the ill-fated plane were
Taliban who were going from Kandhar to Herat in the northwest. The
plane crashed because of the bad weather and diminishing fuel,
said the Taliban spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The dead bodies are being transported to Kandhar, he added.
</P>
<P>
Reports appearing on the local press Wednesday said as many as
80 people, most of them Afghan nationals, died during the plane
crash.
</P>
<P>
The Plane crashed at 10:30 p.m. (local time) near Chaman, about
110 kilometers north of Quetta, provincial capital of Balochistan
due to inclement weather, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft took off from the Kandhar Airport in southern
Afghanistan for the northwest province of Herat Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
However, when it reached near destination, it could not land
due to inclement weather. The plane then returned to Kandhar, as
the weather of Kandhar was also foggy, it could not land there
either, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Later the pilot moved the plane towards Pakistan informing the
Quetta airport control about the situation and requested to allow
for emergency landing. The civil aviation authorities on an
information arranged emergency landing for the ill-fated passenger
carrier.
</P>
<P>
The plane was on its way to the Quetta airport when it crashed
in Khojak pass's hilly track because of darkness and cloudy
weather, killing all the passengers and crew.
</P>
<P>
The local authority in Chaman said Wednesday that they arranged
rescue teams immediately after getting the news and tried their
best to reach the spot. However, due to darkness and the rain,
they could not start relief operation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
