<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multinationals Help Transform China's State-owned Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, a leading industrial
base in north China, has used investment by multinationals to help
its large and medium-sized state-owned firms as an increasingly
important way of helping local economy, Vice-mayor Ye Disheng said.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin had an average of 3.38 billion US dollars worth of
overseas investment annually from 1993 to 1996, Ye said, and the
city is planning a complete overhaul of all medium-sized or large
companies in the next eight years.
</P>
<P>
The city is popular because of its good investment environment,
industrial production, labor resources, and market potential, Ye
explains.
</P>
<P>
Major multinationals like Republic of Korea's Samsung and the
LG Group, and the US's Otis Elevator and Motorola have cooperative
ventures with state-owned firms in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June of last year, 195 of these companies were
involved in 299 mechanical, automobile, electrical, chemical,
medicine, or communications project in Tianjin, at a total cost of
seven billion US dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
By drawing technologically-advanced and multinationals with
market savvy the city has developed a number of name-brand
products that do well on the international market.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the GDP has grown at more than 14 percent for
three consecutive years. The national average was 8.8 percent in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The gross industrial output and pre-tax profits of
overseas-funded firms accounted for 43.2 percent and 52 percent of
the city's total, respectively in 1996, to which multinationals
contributed 90 percent and 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
Co-operation between domestic state-owned enterprises and
multinationals has greatly improved the city's foreign trade. It
had four billion US dollars in exports in 1996, and will surpass
five billion US dollars for 1997, Ye said. Exports of
overseas-funded firms have accounted for 60 percent of the city's
total, to which multinationals occupy 96.3 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
