<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Shares Continue Rebounding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks rebounded
5.81 percent Wednesday for a second straight gain of the new year.
</P>
<P>
The local shares had rebounded on Tuesday, after a consecutive
eight-day plunge since December 31 last year.
</P>
<P>
Dealers attributed the continuous rise to the easing interbank
rates, the stabilization of regional currencies and a second
consecutive gain on Wall Street overnight.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng index gained 506.55 points to close at
9,226.55 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The day's session registered a turnover of 11.408 billion HK
dollars (1.462 billion US dollars), against the 11.038 billion HK
dollars on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index rose 598.94 points, or 2.21 percent, to
open at 8,979.95 in the morning and it gained 523.20 points, or
6.0 percent, to close at 9,243.20 at midday.
</P>
<P>
The index had jumped 598.94 points to close at 8,720.00 on
Tuesday, which stopped a freefall the previous day caused by high
interest rates and the collapse of locally-based Peregrine
Investment Holdings, once Asia's largest independent investment
bank.
</P>
<P>
The current tour of the region by IMF officials was also
thought to help restore stability on regional financial markets.
</P>
