<HEADLINE> Presidents of Celebrated Universities to Gather in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Presidents of celebrated
universities in the world are expected to gather here in May for a
forum on education in the next century.
</P>
<P>
The forum is scheduled for May 2-4 at Beijing University, one
of China's most prestigious ones.
</P>
<P>
Those who have accepted invitations include the presidents of
Stanford and Princeton universities of the United States, Oxford
and Cambridge universities of Britain, the Sorbonne
University of France, Munich University of Germany, and Tokyo
University of Japan.
</P>
<P>
The president of Harvard University even sent a delegation to
Beijing University to discuss details about the forum.
</P>
<P>
Embassies in China from some Asian countries have phoned
Professor Min Weifang, vice-president of Beijing University, to
seek invitations for leading universities in their countries.
</P>
<P>
Min, who was awarded his doctor's degree in the United States,
said: "It will be a big event for the world education. It shows that
China's educational achievements have begun to gain worldwide
recognition."
</P>
<P>
The forum plans to invite 70 university presidents, 20 from
China and 50 from the rest of the world, said Min, adding that
more presidents are applying for a seat.
</P>
<P>
Beijing University will celebrate the 100th anniversary of its
founding this year.
</P>
<P>
Presidents attending the forum will mainly exchange views on
the educational development of the mankind. Chen Jia'er, president of
Beijing University, will deliver a speech titled "the Relationship
between the universities and the society in the 21st century."
</P>
</TEXT>
