<HEADLINE> Indian Prime Minister Gujral Leaves for Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral left here Wednesday afternoon for Dhaka to
participate in Bangladesh-India-Pakistan summit to enhance
economic and trade cooperation among the three countries.
</P>
<P>
There was a need to collectively visualize emergence of a
community of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation
(SAARC), and SAARC had already set a target for itself to move to
a free trade zone in the region by the year 2001, he told
reporters before his departure.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in 1985, embraces Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The three-nation summit was first proposed by Bangladesh Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina at the SAARC summit in Male, capital of the
Maldives, in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Gujral said that the three nations would review the progress
made so far and would discuss how to work out an agenda so that
free trade zone is achieved.
</P>
<P>
Responding to questions, Gujral said that he would hold
separate talks with other two prime ministers on the sidelines of
the summit on bilateral relations.  
</P>
