<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Panel to Boost Bilingual Legal System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Officials of the Justice
Department of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
government have outlined a plan to establish a high-level
committee to oversee the implementation of a fully bilingual legal
system in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Bilingualism is the department's long-term goal and the Chinese
language will be given equal emphasis, officials of the Department
said.
</P>
<P>
The committee is to address policy issues including the role of
Chinese and English in the legal system, the speed at which
bilingualism should proceed and training of law students.
</P>
<P>
It will be composed of representatives from the Department of
Justice, Legal Aid, the Education and Manpower Bureau, the
Official Language Agency, the legal profession and three lay
members to be appointed by SAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which is to be set up soon, will be chaired by
Secretary for Justice Elsie Leung Oi-sie.
</P>
<P>
And the translation of the laws into Chinese will be a top
priority, a provisional councilor said.
</P>
<P>
But experts, who spoke before the Provisional Legislative
Council panel on Administration of Justice and Legal Services on
Tuesday, stressed that the role of a bilingual legal system is
more important than just translating laws. It should produce
original legislation in both English and Chinese, they
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
