<HEADLINE> HK Justice Body to Create Post of China Law Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Provisional
Legislative Council has approved the creation of a permanent post
for a Chinese law expert in the Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
In proposing the new post of deputy government counsel, the
department's Legal Policy Division is aimed at coping with
increasing demand for expertise in laws of China's mainland.
</P>
<P>
The Provisional Legislative Council's Administration of Justice
and Legal Services panel was told on Tuesday that the need for
advice on mainland laws has considerably increased since the
handover.
</P>
<P>
Members of the public would seek advice when they have
misunderstandings about the legal system in China's mainland, said
Stephen Law, director of administration and development at the
China Law Unit.
</P>
<P>
The number of cases involving written advice on mainland laws
went up to 200 last year, compared with just 78 in the previous
year, and they involved mainland constitutional law as well as
criminal, family and nationality laws, he said.
</P>
<P>
The new officer will be answerable to the deputy solicitor
general and responsible for training counsels in mainland laws in
the Department of Justice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
