<HEADLINE> Nigerian Export Zone Delays Taking off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Shortage of investors has
delayed the commissioning of Nigeria's first and only export
processing zone, The Guardian paper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Although more than 90 percent of the zone had been ready after
six years of construction, there were not enough foreign
investors for it to take off, Emmanuel Udugu, Minister of
Commerce and Tourism, complained.
</P>
<P>
At present, only two investors, one producing garments and the
other producing wood work, have installed their machines at the
zone.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 16 companies, both local and foreign, have received
the approval to invest at the zone, but they have not come to
start business, said Grace Ekanem, Commissioner of Commerce,
Tourism and Business Development.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister, who made an inspection to the zone last
weekend, promised that efforts to commission the project are
still going on.
</P>
<P>
The foundation stone of the project, located in southern
Nigeria's rivers state, was laid in November 1991. It had in the
past been slated for commissioning over six times but was later
canceled.
</P>
<P>
The zone was initially to be completed with 800 million Naira
(about 10 million U.S. Dollars) but by 1995, and now more than
3.4 billion Naira (43 million Dollars) had been spent.
</P>
<P>
A high-power delegation of the ministry recently visited some
Asian countries in a bid to canvass investors there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
