<HEADLINE> Trucks Roll Through Snow on Highway to Quake-hit Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 14 (Xinhua) -- With a heavy snowfall over
north China's Zhangjiakou City, earthquake-relief supplies from
nearby cities rolled along a highway resembling a black belt to
Zhangbei and Shangyi counties.
</P>
<P>
At 5 a.m. today on the Zhangbei-Zhangjiakou section of the
state 207 highway, truck lights flashed in the dark. About every
five minutes, a truck with relief goods ran through Zhangjiakou
City and headed for the quake-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
By his truck headlights driver Li Mantang, who had just
returned from the disaster scene, counted the vehicles by their
license plates: "Zhangjiakou, Baoding, Beijing ...".
</P>
<P>
Li told reporters that the trucks he recognized were from a
dozen cities in north China.
</P>
<P>
The Traffic Police's patrol cars could be seen here and there
with red lights flashing. Sometimes, the police cars stopped at
the roadside and helped drivers restart failing engines.
</P>
<P>
Lu Qingguang, director of the Traffic Police Department of
Zhangjiakou City, said that more trucks are expected to arrive at
the quake-hit areas today despite the heavy snowfall.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he noted, more than 300 policemen from his department
were on duty on the highway to the quake-stricken areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
