<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Apex Court Dismisses Petitions against Orders of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"No writ can be issued by a High Court or the Supreme Court
against itself or against each other or its Judges in exercise of
jurisdiction under Article 199 of the Constitution," the Chief
Justice said in his order.
</P>
<P>
The Quetta and Peshawar benches issued orders on November 26
and 28, 1997, respectively, suspending the appointment of former
chief justice of the Supreme Court Sajjad Ali Shah.
</P>
<P>
The Quetta bench issued an order on November 26 last year that
Sajjad Ali Shah was not the most senior judge in the Supreme Court
when he was appointed as the chief justice of the apex court in
1994. The Quetta bench order was supported by the Peshawar bench
two days later.
</P>
<P>
Chief Justice Ajmal Mian has written a 30-page judgment agreed
by all the five judges sitting on the bench.
</P>
<P>
He declared that a bench of this court cannot sit as a court of
appeal over an order or a judgment of another bench of this court.
It is a right of this court entrusted by the Constitution, the
Chief Justice added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the writ may be issued under the Constitution
subject to two exceptions, firstly where a High Court Judge or a
Supreme Court Judge acts as persona designata or as a Tribunal,
secondly, where quo warranto is prayed for and a case is made out.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
