<HEADLINE> Popov Remains King of Freestyle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian Alexander Popov remains
king of freestyle sprint as he beat Australian Michael Klim to win
the men's 100m freestyle final at the world swimming championships
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Klim and Popov, both coached by Russian Gennadi Touretski in
the Canberra Sports Institute, finished 1-2 in the men's 100m
freestyle heats. In the final, Popov showed he was the best.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old Russian, one of the most-crowned swimmers in
the world, clocked 48.93 seconds to win the event, breaking the
championship record of 48.94 seconds set by American Matt Biondi
12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Popov is the world record holder over 100m, four-time Olympic
gold medalist and European champion at both 50m and 100m.
</P>
<P>
Klim touched home in 49.20 seconds for the silver medal and
European champion Lars Frolander of Sweden got the bronze in 49.53.
</P>
<P>
Dutchman P. van Den Hoogenband finished fourth in 49.59.
</P>
</TEXT>
