<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laid-Off Workers Find New Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Shao Yueling, 47, who formerly
worked as a clothing designer, found new positions for herself and
all colleagues declared redundant by a factory in north China's
Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Shao was one of over 100 workers who lost their jobs when the
unprofitable Renqiu Clothing Factory closed in early 1993. Shao
decided to help by signing a contract to operate the factory.
</P>
<P>
Hard work, improved efficiency and teamwork revived the
factory, with the factory earning a profit of 46,000 yuan by
finishing its first order in only four weeks, a task which
normally required six weeks.
</P>
<P>
Shao was appointed as deputy director of another Renqiu garment
factory in 1996, and all workers have since returned to
work. Shao's new factory has hired 36 new employees, many of
suffer from disabilities.
</P>
<P>
The People's Congress in the south China city of Guangzhou
introduced a special reemployment fund. The fund, set up with
an allocation of 50 million yuan, has provided effective
guarantees enabling the local government to implement the
reemployment project.
</P>
<P>
The city government has also allocated 7.2 million yuan from
the fund to provide job training for 8,000 laid-off workers, with
some 60 percent of the trainees finding new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Community employment organizations have been asked to introduce
new jobs to all people currently relying on the unemployment
relief fund on a cost-free basis over the next three
months. Related individuals can also receive either free or
low-cost job training.
</P>
<P>
The series of measures introduced over the past several years
has enabled Guangzhou to maintain its reemployment rate at levels
above 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Hami Prefecture in northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region has founded six free markets in which
laid-off workers can open businesses. More than 1,000 jobless
people, or approximately one third of all unemployed people in
Hami, have opened businesses in the markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
