<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise Sharply on Hopes for Economic Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The key Nikkei index of Tokyo
stocks regained the 15,000 line Wednesday for the first time in
four trading days amid growing hopes for fresh economic steps.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
at the Tokyo Stock Exchange climbed 366.04 points, or 2.48 percent
from Tuesday's close to 15,121.98.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the First Section, gained 27.49 points, or 2.45 percent
to 1,149.11.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the First Section came to an estimated 400 million
shares, up from Tuesday's 389.95 million shares, with failed
Yamaichi Securities the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
In the early afternoon, buyers were attracted to real estate
and banking issues by news that the ruling Liberal Democratic
Party will propose a plan to revaluate corporate landholdings in
an attempt to improve banks' capital base.
</P>
<P>
Market sentiment was also buoyed by Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto's hint during Tuesday's Diet (parliament) testimony that
a single-year income tax cut may be extended to boost the economy,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,327 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
outweighed losers 780 to 311, with 180 issues unchanged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
