<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China's 1998 Economy Witnesses Fast, Stable Beginning (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Xinhua Writer Zhou Zongmin
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- China's economic locomotive,
fresh on the heels of a "soft landing" in 1997, is steaming ahead
on a fast-track robust rate of growth, with the year's GDP
expected to rise by eight percent.
</P>
<P>
The government and Chinese economists have expressed optimism
about this year's economic outlook, and fully expect the current
momentum of high growth and low inflation, the hallmark of
strength, to continue.
</P>
<P>
Experts with the State Planning Commission, State Statistical
Bureau and the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences forecast a rate
of 1-2 percentage points higher than the government target.
</P>
<P>
However, this will depend on a number of factors. For
example, the fast pace of growth depends a great deal on fiscal
control levers, and the impact of international financial turmoil
cannot be underrated.
</P>
<P>
Central authorities have fully considered the restrictive
stance of the 1998 fiscal policy and appear unwilling to push this
year's economic growth rate above last year's level of 8.8
percent. They instead intend to pursue a healthy path which will
more easily promote structural optimization, raise efficiency and
promote the reform of state-owned firms.
</P>
<P>
Government sources say that China expects a desirable mixture
of growth, inflation, unemployment and deficit reduction -- four
major indicators of the national economy -- to strike the keynote
for 1998, the 20th anniversary of the reform and opening drive in
the world's most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
This year's government plan calls for inflation rate to remain
within the range of three percent, despite a 1.2 percent hike in
prices for water and raw materials, The unemployment rate will
remain below 3.5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China's 1998 Economy Witnesses Fast, Stable Beginning (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Xinhua Writer Zhou Zongmin
</P>
<P>
Growth in fixed asset investments, retail sales and exports --
key forces driving the national economy -- are in place and will
hopefully add handsomely to the economy. Fixed asset investments
and retail sales are targeted to jump by 10 percent this year,
with projections calling for exports to hit 8 percent. The budget
deficit is expected to fall by 10 billion yuan (approximately 8.3
yuan equals one US dollar).
</P>
<P>
Enterprise reforms continue to go forward, with forecasts
calling for increasing unemployment pressure and a surge in the
number of laid-off workers. The Chinese government has vowed to
launch massive reemployment programs to reduce the annual
unemployment rate to 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Economists say that China must extend great effort to ignite
the lukewarm buyer's market, nurture consumer satisfaction and
promote various poles of economic growth, burgeoning pillar
industries in particular. A bullish consumer market will be
pivotal to steady economic growth.
</P>
<P>
China's economy currently offers a solid footing for
sustainable growth, including beneficial factors such as easing
bottlenecks, savings deposits totalling 4,700 billion yuan, good
harests for three consecutive years, and foreign exchange reserves
of over 140 billion U.S dollars.
</P>
<P>
Forecasts for this year call for increased agricultural
production, a key element of inflation. China produced 490 million
tons of grain in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade, an area which adds great vigor to the national
economy, stands out in view of modest demand on the domestic
market. Forecasts call for considerable growth in foreign trade
during 1998, with imports growing and exports slowing somewhat.
</P>
<P>
China's effort to open wider to the outside world has enabled
its economy to merge more extensively with the international
business community. At the same time, however, the nation is
becoming increasingly vulnerable to the outside environment.
</P>
<P>
Economists suggest that China should adopt effective measures
to remove outstanding snags in the economic locomotive, especially
bad debts, and should earnestly guard against banking risks.
</P>
<P>
Despite the possibility of occasional fluctuations, the
economic locomotive will continue on the fast-track throughout
1998 if macro-economic control measures adopted in the mid-1993
are pointedly enforced and carried out in a timely manner to
prevent the possibility of any derailment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
