<HEADLINE> Beijing Striving to Expand Opening Drive (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Beijing Mayor Jia Qinglin said
here today his municipality will further improve efforts to open
itself to the outside world and expand its open economy.
</P>
<P>
Jia made the remarks during a government report to today's
first session of the 11th Beijing Municipal People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The congress will summarize the work of last term's local
government, elect a new leading group, and formulate work goals
for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Jia said Beijing will introduce overall improvements to its
multi-level opening framework in various fields, formulate related
work for the service sector, and draw more overseas funds for key
construction projects.
</P>
<P>
The city will strive to convince more overseas financial
institutions to set up branches in Beijing, introduce
foreign-funded retailers, and establish jointly funded
Sino-foreign or cooperative tour agencies in accordance with the
relevant state laws and policies, said Jia.
</P>
<P>
He noted that emphasis will be placed in intensifying the
future direction of industry, and that new policies will be
introduced to encourage foreign businesspeople to invest in a
number of sectors, including the hi-tech industry, infrastructure,
the transformation of dilapidated housing, tourism and modern
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the municipal government will formulate policies to
encourage transnational corporations to base their regional
headquarters in Beijing and invest in China, said Jia, adding that
his government will offer preferential policies for major
projects, including tax reductions or exemptions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Striving to Expand Opening (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jia went on to say that the municipal government will expand
the use of foreign capital by selecting a group of state-owned
enterprises to introduce overseas funds through transfers of
property rights and the reorganization of capital.
</P>
<P>
The city used overseas funds totalling 9.75 billion US dollars
during the previous five years, including investments by 146 of
the world's top 500 transnational corporations.
</P>
<P>
In terms of foreign trade, Jia said the city will adhere to its
diversified market strategy and win market share by offering high
quality products.
</P>
<P>
The city will increase exports of hi-tech, machinery and
electronics products, as well as agricultural goods, and will
extend greater effort to exporting electronic information
processing and name brand products. He said the city will increase
exports of machinery, electronic and textile products to countries
in Asia, Africa, Latin America and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Beijing will also accelerate efforts to reform its foreign
trade system, reorganize the capital structures of foreign trade
enterprises and form large foreign trade groups, according to Jia.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that foreign-funded enterprises will be
encouraged to increase exports, and more industrial enterprises
will enter international markets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jia said, Beijing will adopt various methods to open
new channels for foreign funding over the next five years, and
will steadily enter the world capital market. The city will also
vigorously develop its service and technical trade sectors, and
will increase the proportion of the foreign trade volume to GDP,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Jia's report also pointed to the need to increase economic and
technical cooperation with Taiwan, Hong Kong and Macao, and to
boost the common economic progress of both sides of the Taiwan
Straits.  
</P>
</TEXT>
