<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Government to Rebuild Public Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After meeting with President Soeharto at his residence along
Jalan Cendana, Central Jakarta, visiting U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said that the U.S. government believes that
Indonesia will be able to regain public confidence in its economy.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who arrived here Tuesday for a three-day visit, said
that U.S. President Bill Clinton has given his support to
Indonesia's economic and financial restructurization program.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Indonesia's economic recovery program is on the
right track, Cohen said, "I am here not as an economic expert."
</P>
<P>
He said during the 40-minute talks, they did not talk about the
sale of U.S. arms to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia last year canceled the purchase of nine U.S F-16 jet
fighters to protest against what it claimed to be "wholly
unjustified criticism of the country's human rights record by the
U.S. congress.
</P>
<P>
The government then decided to buy 12 Sukhoi warplanes and 8
helicopters from Russia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Indonesian Defense Minister Edi Sudradjat, who
accompanied Cohen, said the government has canceled the purchase
of military equipment due to the ongoing monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah (national currency) fell to a historic
low last Thursday after plunged to 10,000 against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The government recently decided to postpone the purchase of the
12 Sukhoi jet fighters and the 8 helicopters from Russia due to
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Sudradjat said Indonesia has the right to decide from which
country it will buy its military equipment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
