<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Negotiations Underway to Create Arab Common Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Negotiations are currently
underway to reach a final settlement among Arab countries for the
creation of an Arab common market, head of the Association of
Lebanese Industrialists Jacques Sarraf has said.
</P>
<P>
Sarraf made the remarks following his meeting with Lebanese
Economy and Trade Minister Yassin Jaber Tuesday, local newspaper
the Beirut Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sarraf just returned from Cairo where a delegation of the
general confederation of the Arab chambers of commerce headed by
Lebanese Chamber of Commerce President Adnan Kassar held talks
with Arab League Secretary General Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid on the
region's economic situation, especially the creation of an Arab
common market.
</P>
<P>
Sarraf said that in Cairo, Kassar delivered a memorandum to
Abdul-Meguid, which calls for more effective measures to be taken
by Arab governments to ensure that the Arab common market is
created swiftly.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that "a decision will be made today by the Arab
League concerning the creation of an unified Arab economic
community," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Sarraf said that Lebanon was one of the countries in total
support for the creation of the market, adding that "Lebanon is
keen on opening up to all Arab markets."
</P>
<P>
Prior to the establishment of the common market, Lebanon is to
conclude bilateral agreements with other countries, specially the
two major consumer markets in the region, Egypt and Syria, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The idea of a common market has been circulating since the
1950's. An Arab summit in 1996 further called for the
acceleration of the creation of the free market.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1997, the Arab League launched a regional free
trade program which is considered as an important step that could
lead to the creation of a common market. Eighteen countries in the
region have agreed to join the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
