<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU in Quest for Community Strategy on Climate: EU Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Union is expected
to start seeking a community-wide strategy on climate change as
proposed by its environment commissioner Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ritt Bjerregaard outlined in a document to her European
Commission colleagues that the EU member states have to evaluate
the precise content of the commitments made in the Kyoto climate
conference last month before drawing up a community strategy for
the implementation of the commitments.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said that the member states had to start
preparing for the signing of the Kyoto protocol.
</P>
<P>
A council meeting of EU ministers is slated for March when a
detailed report specifying the real commitments the Kyoto protocol
represents for the union will be worked out.
</P>
<P>
The member states will then start ratifying the protocol, but
Bjerregaard said the ratification would require the development of
a post-Kyoto strategy.
</P>
<P>
The strategy will concern such sectors as energy efficiency,
promotion of renewable energy resources, transport measures,
sustainable management of forests, limiting or reducing methane
emissions through better waste management, new forms of
sustainable agriculture and modifications in the production,
transport and distribution of energy.
</P>
<P>
The strategy will also specify the implications for the member
states of new targets for reducing emissions of six gases instead
of three and the impact of burden-sharing among EU countries.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner also raised the question of whether the union
should settle on the 8-percent target laid down in the Kyoto
protocol or commit itself unilaterally to a higher figure of 15
percent as it proposed in its negotiating position in Kyoto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
