<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue To Surge on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continue to
surge on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index shot up by 86.75 points to close at 1243.27
points on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said market sentiment was boosted by optimistic
comments by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and U.S.
officials that economic reform in Indonesia will kick-start a
regional recovery.
</P>
<P>
They added that stable regional currencies shored up market
sentiment, along with the second consecutive gain on a resilient
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased to 578.56 million units,
valued at 832.68 million Singapore dollars (about 478.55 million
US dollars). Advances overwhelmed declines by 369 to 48, while 195
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Renong Bhd was the most actively traded counter as it
registered a turnover of 62.75 million units. It was followed by
Wing Tai which had 37.89 million of its shares traded. DBS
(Development Bank of Singapore) Land was next with 23.4 million of
its shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Local computer sound card maker Creative 50 led the gainers of
the day as it surged by three dollars to finish at 33.6 Singapore
dollars. SPH (Singapore Press Holdings) Foreign increased by 1.4
dollars to end at 20.8 Singapore dollars. SPH was up by 1.1
dollars to close at 15.3 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Perlis Plant was the biggest loser as it
declined by 1.25 dollars to end at 1.83 Singapore dollars.
InchMarkt fell by 49 cents to close at 46 Singapore cents, while
Singapore Airlines (SIA) Foreign lost 40 cents to finish at 10.6
Singapore dollars.  
</P>
