<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Winched Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
was winched 1.5 percent higher Wednesday, clawing back the rest of
Monday's 2.3 percent slide after strong gains in the U.S., Japan
and Hong Kong combined with a better gold price to steady investor
confidence.
</P>
<P>
The resources sector rallied, also driven by an announcement by
the world's largest miner, Rio Tinto, that it plans to buy back up
to 10 percent of its shares.
</P>
<P>
Blue-chip industrials also posted healthy rises Wednesday,
helping the all ordinaries index to a close of 2,605.3, up 40
points.
</P>
<P>
"Rio's rally was the big contributor to the strength in the
resources sector on top of the bullion price jumping," Shaw
Stockbroking's Jamie Spiteri said.
</P>
<P>
Improved industrial stocks were largely a carry-over from
Tuesday's market performance, further spurred by the 84.95-point
rise in the Dow Jones Industrial Average overnight to 7,732.13,
Spiteri said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong and Japan continued their recoveries with the Hang
Seng up 523.2 points to 9,243.2, while in Tokyo, the Nikkei firmed
366.04 points or 2.5 percent to a close of 15,121.98.
</P>
<P>
Locally, the resources index jumped almost four percent or 41.8
points to 1,097 and the all industrials index rose 42.5 points to
4,491.5.
</P>
<P>
The gold index surged 3.5 percent or 33.9 points to 995, just
shy of the 1000-point barrier. In Sydney, spot gold was trading at
285.30 US dollars an ounce, up 7.20 from late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Telstra installment receipts edged up six cents, Coles Myer
added 15, Qantas ended nine stronger, CSL jumped 40 and Coca-Cola
gained eight cents.
</P>
<P>
National turnover topped 310.1 million shares, worth 916.7
million Australian dollars (586.68 million U.S. dollars). Rises
outpaced falls 679 to 414.  
</P>
