<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Spend Million Ecu on Data Collection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Union is
estimated to spend up to 95 million European Currency Units (ecu)
each year till 2002 to keep track of the organization's progress
in economic and monetary union, employment, enlargement and other
fields.
</P>
<P>
The estimate, made by a five-year community statistics program,
will be presented to the European Commission Wednesday at its
council meeting.
</P>
<P>
The fund, with additional resources from national budgets of
the 15 EU member states, covers 18 fields such as free movement of
goods, people, service and capital; agriculture; economic and
monetary policy; common commercial policy; public health and
trans-European networks.
</P>
<P>
The program is expected to provide rigorous statistical
monitoring required by the launch of the single currency and to
ensure proper assessment of the economic convergence of member
states.
</P>
<P>
It will also collect data for negotiations with the accession
candidates, including Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic,
Cyprus, Slovenia and Estonia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Appraises TB-Control Program in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, January 14 (Xinhua) -- About 50,000 tuberculosis (TB)
patients, 96 percent of the total in northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province, have recovered because of loans from the
World Bank, which sponsored an anti-tuberculosis program in the
province, official sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang has the country's third highest incidence of TB,
next to Xinjiang Uygur and Tibet autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that, by the end of 1997, 150,000 people in the
province were found carrying the TB virus, 52,000 of which are TB
patients.
</P>
<P>
The 5.3 million U.S. dollars in loans from the World Bank from
1993 to 2000, plus 45 million yuan aid from the country, has
enabled the province to control the disease.
</P>
<P>
Local health departments sent TB-control staff members to give
face-to-face treatment to TB patients, who received their daily
drug dosage under the staff's supervision to ensure that they took
the medicine for the required three-to-five months.
</P>
<P>
The no-interest loans from the World Bank provided treatment
for many TB-sufferers who cannot afford the medicine or get
on-time treatment.
</P>
<P>
The program financed by World Bank was also conducted among 560
million people in 11 other provinces and autonomous regions in
addition to Heilongjiang.
</P>
<P>
Tuberculosis was previously curable. However, it re-emerged as
a major world health problem in recent years, mainly due to
improper treatment and the emergence of multi-drug resistant
strains of TB.
</P>
<P>
The number of TB patients in China accounts for one-fourth of
the world's total, and more than 250,000 people die from TB each
year in the world.
</P>
<P>
Citing TB as a serious epidemic, the World Health Organization
declared the disease a global health emergency in 1993.  
</P>
</TEXT>
