<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Bounces Over One US Cent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar soared
as much as one-and-a-half US cents Wednesday, peaking above 65.00
US cents, as Asian currencies rebounded and the gold price firmed.
</P>
<P>
Despite losing some of its gains in afternoon trading, the
currency held on to close almost one US cent higher at 64.94,
compared to 63.98 late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It earlier reached a high of 65.40 US cents when it hitched on
for a ride with other Asian currencies as the Japanese yen surged
against the US dollar.
</P>
<P>
A strong bounce in the gold price added to the bullish tone.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion in Sydney closed at 285.95 US dollars per fine
ounce, 7.70 US Dollars higher than the previous close.
</P>
<P>
Traders said a report from US investment bank Goldman Sachs
which suggested the local unit was at "an extreme level of
under-valuation" against the US dollar also bolstered the
currency's rise early in the session.
</P>
<P>
Goldman Sachs' weekly analysts' report said the Australian unit
was 19.8 percent below its assessment of fair value.
</P>
<P>
"If stability ever returns to Asia and commodity prices were to
recover in 1998, the Australian dollar could reverse some of this
substantial disequilibrium," it said.
</P>
<P>
While those factors all gave support to the beleaguered
Australian unit, traders said attempts to aggressively buy the
currency and push it up through 65.50 US cents were thwarted by a
rebound in the US dollar against the yen.
</P>
<P>
While talk that the Asian crisis might be near bottom swept
markets Wednesday, analysts said it might take more than a day or
two of good news to substantially alter the negative sentiment
surrounding the region.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended Wednesday at 85.17 yen from 84.96
and at 1.1879 marks from 1.1656.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
