<HEADLINE> Old Industrial Center Absorbs More Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, January 14 (Xinhua) -- A total of 2.8 billion
U.S. dollars in direct foreign investment was used in northeast
China's Liaoning Province in 1997, according to Vice-Governor Gao
Guozhu.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the contractual volume of foreign funds to be
used in Liaoning's projects during the year hit 4.5 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gao revealed the figures at a conference on Liaoning's use of
foreign investment now in session in the provincial capital of
Shenyang.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of foreign funds the province used through
various forms during the past five years hit 20 billion U.S.
dollars, or an average of four billion U.S. dollars a year, said
Gao.
</P>
<P>
As an old heavy industrial base in China, the province approved
1,506 overseas-funded enterprises in the first 11 months of last
year, with the total contracted volume standing at 4.1 billion U.S
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Large state-owned enterprises in Liaoning formed 53 joint
ventures with overseas partners last year.
</P>
<P>
A local auto industry company has joined hands with Mitsubishi
Company of Japan to produce parts for light-duty vehicles. The
first phase project has a designed annual production capacity of
150,000 automobile engines, with projections calling for its
annual output value to hit 4.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The province signed 16 infrastructure construction contracts
valued at 800 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
This year, the province will use overseas funds to upgrade the
technology of state-owned enterprises in the metallurgical,
petrochemical, electronics and automobile manufacturing sectors,
according to Gao.  
</P>
</TEXT>
