<HEADLINE> UNITA Hands over Diamond Mine to Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Angola's former rebel movement
the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA)
has formally handed over the diamond mine in Cuango to the
government.
</P>
<P>
a government delegation headed by Higino Carneiro, Vice
Minister of Administration of Territory, attended the handover
ceremony held in Cuango in the northeastern province of
Lunda-Norte. Isaias Samakuva, head of the UNITA
delegation in the Joint Committee of Peace Process also
attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Jose Dias, General Manager of the state-owned Angolan Diamond
Corporation, said to the press after the ceremony that the
diamond mine will increase the country's earning in foreign
currency and help revert its deficit and creat more jobs for the
Angolans.
</P>
<P>
Cuango, one of the major diamond producing areas in Angola,
was occupied by UNITA at the end of 1992 after the civil war
restarted in the country.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the mine could yield an annual income of
over 600 million dollars, which had been a major economic source
for UNITA.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said diamond mines had always been a critical
issue in the Angolan Peace Process. The handover of the mine
has been regarded as an important achievement in the peace
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
