<HEADLINE> Top Academy Faces Shortage of Scholars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Eighty-five percent of the
leading scholars of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences (CASS)
will retire before 2005, said Wang Renzhi, vice president of the
academy.
</P>
<P>
At the academy's annual work meeting today, he said that half
of its 500 leading scholars will retire before 2000, and another
35 percent before 2005.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the academy's most influential scholars are
57 or older. A crisis of succession can be attributed to the
so-called "Cultural Revolution" (1966-1976) which halted
university education. In addition, during the 1980s many poorly
paid scholars quit academia for more lucrative jobs.
</P>
<P>
The CASS, a think tank for the central government, launched a
program last year to cultivate young scholars. More than 200
outstanding young people have been chosen to inherit the academic
legacy.
</P>
<P>
Wang revealed that young and middle-aged scholars' housing
problems have been eased and they can get quick promotions.
</P>
<P>
The academy this year will take more steps to attract
first-rate scholars from other research institutions and
universities, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
Ru Xin, another vice-president, said the academy will try its
best to provide young scholars with opportunities to study abroad
and attend international seminars.
</P>
<P>
"All these measures will lay down a basis on which China's
top-rate scholars will be born in the 21st century," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
