<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Chief Hopeful of Recovery in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 14 (Xinhua) -- International Monetary Fund
(IMF) Managing Director Michel Camdessus Wednesday expressed his
hope that a second letter of intent will be signed with Indonesia
on Thursday in a joint effort to restore confidence in the
country's market.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here before he left this
afternoon for Jakarta, Camdessus said, "The immediate priority and
the very purpose" of his visit to the Indonesian capital is to
"arrest and turn around the tremendous loss of confidence and
stabilize the market through monetary disciplines and a dramatic
acceleration of the long overdue structural reforms."
</P>
<P>
"We have in our program a very significant list of measures,"
said the IMF chief, who arrived here on Tuesday en route to
Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
He said that what he looks forward to and what he hopes the IMF
could achieve is a new letter of intent to be signed on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The new letter of intent will not only demonstrate that the
Indonesian government and president are fully supportive of
implementing those reforms, but also demonstrate this by
accelerating and strengthening the implementation, he said.
</P>
<P>
If this could be achieved, he said, then people could see, in
Indonesia, the long-awaited strengthening of the exchange market
being put on "a more steady path of recovery."
</P>
<P>
"We believe that for re-establishing confidence in Indonesia
after doubt which has been generated by some hesitation in
implementation of the initial letter of intent, we see the need
for the authorities not only to reaffirm that 'we do that', but to
demonstrate their determination by action," the IMF chief said.
</P>
<P>
He also added that no better action could be found than the
strengthening and acceleration of the structural reforms, which
were already embedded in the initial letter of intent signed by
the two sides last year.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the situation in Singapore, where the local
currency and stock markets suffered sharp losses in the past
week, Camdessus said Singapore is a place which is no doubt
receiving the impact of the turmoil around it.
</P>
<P>
But he was quick to add that Singapore has managed the
situation very well, based on sound macroeconomic policies, a
strong financial position of its financial institutions as well as
continuous effort to introduce more transparency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
