<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Commercial Bank Posts Huge Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The Industrial and Commercial
Bank of China (ICBC), one of the country's four largest banks, has
reported three billion yuan (361.44 million U.S. dollars) in
profits in 1997, according to a bank report.
</P>
<P>
This is the ICBC's biggest profit in recent years, adjusted for
an increase of three percentage points in business tax, according
to officials with the ICBC.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show a growth in bank deposits of 318.1 billion
yuan to 2.155 trillion yuan last year, which increased the ICBC's
fund self-sufficiency by six percentage points to 112 percent.
</P>
<P>
Bank loans last year were up by 193 billion yuan to 1.9
trillion yuan, with most of the new loans going to the 512
state-supported key enterprises and businesses with good
profitability and high credit ratings.
</P>
<P>
The bank established an additional 3,800 operational branches
in its nationwide electronic network, increasing the number of
networked branches to 85 percent of the total. ICBC issued 25.1
million credit cards last year for a 40 percent market share,
doing 565.8 billion yuan in credit card business for a 34 percent
market share.
</P>
<P>
The international settlement business rose 25 percent to 70
billion U.S. dollars in 1997, with the buying and selling of
foreign exchange business increasing by 16 percent to 37 billion
U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
