<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Aviation Industry Loses to Harmattan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's aviation industry is
expected to lose over 100 million Naira (1.3 million U.S.
Dollars) due to flight disruptions to the northern parts of the
country caused by Harmattan Haze within the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
At least 200 flight schedules to the capital Abuja in the
middle of the country have so far been cancelled due to poor
visibility caused by the seasonal hot, dry, sand-laden wind, This
Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
Flight cancellation does not bring losses to airlines but also
to aviation oil companies, maintenance and other related service
companies, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
As the situation has not improved, Abuja travellers have no
resorted to buying up to three tickets with the hope of using
whichever airline that is available to the capital.
</P>
<P>
The problem, many travellers have complained, is attributed to
the poor equipment situation due to under-funding at the
country's domestic airports.
</P>
<P>
According to Finance Minister Anthony Ani, the Federal
Airports Authority of Nigeria, which oversees the country's
airports and also a huge loser to harmattan, has got the money
for the development of the airports.
</P>
<P>
The Aviation Ministry has kept silent at the latest
development so far.
</P>
<P>
International fligths have not been affected.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Tent Families in Quake-hit Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 14 (Xinhua) -- In Zhangbei and Shangyi
counties in North China's Hebei Province, "makeshift families" are
forming in tents among villagers who lost their homes in the
January 10th earthquake.
</P>
<P>
At Xingjialiang Village of Dahe Township near the epicenter,
Xing Renzhi's family and another six households now dwell in a
large tent set up by the People's Liberation Army (PLA).
</P>
<P>
Xing, 31, said that on the second night after Saturday's quake,
she and her fellow villagers moved into tents.
</P>
<P>
Outside Xing's tent, snow is falling and the temperature is 15
or 16 degrees below zero Centigrade (3-to-5 degrees Fahrenheit).
</P>
<P>
But in the tent, a burning stove keeps the temperature at about
10 degrees Centigrade.
</P>
<P>
Xing's tent houses about 30 people. "At night, the children and
women sleep first while the men sit till dawn due to the limited
space in the tent," she said. "Although it is crowded, it is quite
warm."
</P>
<P>
At one corner of the tent is a pile of quilts. Several kids are
sitting or lying on the canvas. Xing's four-month-old baby is
falling asleep near the stove.
</P>
<P>
"We are planning to retrieve some grain from our collapsed
houses when we are told the aftershocks are over," Xing
said. Since they moved into the tent, Xing said the women prepare
a meal each day for the tent-family which consists of seven
households.
</P>
<P>
"Other meals in a day are instant noodles," she said. "Every
other day, we get some food from the PLA soldiers."
</P>
<P>
Near the tent, collapsed houses are scattered on the
snow-covered ground with furniture and kitchenware protruding from
the ruins.
</P>
<P>
About 20 PLA men are in the process of pitching new tents for
the villagers.
</P>
<P>
Xing's mother, who is in her 70s, said that without aid from
the PLA and the government, the quake-hit people would suffer more
from the cold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
