<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Industrial Exports Up 8.2 Percent in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Israel's industrial exports
in 1997 reached 18.5 billion U.S. dollars, an 8.2 percent increase
over that of 1996, The Jerusalem Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted statistics released by Israeli Industry and Trade
Ministry Tuesday as saying that Israel's net exports of polished
diamonds in 1997 increased at the relatively moderate rate of 2.3
percent, amounting to 4.1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ministry noted that the last quarter of 1997 saw a
significant decline in diamond exports mainly as a result of the
economic crisis in Asia, which constitutes an important market
for this sector.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Israel's industrial exports, excluding diamonds, grew
10.1 percent in 1997, after a 6.3 percent growth in 1996. And the
highest rate of growth was in the high-tech industry, whose exports
rose 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, export by traditional industries fell in almost
every sector, with the exception of the wood and paper sectors
and the mining and non-metal mineral sectors.
</P>
<P>
The United States remains Israel's biggest export market, with
exports rising 14 percent in 1997, while Israel's exports to
Britain, the third largest market, rose 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Israel's second largest export market is the Palestinian
National Authority, which imported some 1.75 billion dollars in
goods from Israel last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
