<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Firms to Fund On-line Education Program in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Five firms have agreed to
pool 3.75 million U.S. dollars to sponsor an on-line education
program in California, the United States.
</P>
<P>
The program, the California Virtual University (CVU), will
list, via the Internet, 500 courses offered at any of the state's
301 accredited colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
So far, 65 schools have joined the program offering college
degrees from certificates to doctorates.
</P>
<P>
As enrollment at California's higher education institutions is
expected to grow by half a million over the next 10 years, the CVU
will play an important role in offering local residents the
education they need without adding additional students on campus.
</P>
<P>
California Governor Pete Wilson has proposed in his 1998-1999
budget that the program be expanded with 14.1 million dollars. He
also proposed that all public high school students receive
computing training and all public high schools be linked to
Internet within four years.
</P>
<P>
On-line education programs, or computer-mediated distance
education, have been in the ascendant in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 40 percent of the country's colleges and
universities have or are developing distance education programs to
supplement their array of education offerings.
</P>
<P>
The idea is that wherever or at any time, students can log into
a virtual classroom where from desktop or laptop, e-mail
assignments can be sent and received. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
