<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains in kenya to Be Followed by Drought: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 14 (Xinhua) -- This year's long rains season,
which should start in Kenya late March, may be replaced by a
spell of drought, the East African Standard newspaper today
quoted the Meteorological Department, as saying.
</P>
<P>
If the long rains come at all, they will be poor as an
aftermath of the El Nino weather phenomenon, said the
department's Assistant Director Joshua Wairoto on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Research shows that an intense El Nino is always most
likely to be followed by a reverse dry spell called La Nina, he
said, responding to the mounting anxiety over the rains which
have pounded most parts of the country since October.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains Tuesday washed away a police station, a U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees field office, a tree nursey and Dadaab
refugee camp in Eastern Province. All livestock belonging to the
refugees were dead.
</P>
<P>
Rains already claimed scores of lives, disrupted transport,
destroyed bridges, caused landslides, swept away homes and crops,
prompted cholera and malaria outbreaks.
</P>
<P>
Global forecast indicated that the El Nino has been on a
downward trend from December and is likely to end in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
