<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1998 to Be Tough Economic Year for Zimbabwe: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 14 (Xinhua) -- This year is likely to be an
extremely difficult one to Zimbabwe as it has started amid
persistent deterioration in the economic environment and
plummeting business confidence, a senior Zimbabwean business
official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are deeply concerned... 1998 will be another extremely
difficult year given the harsh economic environment, punitive
lending rates, upward inflationary pressures emanating from
devaluation, an unsustainable budget deficit and huge borrowings
from the domestic market to finance war veterans payments," said
Danny Meyer, President of the Zimbabwe National Chamber of
Commerce (ZNCC).
</P>
<P>
It is not surprising that many of ZNCC members are shelving
crucial investment projects until the economic climate recovers,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Depressed activity in the private sector also made a mockery
of the major objectives of economic reform programs which aim at
creating an investment-led and export-led sustainable
socio-economic development, Meyer noted.
</P>
<P>
The harsh economic environment, he said, would certainly push
many companies to the wall, leading to widespread retrenchments
and worsening the unemployment problem estimated at between 45 to
50 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, said the ZNCC president, hope is not lost since
Zimbabwe's economic base is still strong and what is needed is
political commitment to rebuilding the country's battered image.
</P>
<P>
Suggesting ways of rebuilding confidence, Meyer said, the
government needed to enter into serious dialogue with all
stakeholders in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Citing the budget deficit as one of the greatest causes for
current macro-economic instability, Meyer said the government
should take bold decisions to restructure the public sector so as
to resolve problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
