<HEADLINE> Hewlett-Packard Reduces Notebook PC Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Hewlett-Packard Co., one of
the largest U.S. computer makers, said Tuesday that it had cut
list prices on its notebook personal computers by 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The list price of new HP OmniBook 3000CTX, which has an Intel
233 MHz mobile Pentium processor, was cut to 4,075 dollars and is
expected to sell for 3,670 dollars in retail shops, the Palo Alto,
California-based company said.
</P>
<P>
The list price of HP OmniBook 5700 CT, with a 166 MHz Pentium
processor, was cut to 2,820 and is expected to sell for 2,540
dollars, while the list price of HP OmniBook 2000 CT was cut to
2,300 and is expected to sell for about 2,070 dollars.
</P>
<P>
This is the second cut in a week by the company as a part of
its strategy for rapid growth in the personal computer market.
</P>
<P>
On January 5, the company became the first one among the major
computer makers which announced that it offered Intel-based
multimedia personal computers at 799 dollars -- the lowest price
for such product in the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts say that the battle to capture home buyers of
personal computers will heat up with Hewlett-Packard cutting list
prices on both desktop and notebook personal computers. 
</P>
