<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Mode of Sino-African Trade Cooperation Shows Potential (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Sino-African economic and trade
cooperation made marked progress last year and the new mode used
in the 1990s by the two sides has vast potential for future
development.
</P>
<P>
These remarks came from a senior official in charge of
Sino-African trade in the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has supported and helped African
countries develop their economies since the 1960s, providing aid
without any extra political conditions.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government reformed and adjusted its aid mode based
on the changed situation of the two sides in recent years to
further expand cooperative spheres, help improve economic
advancement on the African continent, and diversify the mode of
economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The new mode integrates aid, trade, contracted labor and
investment to improve economic and trade cooperation, and such a
mode has ushered in a new stage in Sino-African economic and
trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the import-export volume between the two
sides was 4.031 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, up 2.7 percent over
the previous year and 4.3 times that of 1990.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade volume reached 4.012 billion U.S. dollars from
January to September last year, an increase of 44.7 percent over
the same period of 1996. The export volume for the same period
was 2.154 billion U.S. dollars, up 24.9 percent; and the import
volume was 1.858 billion U.S. dollars, up 77.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between the two sides totaled 5 billion U.S.
dollars last year, a major increase over 1996.
</P>
<P>
China has also achieved marked results in the contracted labor
business. Chinese companies had signed 6,983 contracts with
African countries by last October, with a total contract volume valued
at 9.297 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Mode of Sino-African Trade Cooperation Shows Potential (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To help Chinese enterprises explore the African market, China
has decided to set up investment and trade development centers in
10 African countries to provide consulting and other services.
</P>
<P>
The centers in Egypt, Guinea, Cameroun, Cote D'Ivoire, Gabon
and Mali have already been put into operation, while the centers in
Nigeria, Mozambique, Zambia and Tanzania are still in the
preparation stage.
</P>
<P>
Sino-African economic and trade cooperation has been extended
to the fields of mining, agriculture, timber, water conservation,
and construction.
</P>
<P>
The MOFTEC official said that exchanges of visits by senior
leaders of China and African countries have further
strengthened friendly cooperative relations.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin visited six African countries in
May of 1996. During his African trip, Jiang proposed building
long-term, stable, comprehensively cooperative Sino-African
relations that are oriented toward the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng visited seven African countries last
May. Leaders of a great number of African countries visited China
last year.
</P>
<P>
China is the largest developing country and Africa is
considered the largest developing continent in the world.
</P>
<P>
The MOFTEC official said that the common historical tasks,
development goals and interests have put the cooperation
between the two sides on the basis of equality.
</P>
<P>
He said this cooperation is not only of significance for the
development of Asia and Africa in the next century, the
"South-South" cooperation and peace and stability of the world,
but also for pushing China's reform and opening-up drive to
broader areas and greater dimensions as well as adding vigor to
its economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
