<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Identify Killer Disease in Northeastern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Tests have confirmed that the
disease that has claimed more than 350 lives and killed hundreds
of livestock in Kenya's North-Eastern Province is Rift Valley
Fever, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Peter Tukei, a virologist at Kenya medical Research Institute,
said analyses he had carried on 41 human and animal sample
specimens from the affected areas "strongly" indicated the killer
is the rare Rift Valley Fever as 30 samples had tested positive
for the disease.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, another seven were positive for Haema
Agglutination Assay while four were positive for Polymerase Chain
Reaction.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, South African scientists have conducted tests in
Johannesburg with similar conclusion.
</P>
<P>
"Two-third of the people had Rift Valley Fever. The others
were probably something else," said Bob Swanepoel, head of
Johannesburg's National Institute for Virology on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Red Cross Health Coordinator Saade Abdala said in Garissa, a
major affected area, on Monday that the disease was under control
as those affected were being offered medical attention and were
not dying as quickly as before.
</P>
<P>
Most victims got the disease from handling ailing livestock,
she noted, suggesting that local residents burn all carcasses.
</P>
<P>
The disease, whose victims have symptoms of vomiting,
headache, diarrhoea and bleeding from body orifices, was
communicable from livestock to human beings, said Abdala.
</P>
<P>
Fresh rains continued to pound the region in the past two
weeks and flooded the area again, making the disease, which
had actually subsided, recur.
</P>
<P>
Rift Valley Fever is a viral disease transmitted by mosquitoes
and is predominantly found in domestic animals. It can also
affect human beings exposed to heavy infection by direct contact
with infected animals.
</P>
<P>
In 1977, it suddenly flared up as a human infection in Egypt
involving 200,000 people, out of whom 600 died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
