<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Tanzanian Railway Resumes Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's Central
Railway resumed services today after three weeks of suspension
which was caused by devastating floods.
</P>
<P>
A statement released by the Tanzania Railways Corporation
(TRC) today said that the resumption of the much-awaited
services follows the repairs of nine bridges in the
Bahi-Makutupora section.
</P>
<P>
The company plans to resume train services to and from Dodoma,
Kigoma, Tabora and Mwanza.
</P>
<P>
Resumption of the services will make it possible for the
company to transport 60,000 tons of goods monthly, a great relief
to the stranded cargo, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
After completing the rehabilitation of the Bahi-Makutupora
stretch, engineers are ready to concentrate on repairs of the
railway section between Ruvu and Mnyusi where six bridges have
been damaged by floods.
</P>
<P>
Completion of the section will enable TRC to send to the
Mwanza Region 400 wagons and engines stranded in Dar es Salaam
and the Kilimanjaro Region, the company officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Central Railway built by Germans in the 19th century, and
the Tanzania-Zambia Railway constructed with the aid from China
in the 1970s, are the two major railways in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
