<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan War Mars Pakistan's Trade With Central Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The long-running armed
conflict in Afghanistan has become a major obstacle in the
development of trade between Pakistan and Central Asian states.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show the average annual trade between
Pakistan, Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan, Kazakhstan, Tajikistan and
Kirghizstan is below 48 million U.S. dollars in spite of the fact
that these countries have a potential annual trade of more than 1
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's exports to Uzbekistan in the last four years were
worth 103 million dollars while imports from that country in the
same period stood at only 4.995 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pakistan's exports to Kazakhstan in the last four
years were recorded at 40.51 million dollars and imports from it
remained at around 7.44 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Local economists are of the view that Pakistan's external trade
with Central Asian states can be enhanced rapidly provided certain
measures are taken to facilitate trade with that region via
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
They believed that Pakistan and the Central Asian states, which
became independent in 1991, had not made serious efforts to boost
their trade to exploit the existing potential.
</P>
<P>
Both sides should either pacify the warring factions in
Afghanistan to put an end to the long-running war or initiate
cargo service on subsidized rates, they said.
</P>
<P>
Since there is no other land route in this region except that
passing through the valleys of Afghanistan, the volume of trade
between Pakistan and Central Asian states are expected to remain
low as long as war lingers on in Afghanistan and cargo service is
not kicked off.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
