<HEADLINE> Census Puts Australian Students at 3.2 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Australia has almost 3.2
million full-time school students and more than 200,000 teachers,
according to figures released here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Four out of five 16-year-olds and 92 percent of 15-year-olds
went to school full-time in August last year, the preliminary
results of the 1997 National Schools Census found.
</P>
<P>
More than 2.2 million students (70.3 percent) went to the
country's 7,000 government schools while 940,000 were enrolled at
2,600 private schools.
</P>
<P>
Australia has a population of nearly 18 million.
</P>
<P>
The country's capital, Canberra, had the highest rate of
15-to-19-year-old full-time school students (61 percent) while the
sparsely-populated Northern Territory had the lowest (40.7
percent).
</P>
<P>
The country's premier state New South Wales, with more than 1
million children in schools, had the most students.
</P>
<P>
Victoria state was next with 781,000, followed by Queensland
state with 575,000, Western Australia state 311,000, South
Australia state 247,000, Tasmania 84,000, Canberra 61,000 and the
Northern Territory 36,000.
</P>
<P>
The census is based on data collected through the National
Schools Statistics Collection established by the federal
government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
