<HEADLINE> Dong Jiong Upset in Japan Open Badminton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 14 (Xinhua) -- World number one Dong Jiong of
China suffered the biggest upset at the Japan Open badminton
tournament here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The all-England champion was defeated by Malaysia's Rashid
Sidek 15-8, 15-18, 15-7.
</P>
<P>
In a day of surprises, Liu En-Hong of Chinese Taipei caused the
second upset of the day when he toppled world champion and
defending champion Peter Rasmussen of Denmark 18-15, 15-12 in the
men's singles second round.
</P>
<P>
Sidek, bronze medalist in Atlanta Olympic Games, resorted to
his effective baseline strokes and a series of quick attacks at
the net to savor his victory.
</P>
<P>
"I'm happy because he is the second seed. I'm no seed, I've got
nothing to worry about," said Sidek, who avenged his loss in the
Atlanta Olympics semi-finals against Dong, the silver medallist.
</P>
<P>
Rasmussen was tied with Liu at 13-13 in the first and 12-12 in
the second, but the 32-year-old veteran player won the coming
points to seal the competition in one hour.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Roslin Hashim scored a 15-12, 15-5 upset victory over
1993 world champion Joko Suprianto of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
In the third round, Hashim will face Grand Prix Final champion
Sun Jun of China, who defeated Japan's Keita Masuda 15-3, 15-7
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Other favourites, top seed Peter Gade Christensen and fellow
Danish Olympic champion Poul-Erik Hoyer-Larsen, advanced safely to
the next round.
</P>
<P>
Christensen outpointed Wong Ewee Mun of Malaysia 15-1, 15-10,
and Hoyer-Larsen downed China's Chen Wei 17-14, 17-14, while 1995
Japan Open champion Heryanto Arbi of Indonesia beat Japan's Ryo
Nihei 15-6, 15-3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
