<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 30 Percent of Pregnant Women HIV Positive in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 14 (Xinhua) -- About 30 percent of Zimbabwe's
pregnant women are HIV positive and 50 percent of children born
to HIV mothers die within two to three years, a medical
technologist said here last night.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launch of the book titled Monitoring
Transmitted Clinics in Zimbabwe, Alexio Mashu, a chief medical
technologist of the University of Zimbabwe's School of Medicine,
said the project, started in 1993, was aimed at influencing
policy makers to adopt the results and make them available to
everyone.
</P>
<P>
The rate of HIV infection had increased from 18 percent in
1990 to 30 percent in 1996, Mashu said, adding that most babies
were infected with HIV at birth.
</P>
<P>
In Zimbabwe, about 7.2 percent of pregnant women, 17 percent of
males and 18 percent of females are infected with HIV-2 which is
prevalent in west Africa. Mashu described the situation as
frightening.
</P>
<P>
About 68 percent of people who once suffered from sexually
transmitted diseases are highly vulnerable to HIV infection, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malta PM Meets Chinese Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VALLETTA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Malta Prime Minister Alfred
Sant said here Tuesday that Malta is willing to further promote
its friendly and cooperative ties with China in all fields.
</P>
<P>
During the talks with visiting Chinese Vice Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen, Sant said there exist healthy and sound
relations between Malta and China. Malta is eager to further push
forward the economic and trade cooperation between the two
countries in the future.
</P>
<P>
Speaking highly of the China-Malta ties, Qian said that
relations have been developing smoothly since the two countries
established diplomatic ties 26 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the efforts by the present and previous governments
of the two countries, China and Malta surmount their differences
on national conditions and the long distance between them and
develop their bilateral cooperation, Qian added.
</P>
<P>
"During my talks with Malta Foreign Minister George Vella, I
had an impression that China and Malta are certain to further
cooperate with each other closely," Qian said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese foreign minister said that the present cooperation
should adapt to the ongoing economic reforms in the two countries
and enable enterprises to play leading roles in China-Malta
economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
And the big changes in the world situation called for the
adoption of new forms in nation-to-nation cooperation, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that China and Malta can find new cooperative ways
which meet the demands of the two countries," Qian added.
</P>
<P>
Sant said Maltese enterprises were anxious to strengthen
contacts and cooperation with Chinese firms.
</P>
<P>
Malta is also reforming its economic system in a bid to further
diversify its foreign contacts, Sant said. Malta hopes to broaden
its friendly cooperation with other countries including China.
</P>
<P>
Sant believed that Qian's present visit to Malta would surely
contribute to the enhancement of Malta-China economic and trade
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Qian noted that the Chinese and Malta governments should create
opportunities for the two countries' enterprises to promote their
mutual understanding and exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Sant agreed. He said the two countries should attach importance
to the function of the market in their cooperation and make
far-sighted, cooperative strategies.
</P>
<P>
Both Qian and Sant hoped that the meeting of the China-Malta
mixed committee on economic and trade cooperation, to be held this
year, would further reinforce the development of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the financial turmoil in Southeast Asia, Qian said
the globalization of the world economy has brought about both
positive and negative results.
</P>
<P>
In this situation, it is important for a country to establish a
healthy economic frame and financial system, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
On the effect of the market crisis on Hong Kong, Qian said Hong
Kong is able to stand the impact because it has solid economic
fundamentals, a sound financial system and close links with
China's mainland.
</P>
<P>
Sant briefed Qian on Malta's foreign policies and relations,
especially its ties with the European Union and Arab countries
south of the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister noted that Malta has been devoting itself to
maintaining peace and stability and promoting development and
cooperation in the Mediterranean region.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that China appreciates the neutral policy pursued by
Malta. The two countries often share similar views on
international issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
Qian arrived in Malta on Monday for a three-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday morning, Qian also met Malta Minister of Trade Leo
Brincat, Minister of Tourism Karmenu Vella and Minister of
Industry John Montalto. 
</P>
</TEXT>
