<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Coping With Unusually Warm, Wet Winter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Residents in China's leading
industrial city of Shanghai are experiencing a warm and rainy
season this winter.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologist Shi Youhao said that it is the 10th consecutive
warm winter in Shanghai. The average daily temperature in the
first 10 days of January was 7.3 degrees Centigrade (45.1 degrees
Fahrenheit), 3.9 degrees higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
Shi added that the average monthly temperature in December in
1997 was 8 degrees Centigrade, 2.1 degrees higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
If the average temperature in the three-month winter season
(December-February) in Shanghai is one degree higher than normal,
he explained, the winter can be classified as warm.
</P>
<P>
Another major characteristic of this winter is Shanghai's
rainfall, which was 102.5 millimeters in December, triple the
historic average.
</P>
<P>
He said December's rainfall was Shanghai's third-highest
since 1873.
</P>
<P>
Huang Jiaxin, deputy head of Shanghai Meteorological
Station, attributed the warm rainy weather to a relatively strong
humid southwest front and a weak northern cold front creating
stable atmospheric conditions over the area.
</P>
<P>
Department stores and shops in Shanghai have reduced the price
on fur coats and thick overcoats because the unusually warm
weather has hurt sales.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
