<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Scientist Stresses Sino-US Technological Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- An American scientist has
called for more Sino-U.S. scientific and technological cooperation
in personnel training and information exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation in the two fields would help China "revitalize the
country with science and education" and keep up with international
scientific developments, Chang-Lin Tien said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tien, former chancellor at the University of California at
Berkeley in the San Francisco Bay Area, is the first foreign
academician in the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. educator said he is deeply concerned with scientific
progress in China. As a member of the American Academy of
Engineering and the Governor of the Committee of One Hundred, he
has put forward some useful proposals on Sino-U.S. co-operation to
the American president.
</P>
<P>
"The policies for cultivation of foreign scientific and
technological personnel are quite flexible in the United States,"
he said. "Chinese students and researchers are welcome to use the
abundant information resources and advanced facilities in American
universities and institutes to improve their studies."
</P>
<P>
UC Berkeley has received many students from the Asia-Pacific
region, especially from China, Tien said. The school began
cooperation in 1970 with Qinghua University, Beijing University
and other universities in personnel training and academic
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Tien said that information exchanges, which can help scientists
from both countries share their research findings and academic
results, can play a vital role in Sino-U.S. scientific
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said the opening of the China server of the American
Magazine "Science" on the Internet was an example of progress in
this field.
</P>
<P>
An authoritative scholar on heat transmission, Tien is
currently working on cooperative projects concerning the studies
of heat transmission with the State Natural Science Fund
Committee, Chinese Academy of Sciences and Qinghua University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
