<HEADLINE> Klim, Popov to Vie for World Best Freestyler Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Australian Michael Klim, who has
won two gold medals in the current world swimming championships,
is to clash with Russian Alexander Popov Wednesday night to decide
who is the best freestyler in the world.
</P>
<P>
Klim and Popov, both coached by Russian Gennadi Touretski in
the Canberra Sports Institute, finished 1-2 in the men's 100m
freestyle heats and they will square off in tonight's final.
</P>
<P>
Klim, the Polish-born swimmer who was brought up in India,
clocked 49.33 seconds in the heats, just 0.24 seconds clear of
Popov, world record holder over 100m, four-time Olympic gold
medalist and European champion at both 50m and 100m.
</P>
<P>
Dutchman P. van Den Hoogenband finished third and Brazilian
Gustavo Borges was fourth, both reaching the final.
</P>
<P>
American Brooke Bennet won the women's 400m freestyle heats,
beating Kirsten Vlieghuis of the Netherlands and Olympic champion
Claudia Poll of Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Chen Yan, 400m individual medley winner on Monday,
placed fifth.
</P>
<P>
European champion Frank Esposito of France came first in the
men's 200m butterfly heats, clocking 1:56.32.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Takashi Yamamoto finished second in 1:56.99 with
Ukraine's Dnys Sylantyev third in 1:57.62.
</P>
<P>
Two Japanese have booked their spots in the women's 100m
backstroke final as Pan Pacific champion Mai Nakamura and Noriko
Inada finished second and seventh respectively.
</P>
<P>
American Lea Maurer, Pan Pacific silver medalist last year, won
the heats in 1:00.77.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 4x100m freestyle relay heats, the American
quartet of Catherine Fox, Lindsey Farella, Melanie Valerio and
Beth Bedford came first in 3:44.89, 0.91 seconds clear of
Australia and a further 0.03 faster than Canada.
</P>
<P>
Germany, Sweden, Britain, China and the Netherlands also made
the final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
