<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Impoverished Area Making Gains Under Market Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The long-secluded mountainous
Dingxi Prefecture in northwest China's Gansu Province, known as
the country's most impoverished area, is reportedly doing better
under a market economy, and eager to embrace the outside world.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1980s the area had nearly two million people
living below the poverty line, but that number now has been
reduced to 500,000. The prefecture plans to help the remaining
poor farmers rise above the poverty line by 1999, a year earlier
than the state-designated deadline.
</P>
<P>
Colorful advertisements along the region's 312 Highway and
French fries on farmers' tables take some visitors by surprise.
</P>
<P>
The residents of Dingxi once relied heavily on potatoes to
survive famines, but they have changed them into a major product
for export.
</P>
<P>
In the past, thousands of local farmers would leave the region
to go begging, but 300,000 rural laborers now earn 3 billion yuan
annually by working on construction sites in urban areas. Some of
these rural laborers have returned to their hometowns with
entrepreneurial ideas, setting up village businesses and making a
good living.
</P>
<P>
Cash crops also have become very popular. For example, the
herbal medicine Chinese angelica produced in the region accounts
for 70 percent of both the total output and exports in the
country. Local people also are working toward building Dingxi into
China's largest production and processing center for potatoes.
</P>
<P>
More investors have begun showing interest in the area as it
has opened wider to the outside. Fourteen joint ventures have
settled in Dingxi investing 8 million U.S. dollars, said Shi
Zuofeng, the prefecture's Party secretary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Auto Parts Industry Opposes Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 14 (Xinhua)-- India's domestic automobile
components industry is deeply perturbed at the tendency of global
car manufacturers to encourage 100-percent-owned subsidiaries of
components suppliers, local car components industry sources said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Fears have been expressed that this would have adverse impact
on the domestic industry which had been gearing up to meet the
demands of global automobile players.
</P>
<P>
Leading auto components manufacturers have said that the
government should discourage the setting-up of 100 percent
foreign-owned subsidiaries in this sector. They asserted that the
domestic industry has the capacity and capability to supply enough
qualified auto components, adding that technology upgradation and
expansion of capacities have been underway to meet the new
challenges.
</P>
<P>
India's auto components industry has been growing at a fast
pace, though total revenue from it is only 0.7 percent of the
world components industry. The industry said it would prefer joint
ventures and technological collaborations so as to upgrade itself
and emerge as a global player.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
