<HEADLINE> Shanghai, Liaoning, Nantong Report Success in Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The state-run enterprises of
Shanghai recaptured first place among the metropolis' exporters
with 20.13 billion U.S. dollars and a 60.2 percent of the area's
export shares in 1997, today's International Business Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai traded 58.68 billion U.S. dollars in commodities last
year, up 11 percent over 1996, according to the report. Its exports
grew 22.9 percent to 33.45 billion U.S. dollars, while the imports
remained stable at 25.23 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
High-technology commodity exports accounted for 9.6 percent of
the total export in 1997.
</P>
<P>
China's northeast Liaoning Province increased its exports by
6.7 percent over 1996 with a total of 8.9 billion U.S. dollars,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Nantong, a city in east China's Jiangsu Province, recorded a 14
percent growth in 1997 with 2.6 billion U.S. dollars in exports,
the report said. The actual utilization of overseas capital also
increased by 20.83 percent for the year to surpass 600 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-funded businesses made 1.12 billion U.S. dollars in
exports for 1997, 64.4 percent of the city's total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
