<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT: 80 Die as Afghan Plane Crashes in Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 14 (Xinhua) -- As many as 80 people, most of
them Afghan nationals, are reported to have died when a
Russian-made Afghan plane crashed late Tuesday night in Pakistan's
Baloshistan Province.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports Wednesday the plane crashed
near Chaman, about 110 kilometers north of Quetta, provincial
capital of Balochistan due to inclement weather.
</P>
<P>
The plane took off from the Kandhar Airport in southern
Afghanistan for the northwest province of Kerat Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
However, when it reached near destination, it could not land
due to inclement weather. The plane then returned to Kandhar, as
the weather of Kandhar was also foggy, it could not land there
either, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Later the pilot moved the plane towards Pakistan informing the
Quetta airport control about the situation and requested to allow
for emergency landing. The civil aviation authorities arranged
emergency landing for the ill-fated passenger carrier.
</P>
<P>
The plane was on its way to the Quetta Airport when it crashed
in Khojak pass's hilly track because of darkness and cloudy
weather, killing all the passengers and crew.
</P>
<P>
There are other reports saying the crash of the Afghan plane
took place late at around 10:30 Tuesday night when the plane with
more than 90 people on board were on their way to Quetta from
Kandhar. But due to some technical fault and diminishing fuel, the
plane could not continue its journey and crashed in Chaman area.
</P>
<P>
The local authority in Chaman said Wednesday that they arranged
rescue teams immediately after getting the news and tried their
best to reach the spot. However, due to darkness and the rain,
they could not start relief operation.
</P>
<P>
Further details are awaited.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
