<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Japanese Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Japanese newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
Asahi, Yomiuri, Mainichi, Nihon Keizai:
</P>
<P>
-- The Fair Trade Commission on Tuesday searched the Japanese
subsidiary of U.S. computer software giant Microsoft Corp. on
suspicion that Microsoft and the subsidiary violated the
Antimonopoly Law.
</P>
<P>
Yomiuri, Mainichi, Nihon Keizai:
</P>
<P>
-- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto on Tuesday hinted
that a 2 trillion yen (about 15.3 billion dollars) one-shot tax
cut may need to happen more than once.
</P>
<P>
Yomiuri:
</P>
<P>
-- The Japanese government and the ruling Liberal Democratic
Party will push additional pump priming measures, probably in
April. The additional measures could include a plan to continue
income tax cuts in fiscal 1999 and beyond, and supplementary
action to restore stability to the country's financial system.
</P>
<P>
Asahi, Yomiuri, Nihon Keizai:
</P>
<P>
-- Japan's Sanwa Bank and Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi will issue
"permanent" subordinated bonds under a government-drafted scheme.
</P>
