<HEADLINE> U.S. Fears Economic Crisis Disrupts Stability in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen has expressed concerns that the current economy
turmoil in Southeast Asia could disrupt regional stability, an
Indonesian diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who arrived here Tuesday as part of his seven-nation
Asian tour, held discussions with Indonesian officials Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Cohen admitted that Washington is concerned about what has
been happening in the region," Indonesia's ambassador-at-large
Sutresno Nana was quoted by local press reports as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's round-table discussions were held by the Indonesian
Council on World Affairs (ICWA).
</P>
<P>
Nana, who is a member of the council's advisory board, said
Cohen also underlined the importance of Southeast Asia to U.S.
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Cohen is due to meet with President Soeharto Wednesday to
discuss security issues.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah has plunged to historic lows in the past
six months and forced Jakarta to seek a bailout package from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Cohen said Tuesday that his three-day visit here would focus
more on security issues than economic ones.
</P>
<P>
Cohen leaves for Singapore tomorrow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
