<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Oil Product Demand Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bangkok, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The economic slump in Thailand
has resulted in the first drop in more than a decade in the
country's oil product demand, according to the Department of
Commercial Registration.
</P>
<P>
Demand fell by 0.1 percent in 1997 compared with 1996, to an
average of 112 million liters a day, the department was quoted
Wednesday by local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
For more than a decade, Thailand's oil consumption had risen by
an average of more than 10 percent a year, fuelled by a booming
economy. Thailand had one of the highest energy consumption growth
rates in the world.
</P>
<P>
Increased domestic refining capacity and the slowdown in demand
have boosted the country's export of oil products to neighboring
Indochina and Singapore by 38 percent to 15 million liters a day.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reconstruction Progresses Well in Northern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Infrastructure development
programs initiated by the Sri Lankan government in the north of
the country to rebuild the war-ravaged areas are progressing well,
government officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The officials said people in the north will enjoy better living
conditions by February, six months after the programs were
launched to improve transport, education, power, agriculture and
health facilities there.
</P>
<P>
Almost all schools in the Jaffna Peninsula are functioning
again while a few others are expected to be reopened by the end of
February.
</P>
<P>
A new bus stand which can accommodate about 800 commuters will
be put into use this week in Jaffna town, they said. Around 50 new
buses will also be provided to the peninsula soon.
</P>
<P>
Road construction in Jaffna and other areas has been completed
and rural areas in the peninsula will have power supply when six
new power generators reach Jaffna by the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
Ten newly-installed telephone booths in Jaffna have become a
source of sizable income for the Sri Lanka Telecom Company as each
booth can collect nearly 10,000 rupees (164 U.S. dollars) a day.
</P>
<P>
Reconstruction of the Alfred Duraiappa Soccer Stadium, which
cost 1 million rupees (16,393 dollars), has been completed and the
stadium, which Officials said could accommodate more than 30,000
spectators, is due to open by next week.
</P>
<P>
Since the government troops captured the Jaffna Peninsula from
the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam in 1996, various
reconstruction projects have been carried out to rebuild the
war-torn region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
