<HEADLINE> Global Chip Sales Hit Year-Long High in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Global chip sales in November
1997 hit a year-long high of 12.1 billion U.S. dollars,
representing a 0.9 percent growth over October and a 9.1 percent
surge over November 1996.
</P>
<P>
Europe showed the strongest growth with sales increasing 6
percent from October 1997 and 13.1 percent from November 1996, the
California-based Semiconductor Industry Association announced in a
press release on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
European chip sales stood at 2.69 billion dollars in November
1997, against 2.54 billion dollars in October 1997 and 2.38
billion dollars in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. market fetched the largest revenue for November with
sales reaching 3.97 billion dollars, a 12.1 percent increase over
November 1996 and a 0.2 percent decline from October 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sales in Asia-Pacific amounted to 2.73 billion dollars, a 17.6
percent gain from November 1996 and a 0.1 percent fall from
October.
</P>
<P>
Japan's sales were 2.72 billion dollars in November 1997, a 4.8
percent dip from November 1996 and a 1.1 percent decline from
October 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
