<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Publishes Tariff Reduction List Under AFTA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has published its
customs duty reduction list under the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA)
scheme, according to a Government House press release available
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The list covers more than 8,000 items for tariff cuts.
</P>
<P>
A total of 3,419 items under 15 categories have been put on the
"fast track," under which customs duties will be reduced to
between zero and five percent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The 15 categories are cement, fertilizer, paper and pulp,
furniture, wood, gems and jewelry, textiles, electronics,
chemicals, plastics, rubber products, ceramics and glass, copper,
leather and edible oil.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 5,215 items will be on the "normal track," under
which customs duties will be reduced to between zero and five
percent by 2003, when the AFTA process is supposed to have
completed.
</P>
<P>
Items on the "normal track" include non-processed agricultural
goods, ready-to-eat foods, beverages, paints, cosmetics, metals,
machinery, electrical appliances, vehicles and parts, time-pieces
and musical instruments.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 183 items, which had been left off the tariff cut
list, are being gradually phased back into the AFTA tariff
reduction list, at a rate of 20 percent of these goods each year
starting from 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
