<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Readjustment Structure of Export Commodities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai is to reinforce the
adjustment in the structure of export commodities this year, as
part of the efforts to cope with the possible negative impact of
the financial crisis in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The readjustment also aims to accelerate the city's foreign
trade, the Beijing-based International Business Daily has
reported.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai will import a group of foreign-funded high-tech
projects and further expand the export of machinery and
electronics as well as high-tech and high value-added products by
taking the advantage of the state's tax-free policy on technology
import.
</P>
<P>
Other measures to be taken by the city include:
</P>
<P>
-- The industrial and trading companies will join hands to
explore overseas market. Products will be manufactured where they
are sold and new distribution and service centers will be built
overseas;
</P>
<P>
-- Oversea-oriented companies should take the lead in
triggering export. The investment in South Africa will be
increased;
</P>
<P>
-- The city will make effort to absorb transnational companies
to establish production and technology development bases;
</P>
<P>
-- The city will strengthen the reforms of its state-owned
trade firms so as to raise their competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Mayor of Shanghai Jiang Yiren had defined it as one of the
principles to " develop steadily and give priority to quality" in
advancing foreign trade, the report says.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 Shanghai witnessed a total export value of 14,724
million US dollars, 11.22 percent higher than that of 1996. Of the
total export, technology export accounted for 664 million US
dollars, and the export of high-tech and highly value-added
products was valued at 2,247 million US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
