<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0300 GMT, January 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, China -- The earthquake that hit China's Hebei
Province at 11:50 a.m. (0350 GMT) on Saturday has claimed 49
lives, injured more than 12,000, and resulted in damage to 150,000
houses.
</P>
<P>
The magnitude 6.2 quake did 2.37 billion yuan worth of damage
to the area, according to the latest figures.
(China-Quake-Toll-Updated)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Commission is deliberating on whether
or not to recommend lifting the worldwide ban on British
beef. Discussion on the issue commenced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ban was imposed 21 months ago and may be lifted on meat
from "certified" herds in Northern Ireland, where computerized
records have been kept.
</P>
<P>
England, Wales and Scotland must wait until a computer tracking
system is in force and working to European Union (EU)'s
satisfaction. (EU-Britain-Beef)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- More than 500,000 residents in the northern and
northeastern United States remained without power as a result of
last week's ice-storms that also struck large areas of Canada.
</P>
<P>
More than 400,000 people in Maine, about 16,500 homes and
businesses in New Hampshire and 6,000 residents in Vermont were
still left without electricity, an Associated Press report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an estimated 116,500 customers in northern New York
were without power and utility officials estimated that more than
275,000 people were affected. About 9,000 people have to stay in
120 emergency shelters. (US-Storm)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A twin-engine jet crashed near the George Bush
International Airport at Houston Tuesday, killing the pilot and
co-pilot.
</P>
<P>
The Lear Jet was flying from Hobby Airport on the southeast
side of Houston to Bush on the north side.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- An Afghan cargo plane carrying as many as 90
Afghan fighters slammed into a mountain Tuesday in southwestern
Pakistan, the Associated Press of Pakistan reported.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft apparently strayed off course because of bad
weather and hit a mountain near the city of Khojak, but there were
no immediate report about the death toll.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- A fairly strong earthquake measuring 5.0 on the
Richter scale jolted Tokyo and surrounding Kanto Plain early
Wednesday, the Meteorological Agency said.
</P>
<P>
There were no immediate reports of casualties or damage.
</P>
<P>
The quake, which occurred at around 2:17 a.m., was centered 80
kilometers underground in northwestern Chiba Prefecture, east of
Tokyo, the agency said. (Japan-Quake) 
</P>
