<HEADLINE> Thousands Remain Without Power in Northeastern U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Tuesday declared 15 counties in the northeastern state of Maine
disaster areas, entitling the ice-storm-stricken areas to federal
aid.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday was the fifth straight day without electricity for some
130,000 Mainers, as an army of utility workers struggled to
restore power.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 120,000 utility customers were still
without power Tuesday in upstate New York, 5,400 customers in New
Hampshire, and about 4,000 in Vermont, said a report of the
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the week, more than 500,000 people in the region had
been without electricity.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Maine governor Angus King, who said that the storm
has cost his state nearly 6.2 million U.S. dollars, asked for
federal emergency relief.
</P>
<P>
National Guard units were called out to help restore power and
with cleanup throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
The storm brought floods across the south last week and spread
thick ice across the northeastern and eastern part of Canada,
leading to 22 deaths in Maine, New York, Tennessee and other
eastern states, as well as 15 deaths in Canada, reports reaching
here said.
</P>
<P>
The ice storm caused heavy damage to the electric delivery
systems in the northeastern states. Hundreds of utility poles
snapped and power lines were strewn on frozen snow.
</P>
<P>
In the last few days, people in the region have to rely on
woods to warm them up, but it was difficult for them to find dry
burnable woods in the snow after the storm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
