<HEADLINE> Czech Car Production Booms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The year 1997 saw a continued
increase in car production and sales in the Czech Republic, a
spokesman for the Czech Skoda motor works said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said production of Skoda brand cars rose to a record high of
357,000 in 1997, a 35.8 percent increase over that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The sales last year were up 28.8 percent over 1996, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Skoda, a motor works 100 years old, mainly produces low and
medium cost cars. Because of their good quality and low prices,
Skoda cars are now sold to more than 70 countries and regions
including China.
</P>
<P>
The production of Skoda cars has increased steadily in recent
years. Its production in 1995 and 1996 increased to 208,000 and
263,000 respectively from 178,000 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
However, the increase still could not meet the increasing
demand both at home and abroad, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Skoda has set up branch works in Poznan, Poland, and Sarajevo,
Bosnia. Negotiations on setting up joint ventures in India and
Russia are underway. 
</P>
