<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share-holding Revives State-run Brewery in Lhasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The Lhasa Beer Co. Ltd., which
grew on the basis of the state-run Lhasa Brewery, scored a pre-tax
profit of 10 million yuan (1.2 million US dollars) in 1997 since
the new share-holding company was set up last May.
</P>
<P>
The company is located in Lhasa, capital city of China's
plateau Tibet Autonomous Region. It is one of the country's 100
experimental enterprises, and the only one in Tibet, which adopts
a modern enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
The brewery began a depression in early 1995, with losses
standing at 10 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Joining hands with a company from nearby Sichuan Province, the
brewery was turned into the Lhasa Beer Co. Ltd., with the two
parties holding 61 percent of the new company's stocks. And the
remaining stocks are held by several state-run and private
businesses and individuals.
</P>
<P>
Practices have shown that the share-holding method proves to be
an effective way out for state-run enterprises like the Lhasa
Brewery, said Xu Mingyang, vice-chairman of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials in charge of the region's economic
restructuring, state-run businesses in Tibet hold total assets of
more than six billion yuan. However, many of them are in dire
operation and need to be revitalized.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that pillar state-run enterprises in Tibet
will be transformed into share-holding companies, and smaller ones
can be sold out, leased out, annexed, auctioned, or go
bankrupt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
