<HEADLINE> Three-Fourths of Rural Chinese Residents Are Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Over three-fourths of
able-bodied rural Chinese residents are engaged in agricultural
production, with more people moving to non-agricultural
businesses, said the latest report by the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The report said that by the end of 1996, China had 560.855
million working people in the rural areas, and 75.67 percent of
them were involved in agricultural production. The rest of the
people worked in village and township enterprises, commercial or
construction companies, or joined migration waves into the cities
for odd jobs.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the rate of non-agricultural rural people
in eastern areas, where industrial development is the most
advanced in the country, is "obviously higher" than the rest of
the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, China had 2.717 million agricultural
technicians, accounting for 0.64 percent of the total number of
people engaged in agricultural production, at the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, about 22.45 million people, or 5.3 percent of the
national farming population, took part in courses on agricultural
science and technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
