<HEADLINE> Radar System to Detect Drug Trafficking in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, January 13 (Xinhua) -- A radar system supported by
a fleet of United States Awac airplanes will be used to patrol air
and sea space in Latin American countries to control
drug-trafficking, a senior Panamanian official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Panamanian Foreign Minister Ricardo Arias told the press that
the Anti-Drug Multilateral Center (ADMC) will be in charge of
surveying the air space of Bolivia, Peru, Ecuador, Colombia, Mexico
and Panama in order to control drug-trafficking in the region.
</P>
<P>
Arias said that at a ministerial meeting held Monday, officials
from Mexico, Brazil and Colombia discussed the preliminary accords
reached by Panama and the U.S. on December 23 last year in Miami
and decided to set up the ADMC.
</P>
<P>
The ADMC will be located at the riversides of the Panama Canal
and will function for an expandable 12-year term. Some 1,500
people will be working at the center.
</P>
<P>
The formal meeting on the setting up of the ADMC and the
integration of Latin American countries will be held within two
weeks. 
</P>
