<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solar Eclipse Provides Clue to Earliest Chronological Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have put the
country's earliest chronological record half a century ahead
through studying ancient documents on solar eclipse.
</P>
<P>
Previously China had no chronological record before 841 BC, or
the first year of Gong He, when two famous ministers joined
efforts to support King Cheng of the Zhou Dynasty (about 11th
Century-221 BC).
</P>
<P>
This had not been broken until recently when the experts found
a clue in documents of earlier solar eclipse.
</P>
<P>
According to the documents, people in Zheng (present-day Xi'an
in northwest China's Shaanxi Province) saw daybreak twice one day
in the first year of the Reign of King Yi of Zhou. But which year
was that?
</P>
<P>
By studying reports from 18 different locations in northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region for observing a solar
eclipse on March 9, 1996, the experts found that observers from
the western direction could see the phenomenon of daybreak twice
during the eclipse.
</P>
<P>
The experts then searched for all solar eclipses happened
during 1,000-840 BC and figured out the areas where two daybreaks
might have been observed.
</P>
<P>
At last they found two solar eclipses, on April 21, 899 BC and
October 6, 871 BC, separately, may result in two daybreaks in
Zheng. The year 871 BC, however, was not possible to be the first
year of the Reign of King Yi according to other historical
evidences.
</P>
<P>
Thus the experts determined that the year 899 BC was the first
year of the Reign of King Yi. It is the oldest chronological
record ever found in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
