<HEADLINE> More Foreign Investment In East China's Jiangxi Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, January 14 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangxi Province
has become popular with foreign investors, and had used 569
million US dollars of foreign funds by last year,
according to Bi Bisheng, who is in charge of the province's
foreign investment and trade.
</P>
<P>
The province approved 429 foreign investment projects involving
a total of 796 million US dollars from overseas, and direct
foreign investment was 436 million US dollars, almost double the
figure for the same period of 1996, Bi said.
</P>
<P>
Bie attributes the growth in foreign investment to China's
opening up along the Yangtze River Valley and the completion of
the Beijing-Kowloon Railway, which he believed had greatly
improved the investment environment in the province.
</P>
<P>
The province had only one sino-foreign joint venture in 1984
but there were already 5,320 such enterprises by last
December. The joint ventures involve 5.28 billion US dollars in
investment, of which 2.78 billion US dollars had been used.
</P>
<P>
Foreign companies from 45 countries and regions now have
investment in more than 30 economic sectors in the province
including energy, telecommunications, machinery, and electronics.
</P>
