<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippine Peso Rallies on Bank, Govt Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso rallied
Tuesday for the fourth straight session as a result of the Central
Bank and the government's efforts to curb the recent free fall of
the currency.
</P>
<P>
The peso strengthened by 0.75 percent to 43.62 pesos to the
U.S. dollar from Monday's 43.95 pesos. Trading ranged from 43.75
to 43.51 pesos to the dollar on a volume of 86.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Since last Thursday, the peso has been gaining strength, rising
by a total of 4 percent from last Wednesday's weighted average of
45.42 pesos to the dollar to the current level.
</P>
<P>
The local stock market also reversed and performed well due to
the surge of the peso. The 30-share composite index soared 58.02
points, or 3.8 percent, to close at 1,590.99 points Tuesday after
rising 14.97 points on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The peso and the stock market index had been faltering since
the very beginning of the year. The currency dropped to an
all-time low of 46.53 pesos per dollar during last Wednesday's
intra-day trading and the index nose-dived by 138 points, or 8.3
percent, to close at 1,518 points last Friday, the lowest in the
past four years.
</P>
<P>
Analysts and dealers attributed the rebound of the peso to
various measures taken by the Central Bank and the government
recently.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank raised its overnight lending rate to 16
percent Tuesday from 15.4 percent on Monday, but held its key
overnight borrowing rate at 12 percent, to ward off currency
speculators.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the bank also began selling through commercial banks
a new kind of dollar hedge facility, the non-deliverable forward
(NDF) contracts, to ease pressure on the peso.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few weeks, companies with dollar-denominated
debts have been buying the greenback heavily in anticipation of a
further fall of the beleaguered peso, pushing the peso to
consecutive new lows.
</P>
<P>
By using the NDF facility, corporate borrowers can buy dollars
at the pre-determined exchange rate, thus substantially reducing
demand for the greenback on the current market.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Central Bank is considering ordering the banks
to fully disclose their pertinent details including securities
holdings, trading accounts, updated profits, amounts of bad loans
and detailed investment portfolios.
</P>
<P>
It also urged the banks to set aside a two percent reserve
against possible default loans as soon as possible and mulled
stiffer penalties for violations of foreign exchange rules.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the austerity drive launched by President Fidel
Ramos at the end of last year also helped underpin the peso,
giving a boost to investors' eroded confidence.
</P>
<P>
According to Ramos' order, any government departments or
agencies, including state-run colleges and corporations, must cut
at least 25 percent of their spending this year.
</P>
<P>
To attain this target, new capital or huge infrastructure
projects, purchase of new cars, travels abroad by government
employees and all unnecessary celebrations would be suspended this
year.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also urged his fellow countrymen to buy local products
instead of foreign brands and convert their dollars into pesos to
help the country weather the financial storm.
</P>
<P>
However, many analysts and traders remained unconvinced that
the rebound could be sustained for long, as the overall regional
situation has not shown any signs of improvement.
</P>
<P>
Deogracias Vistan, president of the Commercial Banks
Association, said the recovery of the peso may be good news for
some sectors, but banks were worrying that the behavior of the
spot currency market might again attract "global speculators."
</P>
<P>
He said the peso's fast appreciation amid the continued plunge
of other regional currencies, including the Thai baht, was
worrisome, as it might make the Philippines' exports uncompetitive
against other countries whose currencies continued to fall.
</P>
<P>
He suggested the Central Bank intervene in the market and buy
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank governor Gabriel Singson turned down the idea,
saying the peso, which once fell by 76 percent from the original
level of 26.2 pesos to the dollar, has been undervalued.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
