<HEADLINE> Philippines to Borrow to Boost Foreign Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Monetary Board
has authorized the Central Bank to borrow one billion U.S. dollars
to boost its dwindling foreign exchange reserves, the local
newspaper Manila Bulletin reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Five international investment banks, including JP Morgan and
Merrill Lynch, have already offered a total of 3.8 billion U.S.
dollars to the Central Bank, bank officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
But the Monetary Board has decided to tap only one billion of
the sums, said the officials, adding that the excess amount would
be treated as "reserve funds" which can still be availed of if the
dollar reserves are seen not enough to counter future currency
speculations.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank prefers a direct loan from the banks rather
than a bond floatation due to difficulties in attracting investors
in the wake of the regional currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
The loans are expected to come in next month to boost the
country's gross international reserves (GIR) to 10 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The GIR, which consists of the Central Bank's gold holding,
foreign exchange, investments and the so-called special drawing
rights, has been tapped by monetary authorities to infuse dollars
in the currency market to fight speculative attacks on the peso.
</P>
<P>
From more than 12 billion dollars before the de facto peso
devaluation on July 11, 1997, the GIR fell to only about nine
billion at the start of 1998, due to futile efforts of the Central
Bank to defend the currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
