<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Promises Bigger Financial Aid for Yangtze River Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 14 (Xinhua) -- China's largest economic
center of Shanghai will provide bigger financial support for
economic growth in the Yangtze River region, according to a senior
financial official.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai will seek to promote economic growth in the area with
syndicated or special loans, said Wang Huaqing, deputy governor of
the Shanghai branch of the People's Bank of China (PBC), the
central bank.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that 20 percent of the loans granted by
the licensed overseas banks in Shanghai has been directed to areas
along the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Last year PBC Shanghai launched bill discounting in nine cities
in the Yangtze River Valley, which has greatly promoted economic
exchange between Shanghai and other areas in the Yangtze River
Valley.
</P>
<P>
While more national and regional banks and non-banking
financial institutions have set up subsidiaries in Shanghai, and
Shanghai in turn has also accelerated its pace to tap business
opportunities in areas along the Yangtze River and in cities in
other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Shanghai-headquartered Bank of Communications,
Shanghai Pudong Development Bank, Shenyin and Wangguo Securities
Co. Ltd and Haitong Securities Co. Ltd have set up branches in a
number of cities.
</P>
<P>
Capital export is a sign of Shanghai's amplifying power to the
economic belt in the Yangtze River Valley. Official statistics
show that lending to out-city clients through the Shanghai Fund
Center has totaled 261.6 billion yuan since the second half of
1991. Since 1994 more than 80 percent of the lending has gone to
clients in the Yangtze River Valley.
</P>
<P>
The capital market of Shanghai has also gained in importance in
aiding economic development in the Yangtze River Valley. Turnover
at the Shanghai securities market amounted to more than 1.8
trillion yuan in the first half of 1997 alone. More than 90
percent of the 59 companies listed on the Shanghai Stock Exchange
in the first six months of 1997 were from other provinces and
municipalities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
