<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Gets China's First Regional Banking Clearance System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 14 (Xinhua) -- A regional computer system to
clear transactions has been set up in Guangzhou, the capital of
South China's Guangdong Province, to help update capital
circulation and avoid financial risks.
</P>
<P>
The system is in use in only a few places like the U.S,
Switzerland, and Hong Kong, according to local bank officials.
</P>
<P>
The system connects local commercial banks with a national
satellite network of the People's Bank of China, the central
bank. Commercial banks can use electronic data to help settle
accounts with customers and the central bank within minutes.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the system had handled 330,000
transactions since March, 1997, valued at more than 90 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
All Guangzhou branches of the Agricultural Bank of China, the
Industrial and Commercial Bank of China, Bank of China, and
Communications Bank of China are connected to the network, and the
Guangzhou City Cooperative Bank is expected to join this "bankers'
club" this month.
</P>
<P>
Bank officials estimate that daily transactions will reach
three billion yuan when all local banks join this year.
</P>
<P>
Local enterprises will be able to increase earnings from bank
deposits because of the high efficiency of the system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
