<HEADLINE> China to Speed Up Construction of Highway, Port Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- China plans to build seven
major highway arteries by the end of this century, linking Beijing
with Zhuhai, Shenyang and Shanghai, and connecting Tongjiang with
Sanya, Lianyungang with Horgas, Shanghai with Chengdu, and
Chongqing with Beihai.
</P>
<P>
And in 1998, the country will add 2,370 km of new lines,
including 800 km of expressways and 540 km of Category-A and
Category-B highways for special use, Minister of Communications
Huang Zhendong said here today.
</P>
<P>
Huang said China's ports will add a handling capacity of 4.7
million tons this year, and nine deep-water berths will be built.
</P>
<P>
He said that as an effort to commemorate the 50th anniversary
of the founding of the People's Republic of China, the Ministry of
Communications will build ten key projects, such as the
Beijing-Luohe section of the Beijing-Zhuhai expressway, the
Jiangyin Yangtze highway bridge, and the harnessing project for
the Jiangsu part of the North-South Grand Canal.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that China's transport "bottleneck" is still
there, and transport conditions are expected to meet the demand of
national economic and social development in 2020, and by the
mid-21st century, the country will have a modern transportation
network.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of last year, the country's
highway mileage reached 1.21 million km, including 4,735 km of
expressways.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, China built 27,000 km of highways, including 1,313 km
of expressways and 3,300 km of Category-A and Category-B highways.
</P>
<P>
The country also accelerated construction of ports last year,
bringing the number of berths to 450.  
</P>
</TEXT>
