<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highway Transport Takes Lead in Market Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- A total of 11.4 billion people
traveled on highways in 1997, a rise of 2 percent over the
previous year, according to the latest statistics from the
Ministry of Communications.
</P>
<P>
Highways also carried 9.9 billion tons of cargo, up 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The growth was achieved against fierce market
competition. Statistics show that railways transported 917 million
people last year, down from 942 million in 1996, and the amount of
cargo delivered kept the same level of 1996 to stand at 1.62
billion tons.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, more travelers have turned to highway or air
transport from railway for faster or more comfortable service.
</P>
<P>
A report from the State Planning Commission said that the
demand of highway and railway transport will increase as a result
of national economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
The demand of passenger and cargo transport on highways will
increase by 5 and 4 percent, respectively, this year, and that of
passenger transport on railways will be up 2 to 4 percent, and
that of cargo transport on railways will maintain the same level.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the number of air travelers rose by 10.4
percent to reach 59 million last year. Waterways transported 220
million passengers, down 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Major ports handled nearly 1.3 billion tons of goods last year,
a rise of 1.6 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
