<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Coastal Provinces Most Competitive Economically </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 14 (Xinhua) -- The coastal areas of China have
become the most competitive in the country, according to the State
Statistics Bureau (SSB), which ranks Shanghai, Guangdong, Beijing,
Tianjin, Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Shandong, Fujian, Liaoning and Hainan
as the ten most competitive regions.
</P>
<P>
This is based on eight basic economic factors for economic
force, market openness, government efficiency, finances,
infrastructure, management, science and technology, and labor
force.
</P>
<P>
The competitiveness of the country's 30 province-level regions
reflects the rapid change in different areas since the reforms and
opening-up began in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Two decades ago, the top ten regional economies were Shanghai,
Beijing, Liaoning, Tianjin, Guangdong, Shandong, Jiangsu,
Heilongjiang, Hebei and Hubei, most of them inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The imbalance in economic competitiveness of coastal and inland
areas has become worse and the income gap between the two regions
has widened. Coastal and inland areas should therefore try to
build a reciprocal economic relationship to improve the
competitiveness of the whole nation, the SSB report says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980114.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Causes Crop Losses and Roads Destruction in Uruguay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Rains and floods caused by
the El Nino climatic phenomenon have prompted losses of over 30
million U.S. dollars in destruction of crops and roads in Uruguay,
authorities said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
As the summer comes in, continuous rains have pounded specially
the Northern territory and the coast, causing damage to crops,
cattle and infrastructure, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture, Livestock and Fishing Ministry reported that
15 to 20 percent of wheat and barley crops worth some 20 million
U.S. dollars have been lost.
</P>
<P>
It also said that damage to highways has amounted to 10 million
U.S. dollars so far.
</P>
<P>
Local weather experts have forecast three to four added
months of storms due to El Nino.
</P>
<P>
The Uruguayan government is setting up a package of measures to
lower the losses brought about by natural disasters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
