<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch FA Criticizes World Cup Ticket Allocation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch Football Association
Tuesday joined its Belgian counterpart in criticizing the ticket
allocation plan of the coming World Cup tournament.
</P>
<P>
Dutch Football Association spokesman Rob de Leede said in
Amsterdam: "We have written to FIFA saying we are not happy with
the situation. The demand is three to four times the size of our
ticket allocation."
</P>
<P>
World Cup organizers gave the Dutch association 5,800 tickets
for the country's opening match against Belgium in Paris'
80,000-seater Stade de France stadium.
</P>
<P>
Belgium was given 5,400 tickets for the same match though
Belgian Football Association officials said that they had been
overwhelmed with 120,000 requests for tickets for the June 13
match.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch are given 4,700 tickets for their match against South
Korea on June 20 in Marseille and 2,200 tickets for the match
against Mexico on June 23 in St. Etienne.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch association is selling its World Cup allocation
through the Orange Supporters Club which currently has 28,000
members.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of the 2.5 million World Cup tickets are
reportedly designated for French fans.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands and Belgium were drawn into the same group in
the first-phase of competition of the 32-team World Cup
tournament. In last year's qualifying tournament, the two teams
also played in the same group.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch won their games both at home and away, with scores at
3-1 and 3-0. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
