<HEADLINE> NZ Doctor Wants to Try HIV to Find Anti-AIDS Vaccine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 14 (Xinhua) -- A New Zealand doctor has
volunteered to inject himself with a modified strain of the HIV
virus as part of a research to find a cheap vaccine against AIDS.
</P>
<P>
A local press report said Wednesday Dr Charles Farthing has
told his mother Ngaire Farthing about his plan.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted his mother as saying: "I'm not happy about it
but I feel very confident that he knows that he's doing. I don't
think he'd do it if there was a major danger."
</P>
<P>
Farthing, 44, an internationally-known AIDS researcher and
director of the Hollywood-based AIDS Healthcare Foundation, has
asked other medical professionals to join him in injecting
themselves with a weakened form of the HIV virus as part of an
effort to find a cheap protective vaccine against AIDS, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
But he still needs permission from the American Food and Drug
Administration for the injections, and the permission could take
up to a year to come.  
</P>
