<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Falls as Asian Stock Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell against
the Japanese yen and German mark Tuesday as Asian stock markets
rebounded after Indonesia's president promised to take measures to
mend the country's troubled economy.
</P>
<P>
Stock markets across Asia rebounded, led by a 9.1 percent rise
in Indonesia's main stock index. The rally boosted the yen against
the dollar and the mark, forcing the U.S. currency lower.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was quoted at 131.72 yen, down from 132.69 late
Monday. It also settled at 1.8200 marks, down from 1.8211.
</P>
<P>
The new official report indicated that the U.S. inflation rate
of 1997 stood at 1.7 percent only, down from 3.3 percent in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also was hurt by fears of a possible interest rate
cut by the Federal Reserve, as well as concerns that international
central banks could join in an effort to sell dollars on the open
market to boost slumping Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday:
1.4781 Swiss francs, up from 1.4764; 6.0915 French francs, down
from 6.0969; 1,791 Italian lire, unchanged from 1,791; and 1.4349
Canadian dollars, up from 1.4341.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6348 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6215 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
