<HEADLINE> Afghan Cargo Plane with 90 People on Board Crashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (Xinhua)-- An Afghan cargo plane carrying
as many as 90 Afghan fighters slammed into a mountain Tuesday in
southwestern Pakistan, the Associated Press of Pakistan reported.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft apparently strayed off course because of bad
weather and hit a mountain near the city of Khojak, but there were
no immediate report about the death toll.
</P>
<P>
At least 90 people were on board, the APP reported. They were
all believed to be Afghan Taliban fighters from the Taliban
headquarters in southern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan cargo plane, a Russian-made aircraft refitted to
carry passengers, had tried to land in the western Afghan city of
Herat, 150 miles west of Kandahar but had to turn back because of
bad weather, the APP reported.
</P>
<P>
The pilot apparently was trying to return to Kandahar when he
strayed off course. The aircraft crossed into Pakistan and hit a
mountain near Khojak, north of the provincial capital of
Baluchistan. 
</P>
