<HEADLINE> Albright Challenges Congress on U.S. Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright today urged Congress to approve a host of
legislations on foreign policies ranging from paying the U.S.
debts to the United Nations and NATO's expansion.
</P>
<P>
In a year-end major foreign policy speech, Albright said one
of the legislative tests in 1998 for Congress is "whether we will
pay what we owe to the United Nations and the International
Monetary Fund."
</P>
<P>
"This matters because the United States cannot solve every
problem that affects us on our own, nor would we want to try,"
she noted.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers, she said, had created "a truly ridiculous" impasse
by refusing last year to repay U.S. debts to the United Nations
during a confrontation with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The victims of this act of legislative blackmail are the
American people," Albright said. "The best America is a leader,
not a debtor."
</P>
<P>
On Bosnia, Albright said that the evidence is growing that
peace will be sustained in the country only when the U.S. troops
stay.
</P>
<P>
"Quitting is not the American way," she said. "The mission in
Bosnia should determine the timetable, and not the other way
around."
</P>
<P>
"The NATO-led effort to build peace in Bosnia reflects the
importance of a second test for 1998, which is to gain the
Senate's agreement to the proposed enlargement of that alliance
(NATO)," she noted.
</P>
<P>
The speech before the Center for National Policy, a private
group, is in part reflective on her first year as the secretary of
state while also a direct appeal to the Republican-controlled
Congress, which has the final word on Bosnia and NATO.
</P>
<P>
The extension of U.S. peacekeeping operations and the
alliance's expansion to include Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic, three former Soviet allies require congressional
approval.
</P>
<P>
Both the moves by the administration are criticized in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
Some lawmakers are concerned about risk to U.S. troops if
ethnic conflict should break out again in the Balkans and whether
the United States has a vital security interest in the region.
</P>
<P>
The alliance's expansion plan also makes some congressman
worry about a new division in Europe between the alliance and
those outsiders including Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
