<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Seeks Concerted Action, but may also Act Alone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The White House said on
Tuesday that the United States would like to act in concert with
its allies in forcing Iraq to back down in its decision to bar an
American-led weapons inspection team, but would not rule out
unilateral action when needed.
</P>
<P>
"It is always better to act in concert with others when we can,
but there is never any reluctance to act alone if we must," White
House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton said on Monday that he expected the U.N.
Security Council would take "strong and appropriate" action if
Iraq enforces its decision on Tuesday to block the weapons
inspection team, headed by American Scott Ritter.
</P>
<P>
Iraq on Tuesday blocked the Ritter-led team from inspecting
weapons of mass destruction on the ground that he was spying for
the United States and it also complained that the composition of
the team was not fairly balanced as it was composed with nine
Americans, five Britains, one Russian and one Australian.
</P>
<P>
While exerting its effort to press its concerns over Iraq's
challenge on weapons inspections within the U.N. Security Council,
the United States is closely monitoring the situation in the Gulf
"day in and day out" in case there is any incident to be
occurring, McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also made
clear that Iraq must back down in its decision and let weapons
inspectors do their jobs.
</P>
<P>
"It is very important... that unconditional access by UNSCOM
(the U.N. Special Commission) must be the bottom line," she said
in a speech to the National Policy Forum think tank.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to be vigilant and determined and we do not
rule out any options," she said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has maintained 21 warships, including two
aircraft carriers, about 350 aircraft and 28,800 military
personnel in the Gulf region since last November when a weapons
inspection crisis erupted as a result of Iraq's decision to expel
American inspectors within the U.N. teams.
</P>
<P>
Bill Richardson, U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, raised
military threat anew following Iraq's latest challenge in weapons
inspections.
</P>
<P>
"I can tell you, patience is running out in a lot of Security
Council capitals. The Iraqis are really pushing this to the
brink," he told ABC's "Good Morning America" in an interview.
</P>
<P>
"It's very important that Saddam Hussein be constrained," he
said. "We have our forces in the Gulf, we have not ruled that
option out," he added.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen said in Kuala Lumpur,
malaysia, that the United States would continue to pursue
diplomatic initiatives until that option was exhausted. "We have
not reached that point yet." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
