<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Lifts Moratorium on Home Health Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Tuesday lift a moratorium put in place in September that barred
new home health care providers from entering the Federal Medical
insurance program -- Medicare.
</P>
<P>
In a statement Clinton said The Department of Health and Human
Services is removing the moratorium because those new tougher
regulations are in place to root out fraud and abuse in the home
health industry.
</P>
<P>
The FBI and federal prosecutors have been assigned to
investigate health care fraud across the board. Clinton said
convictions have gone up 240 percent and the federal government
has saved an estimated 20 billion dollars in fraudulent claims.
</P>
<P>
Home health care is one of the fastest growing expenditures in
Medicare, rising from 2.9 percent of all payments in 1990 to
nearly 9 percent now.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations require all home health agencies to secure
surety bonds of 50,000 dollars, or 15 percent of annual Medicare
payments received, whichever is greater. The regulations also
require that new home health providers have enough funds to
operate for at least three months before they start accepting
Medicare patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
