<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Jump Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 13 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks rose today,
led by the battered technology sector, after several Asian markets
began to rebound from a series of sharp slides over the past week.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 84.95 to 7,732.13,
trimming January's loss back toward 2 percent. It was Dow's best
performance in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Other indexes also posted sizable gains, with the rally
accelerating just before the closing bell.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where NYSE volume totaled 645.68
million shares as against 682.90 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 12.92 to 952.13, and
the NYSE composite index rose 6.14 to 497.75.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index jumped 34.04 points to 1,541.62, and
the American Stock Exchange composite index rose 9.47 to 655.88.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 7.56 to
418.44.
</P>
<P>
Stock markets across Asia also rebounded today, led by
Indonesia, where stocks rose 9.1 percent. Singapore's market
jumped 8 percent after seven days of steep losses and Malaysia's
climbed 5.5 percent. In Hong Kong, stocks rose 7.4 percent today
after tumbling to a three-year low on Monday.
</P>
<P>
There was little market reaction to a report showing that U.S.
consumer prices edged just 0.1 percent higher in December. The
small increase held inflation for all of 1997 to only 1.7 percent
-- about half the 3.3 percent increase of 1996 and the best
performance in 11 years.  
</P>
