<HEADLINE> White House Top Aide Bowles to Stay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Erskine Bowles said Tuesday
he would remain as White House chief of staff rather than return
to the business world.
</P>
<P>
Bowles announced his decision at a meeting Tuesday of the White
House senior staff, according to the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
In his year on the job, Bowles was reputed to be the driving
force behind President Bill Clinton's pursuit of a balanced-budget
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Making no secret of his desire to leave, Bowles had been edging
toward the door for months but was reportedly stopped by Clinton's
insistence that he stay.
</P>
<P>
Bowles said he would try to dissuade other senior staff from
leaving. "I think this team is functioning well," Bowles said.
"I'm going to do my best -- it's my job to try to keep as many of
them here as I can."
</P>
<P>
Bowles acknowledged that his change of heart was prompted in
part by the prospect of a balanced budget and the opportunity for
Clinton to be a more activist president.
</P>
<P>
He said Clinton's State of the Union would demonstrate the
administration is committed to investing in education, training,
early childhood programs, technology and infrastructure programs,
as well as developing global markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
