<HEADLINE> Jordan Delegation Leaves for US for More Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Jordanian
delegation left here today for the United States to seek help for
finding alternative oil source other than Iraq as well as more
U.S. aid.
</P>
<P>
Jordan will ask the U.S. to help it reduce dependence of oil
supply on Iraq, which has been the sole oil provider for the
kingdom for years, said Foreign Minister Fayez Tarawneh, who
headed the delegation.
</P>
<P>
An informed source here said the delegation either expects the
U.S. would pressure Saudi Arabia to sell Jordan oil at
below-market rates, or hopes Washington would give more money to
enable Jordan to pay for Saudi oil at regular prices.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, also including Minister of Planning Rima
Khalaf, still plans to secure U.S. aid to the kingdom in 1998,
which is estimated at 225 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In October 1997, the U.S. congress approved a sum of 225
million dollars in aid package to Jordan to be included in the
1998 fiscal budget.
</P>
<P>
Iraq agreed to renew a deal with Jordan to supply it with 4.8
million tonnes of oil and oil products at reduced prices in 1998
after a ranking Jordanian delegation visited Baghdad for
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh visited Saudi Arabia last month in an attempt to
persuade it to sell oil to Jordan at reduced prices.
</P>
<P>
Jordan received from the U.S. 120 million dollars in direct
economic aid and 30 million dollars in military assistance in
1997. 
</P>
