<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian MP Favors Restoring ties with US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian Majlis (parliament)
member Tuesday voiced his support for the resumption of the ties
between Iran and the United States, the official news agency IRNA
reported.
</P>
<P>
The improved relations of the two countries will serve the
interests of the two nations if the international standards and
mutual respect are observed, Majid Ansari was quoted as saying by
the news agency.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "Iran is willing to have relations with all
the states except the usurper regime of Gods (Israel)."
</P>
<P>
Referring to a proposal for a referendum on resuming
Iran-U.S. relations, Ansari said that if the referendum is held,
the result absolutely will be negative.
</P>
<P>
Since Iranian President Mohammad Khatami expressed readiness to
hold dialogues with the American people on December 14 last year,
most participants of a hot debate on the media over the relations
between Tehran and Washington have opposed rapprochement with the
U.S.
</P>
<P>
Many Iranian officials have even rejected the referendum
proposal, maintaining that the Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei is the top authority to decide whether to start talks and
resume relations with the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Ansari, the Iranian MP, also criticized the media, the state
television in particular, for "an inappropriate reflection of
President Khatami's interview with CNN."
</P>
<P>
In his interview with the American Cable News Network on
Thursday, the Iranian President Mohammad Khatami said that Iran
"feels no need to have diplomatic ties with the U.S." since
Washington does not change its policies towards Iran.
</P>
<P>
But he called for cultural dialogues between the Iranians and
the Americans to pave the way for a "better future for the two
nations and countries."
</P>
<P>
Ansari blamed the television for not raising the positive
aspects of the interview and failing to provide the public with
the political analysis of the statements made by Khatami.
</P>
<P>
It is the second time in a week that Iran's senior political
and religious figures attacked the country's media for "prejudice
against the president."
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, a Friday prayer leader in Isfahan in central Iran
Ayatollah Jalaloddin Taheri lashed out at the country's Radio and
Television Organization for its prejudice against Khatami. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
