<HEADLINE> TRC to Seek Court Ruling Over Amnesty to ANC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC) today announced that it will seek
a ruling from the High Court on the validity of a blanket amnesty
granted to 37 African National Congress (ANC) leaders.
</P>
<P>
"We shall, as a matter of urgency, approach the High Court to
seek a declaratory order to ascertain whether or not the decision
made by the Amnesty Committee (of the TRC) conformed with our
governing act," TRC Chairman Desmond Tutu said today in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The committee granted a blanket amnesty to 37 ANC leaders,
including Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, late last year,
triggering controversy among political parties.
</P>
<P>
White-based opposition parties like the National Party (NP)
criticized the TRC of double standard in its handling of the
cases of ANC leaders and former NP leader and state president P.
W. Botha, who has been prosecuted for refusing to appear before
the TRC.
</P>
<P>
Tutu made the announcement after a meeting of the commission
on Robben Island off Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
Tutu said his commission came to the unanimous decision after
careful consideration of the matter and with close discussions
with the Amnesty Committee, several members of which have been
present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Tutu also reaffirmed the commission's "full confidence" in the
Amnesty Committee and its operation.
</P>
<P>
The committee supported this course of action and both the
commission and the committee would abide by the court's decision,
Tutu said.
</P>
<P>
Both the ruling ANC and the NP welcomed the TRC decision to
refer the issue to the High Court.
</P>
<P>
ANC spokesman Ronnie Mamoepa said: "We hope that the courts
will lay the matter to rest once and for all, particularly in the
light of concerted efforts from certain political quarters to
undermine the integrity of the TRC and thereby bring the entire
truth and reconciliation process into disrepute."
</P>
<P>
He also promised that the ANC will respect the ruling of the
court, whatever it will be.
</P>
<P>
NP leader Marthinus van Schalkwyk said his party welcomed the
move of the TRC and that his party believEed that the granting of
the amnesty to ANC leaders was illegal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
