<HEADLINE> Carrier Independence to Replace Nimitz in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. aircraft carrier
Independence will replace the Nimitz, which has been deployed in
the Persian Gulf since last October, the Pentagon said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Independence, which is now close to Japan, will join the
George Washington, the other carrier in the Gulf region, but the
deployment order has not been signed out, Pentagon spokesman
Mike Doubleday said. "Soon as that happens I'd be glad to let
everybody know," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Doubleday said the United States had 21 warships, about 350
aircraft and 28,800 military personnel in the region. "We will
continue to maintain that force as long as needed," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has maintained such mighty military force
since last November when a crisis erupted over U.N. weapons
inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A new confrontation took place on Monday when Iraq decided to
bar a U.N. weapons inspection team headed by an American whom
Iraq branded as a spy from carrying its work of dismantling arms
of mass destruction. Washington said it would act in concert
with its allies within the U.N. Security Council, but would not
rule out the use of military force to punish Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
