<HEADLINE> EU Presidency Issues Statement on Algeria Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Britain, the current European
Union (EU) president, said here today that the EU would go ahead
with the planned EU delegation as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said in a statement issued
this evening: "We have agreed today with our EU partners that we
should propose to the Algerian government that a Troika of senior
officials should visit Algeria at the earliest opportunity."
</P>
<P>
The so-called Troika delegation includes the current, the
immediate past and the next EU presidency state.
</P>
<P>
"We have also agreed that the objective of the Troika mission
will be to convey to the Algerian government the public opinion
felt in Europe at the massacres," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the other objective of the EU mission is to
"explore with them what can be done to end the violence, and what
the EU can do."
</P>
<P>
"We are now contacting the Algerian government to discuss the
timing and program for the proposed visit, with a view to the
Troika reporting back to the General Affairs on January 26," Cook
added.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some 1,000 Algerian civilians have been
killed by some unidentified armed guerillas since the beginning of
the holy Moslem month of Ramandan in late December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
