<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Inspector to Begin Talks in Baghdad on Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 13 (Xinhua) -- U.N. chief weapons
inspector in Iraq Richard Butler said here today that he will go
to Baghdad over the weekend and begin talks with Iraqi officials
to find solutions to the latest clash between the United Nations
and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Butler, who has briefed U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and
Security Council on what happened to U.N. inspection team in Iraq,
told reporters that he hoped that Iraq will change its mind and
allow the inspection to go on.
</P>
<P>
Issues on the agenda of his talks with Iraq remain those of
access to presidential and sovereign sites which Iraq disallows
the U.N. team to inspect, Butler said.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad's insistence on seeking to remove from the team certain
inspectors on the basis of nationality is not acceptable, he said.
</P>
<P>
The team headed by Scott Ritter and formed on Tuesday comprises
of 31 members from 12 nations, Butler said.
</P>
<P>
It "represents multiplicity of nations" and its members are
"all inspectors" and "all of the relevant disciplines, drawn from
nuclear, missile, chemical, biological and export/import...", he
went on.
</P>
<P>
Dismissing Iraq's charge that Ritter is an American spy, Butler
said Iraq is waging an "unrespectable campaign" against a
"perfectly competent individual" who is "a professional arms
control inspector".
</P>
<P>
Butler put Ritter as a man previously with the functions
"that were to do with the verification of the Intermediate
Nuclear Force Treaty between the United States and former Soviet
Union".
</P>
<P>
Iraq on Monday said it would bar the Ritter's team from
operating on the ground that it was dominated by American and
British members. It said the suspension would stand until the team
has a balanced composition.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council is meeting today on the Iraqi issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
